hardCodedText: Mavis Haywood was born in Colon, Panama, in 1944 and grew up as one of six siblings. After graduating from secondary school, she attended a trade school where she trained to be a seamstress. She met her husband Wilfred Haywood and married in 1968. Wilfred immigrated to the U.S. and the couple were reunited in New York City in 1969. Wilfred opened a dry cleaning business in Flatbush, Brooklyn, while Mavis stayed home to raise their three sons. Finances were tight at times but the Haywoods supported all three children throughout high school and college. Mavis enjoyed baking and was known for her signature Panamanian fruit cake. She supported over 20 different charities including the American Diabetes Association, Cheyenne River Indian Outreach and Shriners Hospitals for Children. Mavis worked as a home health aide in the 1990s, retiring in 2001. She later cared for her husband, Wilfred, after he was diagnosed with Lewy body dementia. Mavis fell ill with COVID-19 in April 2020 while at home in Brooklyn. She was hospitalized at Maimonides Medical Center and died on April 12, 2020, at the age of 75. A few weeks later, Wilfred developed pneumonia due to COVID-19. He died on May 25, 2020 at the age of 82. They were laid to rest next to each other at Rosehill Cemetery in New Jersey. The Haywoods are survived by their sons Wilfred, Kareem and Daniel and one grandson, Emmanuel.
hardCodedPullquote: She was a giving person.
pullquoteSource: Wilfred Haywood Jr., Mavis Haywood’s son

hardCodedText: Shortly after Jeffrey Paley’s death, his wife Dr. Valerie Paley found a scrap of paper in a tray where he kept spare change. On it, he had scribbled down a quote by Ralph Waldo Emerson: “To know even one life has breathed easier because you have lived, this is to have succeeded." Jeffrey lived by these words. He was born in Chicago, Illinois, on Aug. 11, 1938, and adopted by William S. Paley, the founder and chairman of CBS Inc., and Dorothy (Hart) Hearst. He was raised on the Upper East Side and graduated from Harvard University in 1960. Jeffrey pursued three separate careers. He first worked as a journalist, reporting for The International Herald Tribune in Paris, where he eventually wrote a syndicated column about world affairs and the economy. In the early 1970s, he co-founded the Paley and Lowe Gallery in SoHo, which featured the work of young artists. His third and final career was as an independent private investor in the stock market. Jeffrey and Valerie met while living in the same apartment building in Greenwich Village. The couple married in 1989 and moved to the Upper East Side where they raised their son Austin and daughter Elianne. Jeffrey read the news voraciously — a passion that he maintained until his death. When he didn’t have to be in the city, he spent time with his family on Nantucket, where his ashes are buried. “In spite of his many accomplishments throughout his life, in the end he was most passionate about his family and kids,” Valerie said. He loved to read and play tennis, had a booming laugh and didn’t suffer fools, she added. Jeffrey died on Feb. 27, 2021, at NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital/Weill Cornell Medical Center at the age of 82.
hardCodedPullquote: He was his own man. He was adopted into great privilege and certainly had many wonderful opportunities, but he wasn’t afraid to do things the hard way. He was passionate, intellectual, discerning, and a larger than life human being.
pullquoteSource: Dr. Valerie Paley, Jeffrey Paley’s wife
author: Madeline Muldoon

hardCodedText: At the age of 17, Christos Arsenis moved from Greece to New York City where he worked in the restaurant business for the next 45 years. He co-owned and operated Broadway Diner on the Upper West Side for more than 41 years. Christos spent most of his time at the diner, which has appeared in many movies over the years, including “Meet Joe Black,” said his daughter, Dora Arsenis. In the spring of 2020, Christos was too sick to work and stayed home for nine days before he was hospitalized. He endured 33 days in the ICU before the doctors told his family to come and say goodbye, Dora said. Christos died on May 6, 2020, at Mount Sinai Queens at the age of 74.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a loving father, husband and carried a heart of gold. His family came first. He worked nonstop so he can give us a better future. He will truly be missed.
author: Paige Gorman

hardCodedText: Rev. Lynette Woodland Love was born in 1939 in Washington D.C. She moved to New York City in 1954 as a teenager. She met and married Harold Woodland and moved to Queens and had three children: Phyllis, Sherrie and Harold Jr. After many years as a stay-at-home mom, Lynette started a career as a telephone operator at the New York Telephone company, where she was elected as a union representative. After 24 years at the company, she retired. Lynnette later remarried and, in 1998, she was ordained at New Life Missionary Baptist Church in Queens and joined New Jerusalem Baptist Church as a reverend. She was gracious, outspoken and demonstrated strength with every hardship she faced, said her daughter Sherrie Woodland. Whenever she was asked how she was doing or if she needed anything, she’d say: “I need money and a man.” Lynette died on June 2, 2021, at Calvary Hospital in The Bronx at the age of 82. She is survived by her three children, Phyllis, Sherrie and Harold Jr., five grandchildren and four nieces and nephews.
hardCodedPullquote: She was so incredibly strong and very, very giving. She instilled both of those traits in her children, most definitely.
pullquoteSource: Sherrie Woodland, Rev. Lynette Woodland Love’s daughter
author: Madeline Muldoon

hardCodedText: Monsignor John Ruvo was born in 1927 in Potenza, Italy. He was the oldest of four children and moved to The Bronx when he was six years old. The Ruvo children had a simple but happy childhood in an Italian neighborhood. “We didn’t have much, but we enjoyed what we had. We enjoyed the family,” Marie said. After graduating from P.S. 45 in The Bronx and Cathedral College, a preparatory seminary, John joined St. Joseph’s Seminary. He was ordained at St. Patrick’s Cathedral in 1954 and served as a priest for more than six decades. John served as pastor at Our Lady of Mount Carmel in The Bronx from 1984 to 2008, then as senior priest at St. Joseph in New Rochelle until his retirement when he moved to the Edward Cardinal Egan Pavilion in Riverdale. He died on April 26, 2020, at the ​​Edward Cardinal Egan Pavilion, at the age of 93.
hardCodedPullquote: John was a people person and a family person. He was a very good priest, and a very good brother. He took care of the rest of us.
pullquoteSource: Marie Ruvo, Monsignor John Ruvo’s sister
author: Madeline Muldoon
additionalNotes: His title is "Monsignor or Msgr."

Theron O. Worth, Jr. of Manhattan died, with his family by his side, on January 19, 2021 at New York Presbyterian Hospital. Cause of death was complications of Covid-19. 
Theron Oscar Worth, Jr. hailed from a long line of English whaling captains, the family having arrived in Nantucket in the 1640's. Eventually, Toby's antecedents settled in Bridgehampton, NY, where Toby's grandfather and father are buried. There, Toby learned the game of tennis from his father, and a deep love of sailing and the Ocean, whose bounty provided so much to his ancestors. 

Toby is survived by his wife of 60 years, Merwin Braxton, his six children and 13 grandchildren, and his younger sister, Courtia Worth of Tillson, NY, and predeceased by his sister Edwina Worth Hatch of Bridgehampton, NY.

hardCodedText: Manh Nguyen was born and raised in Vietnam. He met his wife Bay Dang in 1960. Together, they immigrated to the U.S. to find work, settling in The Bronx in 1995. The couple had four children. Nguyen worked in construction and as a factory worker. His biggest accomplishment was transitioning to the U.S. and providing for his family, said his daughter, Tran Castore. He spent most of his time with his family, going to the park with his wife and children. Castore remembers him for being kind and patient with everyone around him. Nguyen died on March 18, 2021, at Montefiore Hospital in The Bronx at the age of 86.

hardCodedText: Kenneth Earl Green Jr., affectionately known as "Wayne," was born to Dolores and Kenneth Green Sr. in Jamaica in 1966. Green grew up in Kingston, Jamaica where he formed a close-knit relationship with his cousins. After losing a close friend at a young age, Green moved to New York City to study at Queens College and the University of Bridgeport. While in the city, he met Roxanne Hobbs, who became his wife and mother to their twin boys Isaiah and Isaac. Green operated a successful chiropractic office.“Wayne would never hesitate to share a laugh, to lend an ear, a dollar, a hug — whatever would lighten the loads of his beloved family and friends,” said his cousin Kelli Connolly. Green died on April 18, 2020, at NewYork-Presbyterian Brooklyn Methodist Hospital at the age of 53.
hardCodedPullquote: He was the glue that held the family together.

hardCodedText: Maureen Portia Robinson-Morgan’s father died when she was 5 years old. She was raised by her mother in Harlem, who instilled a love of music and the church in her children. Maureen “had a voice like Aretha Franklin,” said her sister Selina Robinson. “She could hear four-part harmony in her head.” Maureen, Selina and their brother Eugene sang in church choirs across the city and eventually formed their own  group called The Selmagene Singers. “They were booked everywhere,” said her best friend Gloria Whittaker-Driver. Maureen also sang background for artists such as Pastor Shirley Cesar and Evelyn Champagne King. She graduated from Marymount Manhattan College with a degree in Biology, intending to pursue a career in medicine. After working briefly at the OB-GYN Clinic at Harlem Hospital, her passion for music called and she left to become the choir director at White Rock Baptist Church in Harlem, the church that she grew up attending. Over the years, many accomplished singers and songwriters were part of the choir, including Valerie Simpson, Nicholas Ashford and Freddie Jackson. Maureen directed choirs across the city for the rest of her life. She met her husband Robert Morgan Jr. at White Rock Baptist Church. Freddie Jackson sang at their wedding. The couple had two daughters Rachelle Morgan-Wright and Stacey Morgan. Maureen was known for her effortless sense of humor, sweet disposition and ability to make friends wherever she went, said Whittaker-Driver. Maureen died on April 26, 2020, at home in The Bronx. She was 66 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: Maureen loved helping people. She was my hero because she had so much faith. She would just sit listening as young people poured out their problems, and would advise them. And if they needed a place to stay? Her door was always open for them to come and have a safe haven.
author: Madeline Muldoon

hardCodedText: Rodolfo Perez Acevedo was born in Panama and raised in Nicaragua. At the age of 10, he moved to Corona, Queens, with his parents and his brother, James. When he arrived, Acevedo spoke very little English. He later graduated from P.S. 73 and joined the Army at the age of 18. Acevedo served as a paratrooper in the 82nd Airborne Division for nearly 20 years. He then worked as a custodian for the U.S. Postal Service, retiring in 2003. Acevedo never married or had children but he dedicated much of his time to caring for his family, said his great-niece Samantha Silva. After his brother died in 1989, Acevedo stepped in as a father-figure and raised his nieces and nephews as if they were his own children, Silva said. He took them on trips to the park and to the zoo; taught them how to tie their shoes and ride bikes. Acevedo enjoyed collecting vinyl records, building model airplanes from his days as a paratrooper and watching classic movies. Acevedo died on April 1, 2020, at home. He was 74.
hardCodedPullquote: Rudy was a true patriot, in every sense of the word.
pullquoteSource: Samantha Silva, Rodolfo Perez Acevedo’s great-niece

hardCodedText: Jack Smith’s passion, second to his family, was cars, said his daughter Jill Graney. He loved sports cars and owned them throughout his life. A month before he died, Jack fulfilled his dream of owning a Mercedes sports car. Born into a family of Polish immigrants in Toronto, Canada, Jack moved to Brooklyn at a young age, where he eventually met his wife Irene and raised his two daughters, Jill and Stacey. He was an accountant and spent his free time working on his car, building things out of wood and rooting for the Mets and Jets. Once his daughters were grown up, he and Irene moved to Lincroft, New Jersey, for a brief period. New Yorkers at heart, they soon moved back to the city and settled in Manhattan where Jack spent the last 18 years of his life. Jill said he was a quiet, soft-spoken man who loved being around friends and family, but never needed to be the center of attention. Jack was committed to helping others. After his retirement, he spent 16 years volunteering for Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center. In 2010, he was given the Hospital Auxilian and Volunteer Achievement Award and was honored at a lunchtime ceremony at the Waldorf Astoria Hotel. Jill describes how her dad loved spending time with his daughters, their husbands and his five granddaughters, who were his proudest accomplishment. Jack died on April 16, 2020, at NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital at the age of 86. Shortly after he passed, his granddaughter Bo had a baby boy – the first boy in the family – who she named “Dylan Jack” after her grandfather.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a good guy, and everybody knew he was. He never said a bad word, and had a lot of friends who all had nice things to say about him.
author: Madeline Muldoon
additionalNotes: Survived by his wife Irene, his daughters Jill and Stacey, and his five granddaughters

hardCodedText: Carlton Naughton Sr. was born in Mount Vernon, New York. After playing football for Drake University in Iowa, Naughton moved back to New York where he worked at Mount Vernon High School for almost 40 years. Naughton was a special education teacher and coached football, girls’ basketball and girls’ track teams. He also served as a basketball referee. Naughton’s students loved and admired him, nicknaming him “Big O” or “Big Naught.” In 2015, he was inducted into the Westchester Hall of Fame for football. At 6-foot-4, Naughton was a huge presence, said his fiancée Gladys Mitchell. When the two met at the Greater Centennial A.M.E. Zion Church, Naughton already had five children. Mitchell’s three daughters called him their “bonus” dad as he treated them just as if they were his own. In his spare time, Naughton loved listening to music, especially Tupac and DMX. He also loved listening to Mitchell sing and said he was her number one fan. Naughton enjoyed singing in church and was part of the men’s choir. He also loved dancing and watching TV shows like “In the Heat of the Night” or “Superman.” Naughton died Feb. 24, 2021, at the age of 63. He is survived by his fiancée Gladys Mitchell, five children, Mitchell’s three daughters, 12 grandchildren and six siblings.
hardCodedPullquote: He was such a peacemaker, a gentle giant.
pullquoteSource: Gladys Mitchell, Carlton Naughton Sr.’s fiancée

hardCodedText: Ramon Furcal was born in Santiago de los Caballeros in the Dominican Republic in 1966. At the age of 16, Furcal immigrated to the United States with his mother and settled in Washington Heights in Manhattan in an apartment in which he would live for the rest of his life. Furcal worked in construction, hiring himself out as a painter, carpenter and general contractor. His true passion, said his cousin Katira Cepeda, was “to live life to the fullest.” Furcal enjoyed traveling, visiting family and friends, spending time by the ocean, fishing and cooking. He spent several months a year in the Dominican Republic, where his mother now lives part-time and in Florida where his aunt, Cepeda’s mother, currently lives. When he was admitted to the hospital with COVID-19, it took Furcal’s family two days to locate him, said Cepeda, because he did not have access to his cell phone. Furcal remained hospitalized for over 30 days, during which time his family was unable to visit. His mother, who had traveled to New York from the Dominican Republic, was only able to see her son after he died, Cepeda added. Furcal died May 19, 2020, at NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital in Washington Heights. He is survived by his mother, father and son, as well as a large extended family.
hardCodedPullquote: Ramon was always ready for any new adventure. His motto was to live life without any cares or any concerns about what others might think. Living, loving and laughing describes everything he embodied and more. If only we had had more time together.
author: Talia Bloch
additionalNotes: Contact was cousin, Katira Cepeda.

hardCodedText: Annie Ruth Johnson was born in 1937 in Wilson, North Carolina — the youngest of 18 children. Johnson moved to New York City to finish her education. A matriarch in her family, church and community, she was “a small woman with a big presence,” said her granddaughter, Shardi White. Johnson was a deacon at Bethany Baptist Church in Harlem. She took pride in her role in the community and was one of a few female role models in the church. The church community was her extended family where she was known as “Mom,” especially to members whose parents had died. As part of her role, Johnson attended seminary school to become a chaplain, learning to pray with people as their family and friends were dying. Each week, Johnson looked forward to her Bible study group and spending time with family and friends. She called loved ones to check in each day and her home was a gathering place for holidays and special occasions with her children, grandchildren, nieces and nephews. Johnson died on April 23, 2020, at Mount Sinai Hospital. She was 82.
hardCodedPullquote: She was the person who was there for everybody, and she never wanted to stop doing things. I admire her for that.
pullquoteSource: Shardi White, Annie Ruth Johnson’s granddaughter
author: Colleen McBride

hardCodedText: Diego Agron was born in Puerto Rico in 1959, one one of six siblings raised by a single mother in a poor neighborhood. He moved to New York City at 18, searching for new opportunities. He started working immediately, picking strawberries, coffee and beans in the surrounding farmland. In New York, Agron reunited with his two older brothers and was later joined by his mother and younger siblings. In 1994, he met Elizabeth Cubero and quickly became a father figure to her two children, Jeffrey and Anthony. They later married and enjoyed spending time together, watching movies and taking trips. Agron later worked as a butcher. He was proud of the work he’d done to support his family and hoped to retire to Florida. He contracted COVID-19 in April 2020 and was hospitalized after losing consciousness. He died later that day on April 19, 2020, at NYU Langone Hospital in Brooklyn. He was 60 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: He was such a teddy bear. We did everything together — he was the rock of the family and such a humble person, my children and I were so blessed to have him in our lives. He will be dearly missed.
author: Colleen McBride

hardCodedText: Angie Rosa grew up in Newark, New Jersey, and was the youngest of seven children. She married at the age of 20 and moved to New York City. Angie later became a single mom, raising four children, all of whom attended college. In her mid-40s, she enrolled in an education and training program that taught clerical skills. Angie went on to work as receptionist and secretary at The New York Observer, retiring at the age of 64. Her family described her as a generous, loving mother and a strong woman. In 2017, Angie suffered a heart attack and moved to a nursing home in Queens. After a year, she returned to her apartment.  Although she relied on an oxygen machine, Angie stayed active by cooking, shopping with her daughter and socializing with family and friends. She died March 28, 2020, at Wyckoff Heights Medical Center at the age of 87. She is survived by four children, four grandchildren and her cat, Ginger, who has since been adopted by her oldest daughter, Barbara.
hardCodedPullquote: My mother was very generous and kind-hearted. If you needed it, she had it. If she only had part of it, she shared it with you. Missing you everyday, Mom.

hardCodedText: Born and raised in San Pedro de Marcorís, Dominican Republic, Cesar Augusto Morales Sr. was the “man of the house” supporting his family from a young age, said his daughter, Annais Morales. Before turning five, he helped his single mother deliver milk and sell newspapers, Annais said. Cesar fought in the Dominican Civil War of 1965 alongside the Constitutionalists who were attempting to reinstate former President Juan Bosch who had been overthrown by a military coup. After a new government took power, Cesar endured several attempts on his life from political enemies, his family said, and fled to the U.S. in 1967. He settled in East Harlem where he worked as a handyman and carpenter. Cesar later moved to The Bronx and lived there for 50 years. Cesar had 10 children, 24 grandchildren and 12 great-grandchildren. He instilled a “go-getter” attitude in his children, Annais said. One memorable lesson: When she turned 18, Annais asked her father for a cell phone and he said no. Although he could have bought it for her, his refusal taught her the value of a hard-earned dollar. “It forced me to go out and get a job...and I got myself a nice little cell phone,” she said. Even as a senior citizen on a fixed income, Cesar donated to charities like The Wounded Warriors Project and the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. Cesar loved traveling to the Dominican Republic to be with family and friends. “He was always out and about … it’s like I had a 25-year-old for a dad,” Annais said. He died April 15, 2020, at Lincoln Hospital at the age of 89.
hardCodedPullquote: He was just so full of life, so funny, so charming, so generous and so smart.
pullquoteSource: Annais Morales, Cesar Augusto Morales Sr.'s daughter

hardCodedText: Mateo Rivera was born in 1948 in Comerio, Puerto Rico. He was one of ten siblings. Mateo moved to The Bronx in 1967 at the age of 18 where he met and married his wife, Aurora Rivera, who goes by Doris. Mateo became a chef and later worked in a nursing home. He was very sociable and always happy, said his wife. Mateo enjoyed spending time with his siblings and friends. At family gatherings, he would dance the night away, she said. The couple visited Atlantic City many times together. If they were upset at each other or lost a bet, they always left with smiles on their faces. Mateo moved to an assisted living facility in The Bronx in 2015. There he met one of his best friends, Rosa Triguero, said his wife. Triguero had lost her eyesight and was unable to care for herself but Mateo always made sure to help however he could. After the pandemic started, he continued to go to her room to make sure she was eating. Mateo died on April 9, 2020, at Jacobi Medical Center at the age of 71. Triguero died four days later. Mateo is survived by his wife; two children, Melissa Peña and Matthew Rivera; three grandchildren, Destiny Rivera, Amaya Rivera and Xavier Peña and his great-granddaughter, Helane Peña.

hardCodedText: Alexander Tabarovsky was born in Kiev in the former Soviet Union in 1928, the eldest of three brothers. His early life was overshadowed by World War II, with his Jewish family attempting to flee eastward to avoid the Nazi army. One of their initial attempts was by ferry. However, Tabarovsky was finishing a soccer game with his friends, causing him and his family to miss the ferry. This saved their life, as the boat sank, killing everyone on board. His family eventually managed to flee to safety in Siberia. His love of sports had saved his life, and while Tabarovskywas interested in a variety of sports, he created a career out of one in particular: table tennis. Tabarovsky served as a table tennis coach for decades, coaching the Soviet Union’s women’s table tennis champion in 1969, Svetlana Grinberg. Despite his success in the Soviet Union, mounting antisemitism forced him to flee, his family said. In the 1980s, Tabarovsky immigrated to the U.S., reuniting with his brother who had moved to New York City years earlier. He settled in Brighton Beach and quickly became a fixture in the Brooklyn community, living in the same two buildings for decades. Tabarovsky contracted COVID-19 in early May 2020 and was hospitalized. He died May 18, 2020, a day after his wife’s birthday. He is survived by his wife, two children, three grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: He was the glue that held our family together.

hardCodedText: When José “Pepe” Jaramillo was growing up in the city of Guayaquil, Ecuador, he used to point to airplanes in the sky and tell his family: “I’m going to be on that plane one day.” He saved his money and, by 1968, at the age of 18, had enough to make his way to Jackson Heights, Queens where he lived with his godmother, Maria. José found a job as a plumber and settled into life in New York. “He was known as the cool guy. He was the ‘Fonzie’ … ‘El Puma,’” said his daughter Jennifer Jaramillo. José caught the attention of an Ecuadorian woman named Ana who had come to the United States from Guayaquil to study to become a doctor. The two married in 1971 and, a year later, had the first of five children. He was a strict father, said Jennifer, “but he would listen and he would always let us speak.” José was also a gentleman and a good dresser, his family said. In the spring of 2020, family members started to fall ill with COVID-19, including José. He was admitted to NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital Queens and later transferred to Columbia University Irving Medical Center, where he died on June 1, 2020. He was 69 years old.

hardCodedText: Michael Xavier O’Connor was born and was raised in Bronxville, in Westchester County. He graduated from Bridgewater State University in Massachusetts with a degree in theater and history. In 1993, O’Connor returned to New York to focus on his acting career. He was an active member of several performance unions, including SAG-AFTRA, AEA and IATSE. O’Connor was an animal rights activist and loved his cat, Lucy, his friends said. “Michael was an inspiration to everyone he met with his unconditional inclusiveness,” said Carol-Marie Labozzetta, his friend. O’Connor was constantly working towards achieving the “best version” of himself, she said, and he loved learning, reading and traveling. Labozzetta fondly recalled traveling to Ireland together, where O’Connor explored his heritage. O’Connor was also a lifelong fan of the New York Yankees. hardCodedText: James H. Weber was a man of letters and learning. Known as “Shamus” to his family and friends, he attended Yale in the 1960s, where he studied English, art history and classical languages. He went on to spend the next 50 years of his life teaching — most of those years at Westover School. “Shamus was a beloved teacher to multiple generations," said Liz Van Hoose, a former student. “Having himself studied with W.H. Auden, he imbued us with the force of poetry. His favorite Auden quatrain, from ‘The Fall of Rome,’ fortifies me still in times of overwhelming hardship: Altogether elsewhere, vast / Herds of reindeer move across / Miles and miles of golden moss, / Silently and very fast.” A passionate and skilled sailor, he once crewed for the accomplished Harry C. “Buddy” Melges. But Shamus’s lifelong passion was his wife, Cynthia Weber, to whom he first proposed marriage at the Lincoln Park Zoo in Chicago in 1951 when they were children growing up together. Eleven years and two proposals later, Cynthia said yes. They were married for 53 years. He died April 1, 2020, at the Cobble Hill Health Center, a nursing home in Brooklyn. Shamus is survived by his wife, Cynthia; two sons, Harley Weber and Clark Weber; three grandchildren; and an Airedale terrier named Zeno.

hardCodedText: Carmen Perez Abreu was born to a large family in Santiago, in the Dominican Republic, in 1931. After being widowed, she left an abusive second marriage and raised her daughter, Carmen Delia, as a single mother, her family said. In 1967, she became the first in her family to move to the United States. Abreu arrived in New York City in the winter with a few dollars and a pair of kitten heels, according to her granddaughter, Ramona Ferreyra. She became a seamstress and eventually retired to Mitchel Houses in the Bronx, where she enjoyed playing dominoes and bingo with friends. Ferreyra described her as a “comedian” and “reluctant activist.” She died Dec. 29, 2020, from liver failure after contracting COVID-19 at the age of 89. She is survived by her daughter, four grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.

hardCodedText: Julius Adorno Jr. was born in 1931 in The Bronx where he would spend the next 74 years. He grew up with two brothers. Adorno was a tall man often confused for a professional football player, and was nicknamed “Tiny” for its irony, said his son Jefferey. Adorno attended Samuel Gompers High School before joining the military in the 1950s. He served in the Korean War and played basketball and baseball for the U.S. Marines. He later worked in the air conditioning and refrigeration business, starting as a truck driver before he was promoted to management at the warehouse. Adorno often ran into his many friends who would yell out: “Hey, Tiny!” Adorno encouraged his two sons and their friends to pursue the arts and music, supporting their band gigs in the tri-state area by providing equipment and transportation. “This was just his natural way of being —  to help people, not part of a grander plan,” said his son Jefferey. Adorno died on April 3, 2020, at Montefiore New Rochelle Hospital at the age of 88.
hardCodedPullquote: My father-in-law was this family man and all the women loved him. He was a gentle giant, he was a gentleman, almost like a James Bond: calm, cool and collected. So many people said he was a second father, with a real true heart.
pullquoteSource: Louise Adorno, Julius Adorno Jr.’s daughter-in-law

hardCodedText: Coralia Galvez emigrated from Guatemala in 1983 at the age of 32. She moved to Harlem where she and her husband, Jorge Galvez, raised their daughters: Evelyn, Karla, Ingrid and the late Karen Galvez. Coralia owned Cory’s Beauty Salon on Third Avenue in Manhattan. On Sundays, if it was sunny, she would take her daughters to Riverside Park or Heschel Park for barbecues. Coralia had the ability to turn anything into a good time, said Kayla and Ingrid, and had a penchant for “lightening the mood.” “Mama Cory” routinely cooked for her family, including a favored dish: chicken with cream. She was also proud of her grandchildren, her family said: Donovan, Stephen, Coryanne, Abigail, Emma, Karina, Luke, Thomas, Layla, Andrew and Robert. Coralia spent her final years travelling the world with her husband. She died at Lenox Hill Hospital on Feb. 14, 2021, at the age of 69.

hardCodedText: Judy Sampson Avilez was born in Trinidad and Tobago in 1961 and immigrated to New York in 1994. As a single mom, Avilez often worked three or four jobs at a time. She embraced “the unpredictabilities of the world,” said her son Brian Babusingh, and believed in going forward “no matter what.” She often told her son: “Just have faith in God, and hold love in your heart. Keep on going that way, and you will be alright.” Avilez was a wise and understanding person, Babusingh added. She “would listen to you and just tell you what she thinks,” he said, “And most of the time, people would end up agreeing with her. They would say, ‘Yeah, Judy, actually, you’re right.’” She was a “joker” and part of “the generation who liked to make provocative jokes,” he added. Avilez was often the center of attention at gatherings, often encouraging people to dance and let loose. Avilez died April 9, 2020, at New York Community Hospital at the age of 58.

hardCodedText: Gurpaul Singh moved from California to New York City in 1985. He drove a yellow cab for more than 25 years and was a landlord. Singh supported his family in India and was able to put his three children through school. He was a carefree person who was the “the glue” of his family, said his daughter Manpreet Kaur, who recalled how her father regularly checked in on her. In his downtime, Singh enjoyed fixing up his house and always looked for new projects. He loved spending time with his children and even his tenants’ children called him “grandpa.” Singh did not speak negatively about people who were unkind to him, Kaur said, a quality she admired. He died on April 15, 2020, at the age of 62 at Jamaica Hospital Center in Queens.
author: Shrina Pahwa

hardCodedText: Paul Douglas Gray was born in New York City and grew up in the Bronx with three siblings: Haskell, Herman and Cathy. Paul worked for the postal service followed by New York City Transit, later moving to a career in social services — a fitting field for Paul, according to his sister, Cathy, who said he had “an innate love for people.” Paul worked for Visiting Nurse Services as the coordinator for a respite care program. He later became a therapeutic foster parent and helped youth with emotional and special needs. Paul was patient and mild mannered with children, Cathy said, a trait that many people admired. He treated his foster children with the same love, discipline and respect as his own children, she added. He was in the process of adopting a foster son, Devon, when he died. Gray was a doting father to his children, Jazmine and Donivan; and a godfather, uncle and brother. “Paul was the life of the party,” Cathy said. “He was a person I could tell all my deep secrets and whatever was on my mind from politics to sports,” said his friend Martin Culler. Paul was a sports fanatic, his family said, and also enjoyed food, music, design and architecture. Paul died in Valhalla, N.Y. on April 20, 2020, at the age of 61.
hardCodedPullquote: Everybody knows Paul was always laughing, always smiling.

hardCodedText: Gladys E. Castillo immigrated to the U.S. from Manta, Ecuador, in 1969, at the age of 25. She arrived by herself and didn’t speak English but found a job and a room to rent the very next day. Castillo settled in Woodhaven, Queens, and supported her family and two children who stayed in Ecuador with her mother. Castillo worked at a jewelry store in Manhattan until her late 40s. She was injured in a car crash and suffered a brain injury that forced her to retire, according to her daughter, Lesme Morales. Yet, Castillo rarely stayed home. She went to the senior center early every morning to see her friends and play bingo. Castillo often brought food to visitors at the center. “She wanted to help anybody who needed it and would try to provide whatever our neighbors needed,” Morales said.Castillo died on April 8, 2020, at Jamaica Hospital Medical Center in Queens at the age of 79.
hardCodedPullquote: My mom was a strong and amazing woman. Nothing stopped her when she wanted to do something.

hardCodedText: Aryeh Norensberg was born in Brooklyn in 1940. Always a hard worker, he shined shoes when he was 9 years old and went on to earn a Ph.D. in economics and teach at Brooklyn College. He was an early pioneer in computer science, working on computers as early as 1959. After the stock market crashed, Norensberg shifted his career and worked for the city in the Administration for Children’s Service, retiring as assistant commissioner. Norensberg’s greatest joy came from watching his family — especially his seven children and 20 grandchildren — succeed. He celebrated each accomplishment with the same fervor “whether it was a kindergarten play or a wedding,” said his son, Avi. Norensberg showed up for his family when they needed him most, visiting a grandchild in the NICU six days a week for her brief life, and welcoming a son into his home who was recovering from addiction. He was affectionately known among his friends and community as “Tatty,” a Yiddish word reserved for beloved parents. Norensberg married Sydney Norensberg in 1963, and they were together for 56 years. A leader of the Bais Yisroel Torah Center and follower of Rabbi Avigdor Miller, Norensberg studied the bible rigorously, his son said. His family remembers the voice messages they would leave for him, with good news they wanted to celebrate. “When I sent stuff to my father, it would literally be like a party in his head,” Avi Norensberg said. Norensberg died April 19, 2020, at Maimonides Hospital at the age of 79.
hardCodedPullquote: We call it “nachas.” You get satisfaction and a genuine joy out of the accomplishments of your children and grandchildren. And he lived for that, that was his thing.
author: Allison Dikanovic

hardCodedText: Ronald “Ronnie” McKie was in Augusta, Georgia, in 1946 and grew up in Brooklyn. There, he met his wife Valerie with whom he had seven children, 16 grandchildren and 9 great-grandchildren. McKie had a short stint at the Brooklyn Academy of Music but soon found a career with the New York Transit Authority where he worked for over 30 years, until 2018 when he retired. He spent his free time with his family, listening to the oldies, rock, rap and playing video games. His favorite games involved racing cars — whether playing in person with his grandkids or online, he would always come out on top. McKie enjoyed eating his wife's Southern-style home cooking and being surrounded by those he loved. His daughter Sha-Von McKie described him as the most “original” person she knew. “His steady presence and originality are dearly missed,” she said. McKie died on May 12, 2020, at NYU Langone Hospital — Long Island at the age of 73. He is survived by his wife Valerie and his children Larry Jr., Shawn, Lawana, Sha-Von, Tamara and Michelle.

Candida Rosa Molina, or Mamá Rosa, lived in San Salvador, El Salvador for most of her life. There, she raised 10 children as a single mother and worked as a housekeeper. In the 1990s, Molina, who was in her 60s, moved to New York City to be closer to her family. She lived with her daughter and son-in-law, first in Elmhurst then in Corona, Queens. Molina did not speak much English and her family worried about cultural differences and language barriers. Yet, she used to go out on her own and return home with stories about people she met, including those who did not speak Spanish. She loved living in the U.S. and used to say “this is my country” and she would “visit” El Salvador. “Living in New York for her meant a start of a new life,” said her granddaughter Yansi Pérez. Molina read People magazine in Spanish to stay on top of pop culture, including R&B and actors. She enjoyed music, radio, watching soap operas and the news on TV, crossword puzzles and tango. Molina died on January 19, 2021, at the age of 99, two weeks before her 100th birthday.
hardCodedPullquote: My grandmother was an energetic and feisty woman.
pullquoteSource: Yansi Pérez, Candida Rosa Molina’s granddaughter

hardCodedText: Chandrawati Gurdiyal was born in 1927 and grew up with five siblings. She was of Indian descent and lived in Guyana. After her husband was injured in a factory accident, she started a rice farming business and owned and operated a store to support her family. Gurdiyal immigrated to the U.S. in 1992, joining her daughter, Sati, in Queens. In her new city, she babysat children. After retiring, she frequently visited a senior center where she spent time with Guyanese friends. She always tried to learn new things, her daughter said, taking classes in public speaking and singing. Gurdiyal was religious and loved to travel, dance and listen to Hindi songs. She “never let anything get her down,” said her daughter, Sati Gurdiyal. Chandrawati Gurdiyal died May 17, 2020, at a nursing home in Queens at the age of 92.
hardCodedPullquote: My mother was hardworking and joyful.

hardCodedText: Theodore Campbell grew up in Harlem. He joined the New York City Police Department in 1985 and was later promoted to the rank of detective. After retiring in 2005, he worked as a security guard at a Manhattan animal shelter run by the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals​​. Campbell’s friends called him "Teddy" or "Soup" because of his last name. He was a classy dresser, yet humble and modest, said his best friend and fellow NYPD officer Ron Stephenson. Campbell got along with everyone, Stephenson said. “Even if they were mean to him, he would be respectful and treat them nice. That's how he was.” When Stephenson told Campbell about his dream of opening a karate school for kids, his friend stepped up to help. Campbell was a basketball player but eventually earned a 5th degree black belt while teaching classes at the karate school. He taught dozens of children, including his own son and godchildren and never missed his students’ graduations, Stephenson said. His son, Theodore Bilal Campbell, went on to win multiple state championships in the martial arts. "He always made sure I was on track with everything and did not feel less than others," his son said.  Campbell died Jan. 9, 2021 at the Long Island Jewish Medical Center at the age of 64. He is survived by two children and his girlfriend, Dawn Adams.
hardCodedPullquote: My father treated people with the kind of love he treated family.
pullquoteSource: Theodore Bilal Campbell, Theodore Campbell’s son
author: Jiyong Lee

employer: Sky Chef at John F. Kennedy Airport

hardCodedText: Born in 1965 in Pelileo, Ecuador, Leonel Tusa Masaquiza went from a boy playing soccer with friends known as “Los Tigres” to a teenager dating Gloria Quinga, whom he described as the love of his life. The couple married and raised three daughters. Tusa,  a civil engineer, immigrated to New York City with his family in 2001 months before the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks, settling in Ridgewood, Queens. Tusa initially worked as a day laborer before transitioning to construction and other jobs. He was humble and blessed everyone with kindness and generosity, said his daughter, Jael Tusa. “He was so down to Earth…He always cared about people so much, even if they hurt him.” Tusa brought his family flowers on Valentine’s Day, Mother's Day and anniversaries, she said. He would often say: “I would be nothing without you guys.” Tusa began studying civics questions for the U.S. naturalization test a year before he booked his appointment. He passed and became a U.S. citizen in 2017 — a major personal milestone, which brought him joy, his family said. “He sent us all a selfie next to the American flag,” Jael said. Tusa died April 29, 2020, at Mount Sinai Queens at the age of 54. He is survived by his wife Gloria Quinga; daughters Evelin Tusa, Jael Tusa and Britney Tusa; and grandchildren Mateo Sanchez and Abby Sanchez.
hardCodedPullquote: He always taught us family is key to everything. He would always say, ‘If one of us goes, we all go.’ So, anywhere we went we were always all together.
pullquoteSource: Jael Tusa, daughter of Leonel Tusa
author: Gabriel Sandoval

employer: New York City Housing Preservation & Development
additionalNotes: Spoke to Rocio Medrano, longtime friend, and Lopez's daughter Angelica

hardCodedText: A teacher, legislator and community activist, Joseph Ferris was a lifelong Brooklynite who served five terms in the New York Assembly representing Park Slope. He “believed deeply in the power of community and the people who live in them,” said his son, Joseph M. Ferris. “He taught me and my brother the importance of civic engagement and making the places you live a better place.” Prior to his time in the New York Assembly, Ferris served in the U.S. Army Reserve and taught in New York City schools and at a prison on Rikers Island. After retiring from the Assembly, Ferris continued to serve New Yorkers, participating in block associations and civic groups. He worked on green education initiatives with the Magnolia Tree Earth Center in Bedford-Stuyvesant, which planted thousands of trees in the neighborhood. Ferris died June 20, 2020, at the Cobble Hill Health Center at the age of 85. He is survived by his two sons, Joseph M. Ferris and Thomas Ferris; a daughter-in-law; and two grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: Joe Ferris had a profound impact on the politics of Brooklyn and New York City, and was a fierce advocate for independence and reform.
pullquoteSource: New York Assembly Member Robert Carroll, Joseph Ferris’ successor
author: Phyllis Kaufman

hardCodedText: Beatriz Soler followed her husband, Andres Jimenez, to New York City in 1990, leaving their two daughters behind in Bogota, Colombia, to provide for her family. Six years later, they brought their daughters to New York City. Their family eventually grew to include four grandchildren. Soler worked at a factory and later opened a bike shop, Bicycle Repairman, in Astoria, Queens, with her husband and daughters. Soler cared for her grandchildren and brought lunch to her family every weekday at the shop. Customers loved Soler’s coffee, a special blend she made using Bustelo and Supremo, a recipe that continues today, her family said. A few months before Soler became sick with COVID-19, her daughter, Leidy Jimenez, bought a house where she hoped to have many barbecues with her mother. Soler died April 10, 2020 at John T. Mather Memorial Hospital in Long Island, at the age of 67. She is survived by her husband, Andres Jimenez; daughters, Leidy Jimenez and Carolin Jimenez; and four grandchildren: Nathaly, Johann, Valerie and Melanie.
hardCodedPullquote: My little one, she still writes to her grandma’s cell phone. She says, ‘Oh, Mommy. I wrote to grandma but she hasn’t answered back.’ She says, ‘Grandma, I miss you. I know you are in heaven.’
author: Ann Choi

additionalNotes: survived by his two daughters and their husbands, Karen and Michael Milano of Killingworth, and Susan and Ken Corbin of Pomfret.

hardCodedText: Ernesto “Ernie” Sanchez, a Puerto Rican immigrant and general contractor, was “like the Mayor of Ridgewood” where he lived for over 30 years, said his son, Jesse Bravo. He always had time to greet neighbors and help them with things that needed repair, his family said. “He loved to help people. If you had a problem he’d come over to your house and fix something, that's just how he was,” Jesse said. Sanchez loved bowling, fishing and was a devoted Mets fan. He enjoyed nature, gardening and bird-watching eagles. He died March 6, 2021, at NYU Langone at the age of 70. He is survived by his wife, Lucy Sanchez; son, Jesse Bravo; daughter-in-law Jennifer; and two grandchildren, Jamil and Julianna Bravo.
hardCodedPullquote: At his funeral the whole neighborhood knew he died. Everybody knew him.
author: Christine Chung

jobTitle: owner of laundromats and hair salons

hardCodedText: Millie Belle Berry was born in 1909. A lifelong resident of Harlem, Millie told family and friends colorful stories about her early life. During the Depression, her family worked for a wealthy Jewish family who made sure they had plenty to eat. During World War II, Millie worked in a factory on Park Avenue making artillery belts. She then worked as a lab tech in the microbiology department at New York Presbyterian Hospital for 30 years until she retired in her 60s. Millie married Leroy Berry in 1928 and had three daughters: Dorothy Lunden, Bernice Berry and Carolyn France. She was widowed in 1945. She leaves behind three granddaughters and four great-grandchildren. Her great-granddaughter, Quasé Beasley, remembers Millie’s baking, especially her homemade rolls: “It was like a piece of heaven.” Quasé also remembers Millie and her daughters as the “Fashionistas of Harlem.” They loved to shop and traveled all over the world, she said. Since 2015, Millie lived at Archcare Terrence Cardinal Cooke nursing center on Fifth Avenue. She died on April 22, 2020 at the age of 110.
hardCodedPullquote: She never had a bad word to say about anyone.  She was a glass half full sort of person.  She was not one to complain or argue. She was very sweet, very kind, never had an enemy.
author: Holly Bell
streetAddress: Archcare Terrence Cardinal Cooke 1209 5th Avenue NY NY
newsSource: Harlem World Magazine - story about her 109th birthday
additionalNotes: There was some controversy about whether Ms. Berry died of Covid or not.  Quase Beasley gave me a history of the last month of her great grandmother's life, which I have forwarded to Anjali.
interviewed daughter Odalis Santana for obit
He is survived by his son Brian, daughter-in-law Sheila; and his son David and daughter-in-law Jessica, of Miami.
Cary Diamond, 220-31 Kingsbury Ave., Oakland Gardens, NY 11364 and daughter, Allison Allisondiamond421@icloud.com

hardCodedText: Dr. Albert Goodgold grew up in Brownsville, Brooklyn, and attended medical school in Bern, Switzerland. He completed his residency in neurology at NYU School of Medicine. He was a “medical detective,” according to his daughter, Carolee Goodgold. “He never ever gave up. Every doctor that couldn’t figure out a problem would send their patients to him,” she said. He saved thousands of lives through a decades-long career, Carolee said. One of his patients reached out to tell her that he cared for 25 members of his family and they referred to him as “Uncle Al.” Goodgold loved music and played the saxophone. “He had the first CD player that ever came out. It opened up like a cassette player and was $600,” Carolee said. At 60, Goodgold decided to learn Italian and translated a book from Italian to English that was eventually published as an e-book. Goodgold was affable and charming, his family said. “He knew every single porter, about 15, that worked in my parents’ building. He knew where they were from, he knew their families,” Carolee said. “Even the bagel guy across the street asks, ‘Where’s the doctor?’” Goodgold died April 14, 2020, at NYU Langone Hospital at the age of 92. He  is survived by his wife Ruth Goodgold; children Henry, Carolee, and Robert; and grandchildren Shauna, Rachel, and Julia.
hardCodedPullquote: He was so passionate about everything. He would say, ‘Let me just read you this one.’ And when he said just one, he meant a whole chapter of a book.
pullquoteSource: Carolee Goodgold, Dr. Albert Goodgold’s daughter
author: Hayley Duffy

additionalNotes: Her daughter, Ellen Wasserman, Her son, Ira Berman

hardCodedText: John Peter Marchini was born in 1957 in Jackson Heights, Queens. As a child, he developed a love for cars that he carried into adulthood. Marchini worked for his family’s sanitation company and later left to open a bakery in Brooklyn Heights. In 1998, Marchini married his wife, Dawn, who had a daughter, Nicolette Plenca. On their wedding day, he gave both his wife and new daughter a ring of their own. The couple later had three sons: Joseph, Anthony and Michael. Marchini spent quality time with his children, bringing them to car shows and the water park. Marchini later opened a pizzeria in Maspeth, Queens. He helped families in need with extra food and money and gave jobs to kids in the neighborhood. Marchini died on April 28, 2020, at St. Francis Hospital in Roslyn, New York at age of 63.
hardCodedPullquote: He was great… the most loving father. He did everything he could for his family.
pullquoteSource: Anthony Marchini, John Peter Marchini’s son
author: Jhevauni James

hardCodedText: Martin Vidal Rosete was born in Mexico. He loved being in nature and often went camping and hunting. When he arrived in New York City in 1998, he immediately began exploring the area, riding trains wherever he could take them. Rosete eventually found a job at the Citarella market, an upscale grocery store, where he found valuable friends in his coworkers. He loved working in a supermarket, making sure customers got the best products available. Rosete took care of his siblings and later, his nieces and nephews, entertaining them with his playful personality. “Martin was the best big brother,” said his sister, Teresa Vidal. He was seen as the life of the party, she added, always smiling and having a good time. Rosete died on May 14, 2020, at New York-Presbyterian Hospital at the age of 52.
author: Jhevauni James

hardCodedText: Luis Santos was born in Ecuador and left school to help care for his mother. In 1978, he moved to New York City, where he stayed with family until he was able to bring his wife, Ginger Santos, to an apartment on the Lower East Side. The couple later moved to Harlem. Despite his limited English, Santos always found a way to communicate with others. He soon found a job as a barber in The Bronx where he often worked six days a week. Luis was a religious man who went to church often. When the congregation sang the hymn “Santo, Santo, Santo,” he’d turn to his daughter, Jasmin Santos, and laugh together about how similar the lyrics were to their last name. Luis loved exploring his roots in Ecuador and frequently traveled back. He was a jokester and the life of the party, Jasmin said, sometimes to his detriment. One night at a party his chest started to hurt. Luis continued to enjoy himself and didn’t alert his family until the next morning. When he went to the doctors office, they said he had a stroke. He died on May 12, 2020, while listening to music, surrounded by his family. He was 70 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a fighter, every little thing that happened to him… he would come out of it.
author: Jhevauni James

hardCodedText: Adolfo Motta was born in 1958 in Guatemala. In the 1970s, he moved to New York where he met his wife, Lety Motta. Adolfo worked as a truck driver to provide for his family, which grew to include four daughters, sons-in-law and 10 grandchildren. He later teamed up with his son-in-law to work in landscaping. Adolfo enjoyed reading and often listened to the Beatles and Creedence Clearwater Revival. He worked hard but never let his work get in the way of spending time with his family, attending recitals and spelling bees, said his daughter, Karem Motta. Karen said her father taught her how to speak Spanish and helped her improve her public speaking skills. He always encouraged his daughters to do better, she added. Adolfo Motta died on Feb. 7, 2021, at North Shore University Hospital at the age of 62.
hardCodedPullquote: Everyone says the same thing, they have the best father in the world, but honestly he was the best.
author: Jhevauni James

hardCodedText: Purim Isakov was born in Quba, Azerbaijan, in 1940. She dreamed of pursuing a career  in music, however, religious and cultural restrictions prevented her from doing so, said her daughter Maya Isakov. She immigrated to New York in August 1994 with her husband, Isak, and their five children. “She always walked with her head up with a smile on her face no matter how difficult it was up to the very last day,” said her daughter Maya. “She always taught us to never give up!” Purim died on May 14, 2020, at NYU Langone at the age of 79.
hardCodedPullquote: She will remain forever in the memory and hearts of her husband, children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren as a bright and kind person.
author: Jhevauni James

hardCodedText: Kenneth Green was born in The Bronx and served in the Marines in the 1980s. He was honorably discharged after injuring his leg. Green later pursued a career as an actor and worked at Macy’s as a security guard. He loved old movies and often watched with his niece Tyra Dickison and nephews Nurud-Din Muhammad and Brandon Simon. Green was a father figure to Dickison who remembers him as a passionate and caring person. Green loved to cook, paint and draw. He was also opinionated, she said, and took to social media to share his views. He died on April 12, 2020, at Montefiore Medical Center at the age of 54.
hardCodedPullquote: He was just always there for you… you could go to him for anything.
author: Jhevauni James

additionalNotes: Survived by her husband, Leon; her 4-year-old daughter, Leona; her mother, Beverly Woods; and her siblings, Angelique, Annie Nicole, John and Alexander.

obitSource: Legacy.com, info provided by her son Charles Green
additionalNotes: *because she spent the last ten years of her life in a nursing home, I used the address of the nursing home.

hardCodedText: Carlos “Candallo” Acevedo was born in Las Marias, Puerto Rico, and moved to The Bronx in his youth to attend high school. He worked at the New York Botanical Gardens as a teenager and then joined the U.S. Army. Carlos later worked as a commercial truck driver. He was a compassionate and wonderful father to his three children, said his wife Yolanda Acevedo. When his daughter’s car broke down in the middle of a highway, Carlos got in a cab to meet her and got it running again with only a bobby pin and a hair tie, said his daughter Jailin Acevedo. He was happiest when surrounded by his family. He loved children and couldn’t stop smiling when he met his grandson for the first time, said his son Carlito Acevedo. Carlos also loved animals and enjoyed spending time outside with his dog, Bacon. He played the congas around the house with a backwards Yankees cap and influenced his children’s love for salsa music. He died on April 15, 2020, at home.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a prickly bear, but he was our prickly bear. There was never a day we doubted we were loved; though we annoyed him tons, we always knew he loved us.
author: Kaitlyn Patterson

hardCodedText: Maria C. Iasiuolo was born and raised in Staten Island in a family with six children, according to her daughter Louisa Mandato. From a young age, Maria took care of her mother who suffered from multiple sclerosis. She became her siblings’ primary caretaker, quitting school to help raise them. Maria married her childhood sweetheart, Jack Iasiuolo. They were married for 42 years until his death in 1993 at the age of 72. Maria raised four children and served as a foster mother for 15 years. In her free time, she crocheted scarves and baby blankets for family members and friends, even making extra to donate to homeless shelters. She loved to cook and could whip up a gourmet meal from scratch. Maria loved fashion and dressed in classy matching outfits, her daughter said. She continued going clothes shopping in her late 80s and 90s. Maria celebrated her 90th birthday with family last November. She died exactly a year later on her 91st birthday, Nov. 27, 2020, at Richmond University Medical Center. She is survived by a sister; four children: Maria McKay, Louisa Mandato, Joseph Iasiuolo and Carol Donovan; three son-in-laws; seven grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: My mom was a warrior.
author: Kaitlyn Patterson

employer: New York City Department of Sanitation
additionalNotes: Survived by 4 daughters

hardCodedText: Miriam Kerpen was born Miriam Civic in 1920 as a fourth-generation New Yorker. After graduating from Cornell University at age 19, she completed a master’s degree in economics at Columbia University and settled in Greenwich Village. In 1955, after divorcing her college sweetheart, she met an Austrian émigré, Fred Kerpen, while volunteering with Americans for Democratic Action and the Adlai Stevenson presidential campaign. They married and moved to an apartment on Washington Square North in 1957, where Kerpen lived for almost 60 years before moving to an assisted living facility. She worked as an assistant to Abraham Epstein, an economist who focused on social justice. She also worked at the National Industrial Conference Board with Alan Greenspan and the City of New York in the Department of Housing Preservation and Development. Kerpen had a lifelong passion for travel and people, her family said. She was devoted to her grandchildren and loved spending time and hosting them in New York City.  Kerpen died Dec. 29, 2020, at the age of 100. She is survived by daughter, Lisa Shufro; stepson Peter Kerpen; and seven grandchildren: David, Philip and Daniel Kerpen and Paul, Jacob, Hannah and Sophie Shufro.
hardCodedPullquote: She had many circles of friends, from childhood, college and through to her last days; she was never without people whom she cared about and who cared about her.
pullquoteSource: Lisa Kerpen Shufro, Miriam Mimi Kerpen’s daughter
author: Cathy Shufro

hardCodedText: Born in 1930 in Laguna Salada, Dominican Republic, Gilda Villaman grew up under a brutal dictatorship. At 30, she fled to the U.S., settling in The Bronx with cousins before finding a permanent home in Manhattan’s Washington Heights neighborhood. She married, divorced and wound up raising her son and daughter as a single mother with her family’s help. Determined to succeed, she learned English by reading novels and watching TV, her family said. After working in a factory, she took a course to become a hospital lab technician and found a position at Roosevelt Hospital (now Mount Sinai West), where she worked until her mid-60s. In retirement, she enjoyed volunteering, helping the needy, tending her rose garden and hosting an annual Christmas party for neighbors, where she served up her specialty: arroz con gandules, her family said. A devout Christian, she cherished her freedom, said her daughter, Wendy. “She was a very, very outspoken person. So she loved that she could criticize the government with no repercussions,” Wendy said. One of eight siblings, Villaman’s sister died in January and a brother in April, the latter to COVID-19. Villaman died at New York-Presbyterian on May 16, 2020, at the age of 89. She is survived by her daughter, Wendy Villaman, and son, David Acosta.
hardCodedPullquote: Even though she wasn’t born in this country, she was very patriotic. She really did love her community and America. It seemed like she was more American than Dominican after a while.
author: Gabriel Sandoval

hardCodedText: Hui Liang Wen, who went by the nickname “Bill,” was born in China, where he painted billboards and opened a photo store at the age of 18. Known for his creative talent and deep empathy, he served even the poorest customers, pretending the copier had printed extra photos that could be given free of charge, his family said. He moved to New York and met his wife, Xiao Hong Wen, at an English learning program. They had three children: John, Kevin and Michelle, all of whom they supported through college. Wen worked in textile manufacturing and, at one point, opened his own business. Eventually, he began working for another manufacturing company. His coworkers were his beloved friends, his family said, and feted him with birthday lunches. His daughter, Michelle, recalls him as a silent hero who carried her in one arm down the side of a steep mountain while hiking in China, as they were stuck without another way down. “He was confident, hilarious, charming, deeply loving, and was deeply loved in return,” she said. Wen died April 14, 2020, at the age of 57 at New York-Presbyterian Brooklyn Methodist Hospital.
hardCodedPullquote: My dad is the type to just really, really be incredibly sympathetic and empathetic for other families, especially those who were struggling… Any notable thing that he’s done seems to center around being compassionate, selfless and a wholesome family guy.
pullquoteSource: Michelle Wen, Hui Liang Wen’s daughter
author: Lauren Abrams

hardCodedText: Nina Marie Favuzza grew up on the Lower East Side. She later lived in Middle Village Queens and worked as a secretary at New York University and at the law firm Kaye, Scholer, Fierman, Hays & Handler. Nina enjoyed traveling, crocheting blankets and listening to music, particularly Elvis Presley and Barbra Streisand. She frequently visited her friends in different states and abroad. She was a member of a book club at the Alley Pond Environmental Center in Queens and often brought brownies to meetings. Since Nina’s death, her sister Rosemarie Favuzza said she has received hundreds of calls, emails and notes from her sister’s friends and neighbors, attesting to her kindness. One neighbor wrote to say that Nina would often stop and talk to him and was a warm presence in the building where she lived for the last two years. “She never spoke badly about anyone and always gave people the benefit of the doubt,” Rosemarie said. Nina died at home on Jan. 27, 2021, at the age of 62. She is survived by a brother, Matthew Favuzza; sister, Rosemarie Favuzza; sister-in-law, Angela; brother-in-law, John; nieces Alexandra and Casey; nephews Matthew and Michael and numerous cousins.
hardCodedPullquote: She did everything without expecting any recognition.
pullquoteSource: Rosemarie Favuzza, Nina Marie Favuzza’s sister
author: Jiyong Lee

hardCodedText: Mohamed Nezaam Harun was born in Guyana and moved to New York City 20 years ago, following his younger brother, Mo Harun. Harun worked various jobs, most recently in retail. Mohamed learned to play the harmonica when he was younger and often played for family and friends. He was the life of the party, his family said. “He loved to make jokes and found humor in everything,” said his brother, Mo. Whenever someone approached him with a problem, he would tell a joke, his family recalled. His neighbors in Richmond Hill, Queens, often stopped by or called him to ask for help repairing their cars or building a shed. He found time for people, according to his brother. Mohamed died Jan. 3, 2021, at Long Island Jewish Hospital at the age of 67. He is survived by his wife, four sons and a daughter, grandchildren and eight siblings.
hardCodedPullquote: [A] soft-spoken and kind-hearted brother. He had a funny bone that he shared with old and young alike.
pullquoteSource: Mo Harun, Mohamed Nezaam Harun’s brother
author: Jiyong Lee

hardCodedText: Olga Zayas immigrated to the United States from Ecuador in the 1960s and became a U.S. citizen in the 1970s. She was the oldest of six siblings and took care of her younger brothers and sisters after their mother died. Zayas settled in The Bronx with her husband, to whom she was married for 51 years. Together, they had five children, including two who were adopted. The family moved to Edenwald Houses in the Baychester area of The Bronx in November 1978. Zayas attended secretarial school, working at several companies before becoming a licensed care provider to babysit children at home. Zayas loved her children and was invested in their education. She volunteered at their school where she was known as “Ms. Olga.” After adopting a son, she decided to foster his sister as well. “My mother was selfless and the biggest advocate for her adopted children, one of whom has autism,” said her daughter, Renee Zayas. Renee added that she and her sister used to wear matching clothes made by their mother, who sewed and knitted in her free time. Zayas died on Jan. 5, 2021, at Jacobi Medical Center at the age of 79. She is survived by four sisters, her husband, five children, seven grandchildren and a great-granddaughter.
hardCodedPullquote: My mother was a very family-oriented lady and did everything for her children.
author: Jiyong Lee

jobTitle: Business Woman - Taught ESL to Chinese students in free time

hardCodedText: Gloria Barone was the epitome of a thoughtful, loving aunt, said her niece, Pam Parlakian. She was born in The Bronx as the youngest of three siblings. She worked as an airlines reservation clerk and then as an administrative assistant, traveling the world with friends and living for a period of time in San Francisco and Madrid. Barone loved the “Fearless Girl” sculpture in Lower Manhattan. Her own fearlessness allowed her to take on new adventures by living abroad and fostering close relationships with both her family and lifelong friends, as well as new friends she made in the Norwegian Christian Home in Brooklyn. Barone was the kind of person who would go out of her way to keep her loved ones close, said Parlakian. She made sure to write long letters — not emails — to her friends when abroad and send gifts on special occasions. Barone was very close to her sister and brother; they bonded over music. Her favorites included The Beatles, Paul McCartney and Frank Sinatra. She was also a devoted PBS and TCM fan. She was also very into fashion, “ordering from catalogs like no other,” Parlakian said. Barone died April 16, 2020, at the age of 86. Her lively spirit will be missed by her friends and family, Parlakian said.
hardCodedPullquote: Everybody loved her because she was sweet, thoughtful and very polite.
author: Isabelle Franz

additionalNotes: Interview daughter Shante Harkless-Brown for obit
Interviewed daughter Jo-Anne Giuliani for obit

hardCodedText: A Bronx native, Terrence Darkim Riley was one of seven children. After graduating from high school, he went through New York City’s vocational training program and studied building maintenance at Hostos Community College. He later pursued a career in security, working as a security guard for Allied Universal, most recently at a public assistance center. Riley took his three daughters to school every day before starting his shift at noon. A family-oriented man, Riley worked hard to support them, his family said, and loved doing it. Friendly and outgoing, Riley loved to have fun: going to parties, family functions or just playing on his PlayStation. On weekends, he’d roam the boroughs searching for a pickup basketball game. Riley also traveled with his family, going down the coast to Atlantic City, Disney World, North Carolina and Miami. His mother, Robin McCutheon, remembers taking Riley to Manhattan to ride a speedboat when he was 14. He was fascinated by the Beast’s shark design as it sped through the Harbor, she remembers. Riley died May 3, 2020, at Brookdale Medical Center at age 32. He is survived by his parents; two sets of grandparents; six siblings; three daughters; and a host of aunts, uncles and cousins.
hardCodedPullquote: He went to several tournaments… wherever there was a basketball and a park, he played.
author: Justin Yip
additionalNotes: Interviewed mother Robin McCutheon for obit
Interviewed Cayce, daughter for obit

hardCodedText: Marisa Soto Williams was devoted to children. Born in California, Williams moved to New York in the early 1990s. Her friend, Qwana Reynolds, recalled meeting Williams in an early childhood education class at City College in 1994. Reynolds, who had a small child and no childcare, brought her son to class and Williams offered to help entertain. Williams “always had a nurturing spirit with children,” she said. Williams graduated with a bachelor’s degree in early childhood education and taught gifted and talented  fourth graders at  P.S.153 in Harlem. She later established the Ricardo O’Gorman Library School with her friend, Ned O’Gorman, and helped run it for two years. Williams then became a full-time mom, devoting herself to her own children’s education. When she was not caring for children, Williams was described as funny and nurturing and loved knitting, music, reading and shopping at BJ’s, her friends said. She died Nov. 27, 2020 at the age of 48 and is survived by her husband, Donnie Williams, and three children.
hardCodedPullquote: She was like a house. She always wanted people to feel loved and sheltered and supported.
author: Holly Bell

Jose helped support church members in Central America and in Jamaica, Queens. I interviewed his Wife, Lydia Aviles. They have 2 sons.
Dorothy was a stay at home mom. I interviewed her daughter, Norine Hurtado.
Interviews her daughter, Debora Coulanges. She had a huge family with 6 kids, and 20+ grandkids/great grandkids and raised them all.

hardCodedText: Rosa Villada immigrated to the United States from Honduras in the late 1970s. For more than 20 years, Villada worked as a  paraprofessional educator, working with special needs students at P.S. 199 Jessie Isador Straus on the Upper West Side. Villada constantly talked about her students with awe and admiration, according to her niece, Marcia Flores Hruska. She was a funny, caring and doting mother and aunt who was also a stellar cook, her family said. Although family members differ on their favorite recipes, her niece, Marcia, said Villada’s best dish was her meatloaf. Villada died May 21, 2020, at New York-Presbyterian Allen Hospital at the age of 68. She is survived by her husband of 35 years, Fernando Villada; her daughters, Diana and Jessica Villada; her mother, Albertina Espinal; her sister, Gladys Flores; her nephew, Alex; her niece, Marcia Flores Hruska; and Marcia’s children, Raquel and Raoul.
hardCodedPullquote: She was a good mom. She was a good teacher. She was all these things that exuded warmth and care.
pullquoteSource: Marcia Flores Hruska, Rosa Villada’s niece
author: Grace Dennis
streetAddress: 74 Van Cortlandt Park S Apt Ee2, Bronx, NY

additionalNotes: I interviewed Linda Molina, wife, and submitted draft of obituary for edits.

hardCodedText: Maria Arechua was born in Catarama, Ecuador, in 1934, the third of 10 children. After graduating from high school, she moved to Guayaquil, Ecuador, where she got married and had her first child at the age of 19. She had three children: Marieta Azucena Velasco, Fernando Velasco and Maria Velasco-Bishun. In 1960, she got a job as a nursemaid for an American diplomat and moved to the U.S. Her family was reunited in New York City eight years later after all three children received their visas. Friends and family nicknamed her “Maria the Great” for her sharp and quick-wit. “She was stern but gave the best advice,” said her granddaughter Mirella Bajana. Arechua had always dreamed of working in the beauty industry and encouraged others to follow their passion. In her free time, she loved cooking, doing crossword puzzles and listening to her favorite radio station, the Spanish-language WADO. Arechua died April 18, 2020, at NewYork-Presbyterian/Columbia University Irving Medical Center at the age of 86.
hardCodedPullquote: She truly was a giver and I hold everything that she has given to me close to my heart.
pullquoteSource: Mirella Bajana, granddaughter of Maria Arechua
author: Molly Wilde

hardCodedText: Born and raised in Puerto Rico, Carmen Pacheco moved to The Bronx to provide a better life for her children. There, she worked as a housekeeper to support her family. “Regardless of what she was going through, she was such a kind person and was always there for her friends and family,” said her daughter Maria Nazario. Pacheco showed her love by  cooking family meals and planning gatherings with friends, Nazario said. “Her favorite thing was seeing everyone together. It energized her and gave her life.” For Pacheco’s 70th birthday, her friends and family organized a big surprise party with  her children, grandchildren and friends from Puerto Rico. “That was the happiest that I’ve ever seen my mom,” Nazario said.  “It was a really special moment for all of us.” In her free time, Pacheco loved shopping, going to the movies and caring for her plants. Pacheco died  April 12, 2020 at St. Barnabas Hospital in The Bronx at the age of 72. She is survived by seven children, four from her first partner: Gladys, Andres, Wilfredo, and Miguel Pablon, and three from her second partner: Maria, Felipe and Johnny Nazario. She also had 17 grandchildren, 16 great-grandchildren and two great-great-grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: She was the glue that kept us all together and I miss her everyday.
author: Molly Wilde

hardCodedText: Originally from Boston, Joseph Anthony Szalkiewicz served in the U.S. Marines Corps before he became a house painter and general contractor. Lovingly referred to as “papa” by friends and family, he was happiest when surrounded by the people he loved, his family said. In his free time, he loved to fish and listen to music, especially pop songs by Adele, Lady Gaga and Sam Smith. He loved spending time with his granddaughters Danielle Alejandro and Jessica Alejandro, taking them to IHOP for breakfast on Sundays and accompanying them to a Beyoncé concert. “He was the cool papa,” Jessica said. On family trips to Universal Studios and Disney World, Szalkiewicz loved going on the amusement park rides and taking pictures with all the characters. “He truly was a kid at heart who had a zest for life,” said his daughter Lisa Alejandro. His playful and adventurous nature also made him a “daredevil” who was not afraid to try new things from parasailing in Hawaii to jet skiing and jumping off waterfalls in Puerto Rico. He will be remembered for his big smile and for giving the best warm, tight hugs, his family said. Szalkiewicz died March 8, 2021, at the Staten University Hospital at the age of 78.
hardCodedPullquote: He was an incredible gift in our lives and we are so blessed and honored to have had him as a father and grandfather.
pullquoteSource: Lisa Alejandro, Joseph Anthony Szalkiewicz’s daughter
author: Molly Wilde

hardCodedText: Charles DeJesus grew up in Brooklyn with three sisters. After earning a bachelor’s and master's from Hofstra University, Charles became a high school history teacher, sharing his passion for learning about the past with young people. Charles loved the arts and went to the theater frequently with Diana Sito, his partner of 35 years. He enjoyed spending time outdoors and had a knack for nature photography. “He had a very unique way of looking at things that made him very attuned, to not only the beauty of nature, but the needs of those around him,” Sito said. Charles had a hearty laugh, a great sense of wit, his partner said, and was passionate about music, especially salsa, rock ‘n’ roll and jazz. He died on April 24, 2020, at Mount Sinai South Nassau Communities Hospital at the age of 66.
hardCodedPullquote: He will forever live in the many hearts and minds that he touched with his love and wisdom.
author: Molly Wilde

hardCodedText: Born and raised in Manhattan, Donato Cannella served in the Vietnam War and the Persian Gulf War before joining the United States Coast Guard for 22 years, reaching the rank of Petty Officer 2nd Class. Cannella later worked as an electrician for 35 years with ABC/The Walt Disney Company and was a member of Local Union No. 3 IBEW. Cannella enjoyed music, especially rock 'n' roll. Cannella attended the Woodstock festival in 1969 and later went to many concerts with his wife Marjorie. For their 45th wedding anniversary, Cannella’s family and friends threw him a rock 'n' roll-themed party. He loved to entertain, frequently hosting barbeques for his family and friends. He was known as the "King of the Grill” and made a signature omelet and specialty dishes for the holidays, said his granddaughter Jenice “Jekka” Santos-Rugaya. He was a handyman and taught his son Don woodworking and how to fix things around the house. Cannella loved watching sports with his son Chris and was an avid Yankees, Jets and Rangers fan. He put family first, said Santos-Rugaya, especially his grandchildren Donato, Angelina, Daniel, Jekka, Franz and Cheko, whom he spoiled every chance he got. Cannella died March 4, 2021, at Staten University Hospital at the age of 74.
hardCodedPullquote: He was the heart of the family. We’re especially going to miss his smile, his laugh and his jokes.
pullquoteSource: Jenice "Jekka" Santos-Rugaya, Donato Joseph Cannella’s granddaughter
author: Molly Wilde
