hardCodedText: Born and raised in Brooklyn, Ruel Aldrington Forbes was the youngest of 10 in a close-knit family. Forbes suffered from renal failure for 25 years but refused to let his medical condition stop him from leading an active life, his family said. He worked as a maintenance worker for the New York City Housing Authority, coaching basketball for neighborhood tournaments in his free time. In 2000, after several years working for the city, Forbes went back to school to become a certified dialysis technician. A son, sibling and father of four, Forbes died at NewYork-Presbyterian Brooklyn Methodist Hospital at the age of 50.
author: Taylor Zhang
jobTitle: New York City Maintenance for NYC housing
additionalNotes: Sean Forbes brother, scforbes01@gmail.com

hardCodedText: Marcus Overton grew up in Tennessee and later moved to New York City. After the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks, Marcus opened his home to people who were stranded. He worked as an exercise physiologist and was beloved by his clients, ranging from retirees or to athletes in their prime. Marcus had the ability to meet people at their level, encouraging them to be their “personal best,” said his friend, Virginia Chang. He loved sports and was a dedicated fan of the Giants, the Yankees and the Vols. He owned a matching pair of sneakers for every outfit. Marcus loved cooking, said his mother, and often prepared recipes from his childhood for his friends in New York. Five years before his death, Marcus suffered a debilitating stroke. He died May 29, 2020, at the age of 48 and is survived by his mother, sister, two nieces and a nephew.
hardCodedPullquote: Marcus had an eternal optimism about himself, his life, and his place in the world.
pullquoteSource: Virginia Chang, Marcus L. Overton’s friend
author: Katharine Dow

hardCodedText: Georgina Aguirre, known as Gina to close friends and family, was born in Ecuador. She left school to take care of her family and later immigrated to the U.S. in 1989 with her daughter. Aguirre worked at the Levinton factory in Brooklyn and took on other odd jobs. At 39, she suffered a stroke and was bound to a wheelchair. Aguirre overcame many obstacles that came with her disability. She always wore red lipstick and had her hair and nails done, said her daughter Karen Moran. Aguirre and her daughter were very close — they spent time cooking together and Aguirre often brought her yellow tulips. She had a sweet tooth and always had a stash of lollipops and chocolates on her nightstand. Aguirre died May 8, 2020, at Mount Sinai Beth Israel at the age of 59.
hardCodedPullquote: She was the one who put everyone together around her.
author: Jhevauni James
additionalNotes: Kin: Karen Moran

hardCodedText: Barbara Giordano Cassella was born in Pittsfield, Mass., in 1930. She moved to Brooklyn at a very young age with her parents and two brothers. Cassella’s first marriage ended in divorce, leaving her to raise two young children as a single mother for a period of time. She didn’t have much but every year her children were sure to find presents under the Christmas tree, said her son, David Aneiro. They were not alone through the hard times and lived above loved ones who were always there to help. Cassella remarried in 1973. In her home, family dinners were not optional. She loved to prepare large meals, combining her passions for cooking and gathering family. Cassella had seven grandchildren and five great-grandchildren, to whom she was affectionately known as “Nanny.” Her granddaughter Julia Aneiro said: “Nothing made her happier than seeing us flourish and celebrating our accomplishments, big or small, with a hearty meal shared around our family table.” Cassella died April 7, 2020, at Saints Joachim & Anne Nursing and Rehabilitation Center in Brooklyn at the age of 89.
hardCodedPullquote: Nanny was silly, neurotic and so full of love, with a smile that lit up a room and made you feel like the most important person there.
author: Nate Ware
additionalNotes: Survived cancer back in the 1980's
Survived by 7 children.
Spoke to her daughter

hardCodedText: William Negron moved from Puerto Rico to Washington Heights in his 20s in search of a better job. Having lost their parents at an early age, he and his six siblings were inseparable. As soon as he moved to New York City, he started working at a luggage factory. Later settling in Sunset Park in Brooklyn, he continued to work in a factory. William was the life of the party at family gatherings, said his niece, Sonia Tulier. On holidays, he cooked for low-income neighbors and those who were sick at his church. Negron died April 2, 2020, at Lutheran Medical Center at the age of 83. His younger brother, Rafael, who also lived in Sunset Park, died of COVID-19 two weeks later. Negron is survived by three children and several grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: He was the joy of our family and a pillar to the family.
author: Jiyong Lee

hardCodedText: Rafael Negron grew up in Puerto Rico and moved to New York City in his 20s with his brother, William Negron, and their four other siblings. Having lost their parents at a young age, the siblings remained close, according to Negron’s niece, Sonia Tulier, and they cherished family gatherings and reunions. Negron lived near his brother in Sunset Park, Brooklyn, and worked at a door factory. Negron also served as a preacher at a local church. He was “a humble man with a big heart,” Tulier said. During the holidays, he cooked dinners for the poor and showed love for those in need, she added. Negron died April 18, 2020, at the age of 79, two weeks after his brother, William. He is survived by his wife, Christina Negron; three children; and several grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a man of great humility and of God.
author: Jiyong Lee

hardCodedText: Marie Proto lived in Brooklyn her entire life. She raised three sons with her husband, Nicholas. Proto never missed an important event in her family's lives. She was famous for her sense of humor and her infectious laughter, her family said. She was an amazing cook and enjoyed gathering her family together for meals on Sundays. She loved playing bingo and having movie nights with her sister-in-law. Proto died April 5, 2020, at the age of 84 at the New York-Presbyterian Methodist Hospital in Park Slope, Brooklyn.
hardCodedPullquote: When she called, if she didn't get through, she left a singing message. She was always happy and laughing. She never said "goodbye" on the telephone and you could never say it either. We had to tell each other to "take care" or "speak to you soon. And she always told us she loved us.
pullquoteSource: Nicole Julia Proto, granddaughter of Marie Proto

hardCodedText: Jill Brandy Lamas sang with the kind of voice that left her audience with goosebumps, her family says. As a teenager, she gave an unforgettable performance at I.S.195. Years later, people in the neighborhood still recalled her singing, said her brother, Josiah Ivan Lamas. Later in life, Lamas was kind even as she battled medical issues and remained optimistic, through her love of song, her brother said. She died Nov. 18, 2020, at St. Joseph’s Hospital in Yonkers at the age of 41.
hardCodedPullquote: Her walk of life saw so much pain, but it never dimmed her light.

hardCodedText: Originally from Ecuador, Manuel Tito came to the United States in his 20s. Although he arrived knowing little English and had no formal education, his street smarts proved more than sufficient, said his daughter, Mercy Lilliana Tito. Tito worked in several Italian restaurants in Manhattan, learning Italian, English and how to make a variety of dishes, such as pasta with pesto sauce and chicken parmigiana. At home, Tito bucked traditional gender norms and took his four daughters to school, did the laundry and ran errands. After retiring at 55, he grew closer to God, his daughter said, participating in church retreat and prayer groups. He enjoyed cooking for his grandchildren, often asking, “Why go eat outside when I can cook for them?” Tito was proud of his daughters and brothers, his family said. Tito was a resident landlord in Corona, renting out part of his home, and he worked on projects ranging from plumbing and electricity to fixing boilers. His resolve guided the family through tough times, like when tenants didn’t pay their rent or brokering neighborhood domestic disputes, his family said. Tito died May 1, 2020, at Long Island Jewish Forest Hills at the age of 63.
hardCodedPullquote: He won’t call someone to fix things, he would find out what was wrong and how to fix it.
pullquoteSource: Mercy Lilliana Tito, Manuel A. Tito’s daughter
author: Justin Yip

hardCodedText: Born in Puerto Rico, Carmen Cruz moved to New York City with her parents when she was 5 years old and grew up on the Lower East Side. Cruz was proud of her heritage and joined the Young Lords, an activist group, in her 20s to fight for equal access to healthcare and education for Hispanics. After graduating from high school, Cruz was hired at Gouverneur Hospital as a secretary and worked her way up over the course of 38 years to serve as a patient advocate. Her son, Rafael Viera, said Cruz was “a little spicy” and “had an edge to her” because of her passion for her work in underserved communities. Cruz was also an active member of the Church of the Blessed Sacrament and would tease her children for not going to church as often as she did. Cruz became a grandmother while still raising her youngest daughter. Whatever she did for her children, she did for her grandkids, said her daughter, Kristina Cruz. She often doted on her family. One Christmas, her daughter said, the family agreed to a “secret Santa” but Cruz couldn’t help herself and broke the rules, giving presents to everyone. Her house was often full of neighborhood kids and open to friends and family who needed a place to stay. Cruz died April 8, 2020, at the Long Island Jewish Medical Center at the age of 74. She is survived by 10 grandchildren and great-grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: She was very youthful at heart. We know that this was a loss because of COVID and not because of anything else. She should’ve been here with us still for many years.
pullquoteSource: Kristina Cruz, daughter of Carmen Cruz
author: Rachel Ruggera

hardCodedText: Joel Dunn was born and raised in Brooklyn by a single mother. His childhood in Coney Island was hard-scrabble, said his son, James Dunn. He had a dark sense of humor, a passion for collecting coins, fixing up old cars and a commitment to his word, James said. After his wife died in 1998, Joel raised James on his own. “He always tried to do the best for me,” James said. Joel taught him to build his own bicycles and enrolled him in the Boy Scouts and hockey. “I was probably one of the worst players, but you would never know it by my dad watching me play. He was one of the only ones screaming.” Joel worked for the MTA for 32 years and did everything from cleaning the stations to renewing subway tracks. In 2015, as he was retiring, James passed the MTA’s entry exam and began his own underground career. Joel was honest about the challenges his son would face on the job but proud that a second generation was following in his footsteps. Like hundreds of other MTA employees, James was infected with COVID-19. Although he recovered, his father, with whom he shared a home in Marine Park, got worse. Joel, who had a pre-existing heart condition that required a stent and blood thinners, died at Mount Sinai Brooklyn on April 11, 2020, at the age of 68.
hardCodedPullquote: My dad said, ‘You’ll be remembered by two things: Your name and your word.’
author: Eleanor Cummins

hardCodedText: “You’re gonna come over for a barbeque.” That’s how everyone in Carlos Alfredo Fernandez’s large family remembers him manning the barbeque and inviting everyone over no matter the time of the year. And at those parties, he was always dancing and singing along, even when he didn’t know the words to the song, his family said. “He thought he could sing but he couldn’t,” said his daughter, Tiffany Romero. Fernandez came from a big family – he had 18 brothers and sisters and his family was featured in a local daily newspaper in the Dominican Republic for its size. He kept in touch with each of them, calling his children at least once a week. Fernandez died May 11, 2020, from COVID-19 in Queens. He was 63 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: Every day at night he would make phone calls to everyone in the family. If anyone ever needed anything, he was there. No matter who or what, he was there.
pullquoteSource: Tiffany Romero, Carlos Alfredo Fernandez’s daughter
author: Mayuri Mei Lin

additionalNotes: Need to check on last name; might be hyphenated, might not be. From what I can tell, not in newspapers or online obituaries. Only source was his granddaughter.

hardCodedText: Seymour “Sy” Collins was born in London, England, and immigrated to New York City at the age of 15. As a young adult, he signed up to work as a New York City EMT. On Sept. 11, 2001, he helped Harlem Hospital Station 18 respond to the terrorist attack. After 9/11, Collins’ daughter, Regina Barnett, said her father developed chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, fought back prostate cancer twice and developed heart disease after being exposed to toxins at Ground Zero. Though he suffered physically after the attack, Barnett says her father remained a stellar cook and was the center of attention at every family gathering. Later in life, Collins taught at FDNY High School for Fire & Life Safety. He eventually retired and moved into the Golden Gate Rehabilitation and Health Care Center in Staten Island. Barnett says she was driving up from North Carolina to visit her dad when he caught COVID-19 at his nursing home and was isolated. He died from complications related to COVID-19 on May 26, 2020, at the age of 63.
hardCodedPullquote: For any occasion, any party, anything, everyone would turn to my dad… he touched everybody’s life.
author: Scooty Nickerson
employer: High School for Fire & Life Safety
underlyingCondition: Cancer, HIV-positive or AIDS, Chronic lung disease

hardCodedText: Warren Bates was born on Long Island, the youngest child with three older step-sisters. At 6-foot-2, Bates was known as a “gentle giant” by those closest to him. He worked as a phone technician at a hospital and was proud of his ability to stay up-to-date with technological advancements in his field. After Bates met Ingrid Cardona at work, the two became friends, were together for nine years and were eventually engaged. He was a loving father, both to his daughter, Yasmin, and to Cardona’s daughter, Aslin Navarro. Bates had a special bond with both girls, and the three were inseparable, his family said. Bates and Cardona had planned to get married in the summer of 2020. In his free time, Bates was the president of his local motorcycle club. He gave up motorcycling when his daughter, Yasmin, was 4 years old and took up making and painting remote-controlled cars. Bates was exposed to COVID-19 while at work, his family said, and died March 22, 2020, at Albert Einstein Hospital in The Bronx.
hardCodedPullquote: He touched the hearts of everyone around him. His passing affects a lot of people and he will be missed very much.
author: Colleen McBride
additionalNotes: next of kin: fianceé Ingrid Cardona

hardCodedText: Maria Victoria Lucas was born in 1958 in Manhattan, a few years after her parents had moved to the city from Puerto Rico. Known as “Vicky” to her family and friends, she married Rufus Michael Woods in 1977 and had three children: Umika, Ebony and Michael. Lucas was passionate about education and proud of her children’s accomplishments, her family said. All three of her children obtained bachelor’s degrees and Umika and Ebony graduated with master's degrees. Lucas worked as a secretary for the New York Public School system until 1990 and, later, became a guidance counselor at Intermediate School 302 after obtaining a master’s degree. She cared deeply for her students and was committed to helping them succeed until her retirement in 2018, her family said. Lucas cared for her mother, Victoria, and her home was a gathering place for extended family to spend time together, including birthdays, holidays, vacations and other celebrations. Lucas also enjoyed gardening, music and watching Telemundo. She visited the hospital frequently to receive treatment for asthma and other respiratory conditions, which is where she contracted COVID-19 in March 2020, her family said. Lucas was admitted to Brookdale University Hospital Medical Center and died two weeks later on April 2, 2020, at the age of 61. She is buried with her father at Cypress Hill Cemetery.
hardCodedPullquote: She was always willing to help you out, she was a very caring and family-oriented person.
pullquoteSource: Ramon Lucas, Maria Victoria Lucas’ brother
author: Colleen McBride
additionalNotes: next of kin: Ramon Lucas

hardCodedText: Candida Caraballo was born in Guayanilla, Puerto Rico, the youngest of 16 children. In 1944, she married Alfonso Caraballo and the couple moved to Brooklyn in 1957. The couple returned to Puerto Rico temporarily before settling in New York City. Candida adapted to life in the U.S., learning to cook lasagna dinners while continuing to make traditional Puerto Rican dishes such as pateles. She had 13 children, 20 grandchildren, 33 great-grandchildren and 11 great-great-grandchildren, who referred to her affectionately as “Candy” or “Ma.” In her downtime, Candida enjoyed watching Jeopardy, buying scratch-offs and reading the newspaper from front to back. She often peered up from the paper to ask her kids: “Can you believe this happened?” Candida and Alfonso retired to Puerto Rico in 1983 and returned to New York in 2007 due to Alfonso’s advanced Alzheimer’s. Candida cared for her husband, who died  in 2012. She enjoyed dancing, singing and making her family laugh. She spent the remainder of her life with her youngest daughter, Nilda, and her family. Candida insisted on getting her hair done even amid frequent treatments and visits to the hospital. She died April 16, 2020, at St. John’s Hospital in Far Rockaway at the age of 91.
hardCodedPullquote: The house feels empty without her presence. There is not a day that goes by that she is not mentioned or we laugh often and remember how funny and sharp she was until the end.
author: Colleen McBride
underlyingCondition: Chronic kidney disease (and/or undergoing dialysis), Chronic lung disease
additionalNotes: next of kin: Nilda Dorta

hardCodedText: Luis Fernando Marulanda immigrated to the United States from Colombia when he was 22 years old. For much of his life, Marulanda worked for New Jersey Transit and New York Waterways, according to a Facebook post by New Jersey Gov. Phil Murphy. On Sept. 11, 2001, in the aftermath of the terrorist attacks, Marulanda piloted a ferry that transported commuters back home across the Hudson River. Marulanda died on April 27, 2020. He was 63. He is survived by two children, two brothers and three sisters, according to an obituary published by Mack Memorial Home.
author: Scooty Nickerson
employer: New Jersey Transit and NY Waterways

hardCodedText: Ada Ficarra was born in Sicily, Italy, during World War II. At the age of 9, she immigrated to New York City with her mother and two siblings. Upon arriving in Brooklyn, Ficarra reunited with her father who was a local fisherman, according to her obituary in the Orlando Sentinel. At 18, Ficarra married an Italian police officer from her home village in an arranged marriage. The couple returned to Queens. On Sept. 11, 2001, Ficarra was working at Guardian Insurance near the World Trade Center. She recalled her office shaking when the plane crashed and black smoke filling the sky outside. Two years later, Ficarra retired to Florida, in part, due to the trauma from the attacks. In 2018, she moved to an assisted living facility. Ficarra was a cancer survivor who suffered from lupus and pulmonary issues, conditions that made her more vulnerable to the coronavirus. Ficarra died on April 26, 2020, according to the Orlando Sentinel. She was 79.. Ficarra is survived by three children and six grandchildren.
author: Scooty Nickerson
underlyingCondition: Chronic lung disease, Unlisted immune deficiency

hardCodedText: Robert Guida was a man of many talents. Early in life, Guida worked as an FDNY firefighter in Brooklyn and Staten Island, according to an obituary in the Staten Island Advance. Guida helped respond to the 9/11 terrorist attacks but was forced to retire early after being injured in a car crash. Guida also acted in plays and a movie, and became a member of the Screen Actors Guild. He also served as the editor in chief of RG magazine, an art and pop culture magazine, which bears his initials and stands for “really great.” Guida died April 23, 2020, at Staten Island University Hospital at the age of 56.
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: Ronnie Cordero, a veteran of the U.S. Marine Corps, joined the fire department in Little Falls, N.J., in 1980 and rose through the ranks, eventually becoming assistant chief. Cordero was a responder at Ground Zero on Sept. 11, 2001, according to a Facebook post by New Jersey Gov. Phil Murphy. Cordero died April 22, 2020, at the age of 61, according to an obituary posted on Gaita Memorial Home’s website.
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: FDNY Fire Marshal Michael Hankins met his wife, Victoria Burton, while working at Ground Zero in the aftermath of the 9/11 terrorist attack, according to NBC News. Burton was a crime scene investigator. The pair started dating a year later and married in 2010. Hankins was later diagnosed with a 9/11-related illness. He retired from the FDNY after 25 years of service. In retirement, Hanks helped train local Queens basketball and football youth athletes. In early March 2020, Hankins tested positive for COVID-19 and was admitted to a hospital, according to NBC. He died April 2, 2020, at the age of 69.
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: Theodore “Ted” Monette Jr. responded to many American crises as an Army veteran and official for the Federal Emergency Management Agency. He served as a colonel in the Army during Vietnam and the Gulf War. In the aftermath of the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks, Monette ran FEMA’s rescue and recovery efforts at Ground Zero, according to the Boston Globe. When Hurricane Katrina struck New Orleans in 2005, he helped guide FEMA’s response. Monette grew up in Chicopee, Mass., where he met his wife of 53 years, Katherine (Dziok) Monette, according to his obituary in MassLive. Monette tested positive for COVID-19 while living in Holyoke Soldiers’ Home in Holyoke, Mass. Monette died on March 30, 2020, at Holyoke Medical Center, according to MassLive. He was 74 years old.
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: Sgt. Anthony Caggiano joined the NYPD in 1990, and retired in 2019 after serving in the community affairs section, according to the Sergeants Benevolent Association. On Sept. 11, 2001, Caggiano was working with the 81st precinct in Bedford-Stuyvesant. He was called to respond to an incident on the Lower East Side and watched the South Towers collapse from a distance, according to the Brooklyn Reporter. Caggiano and his colleagues raced to the crash site and saw the North Tower collapse. Caggiano died April 4, 2020, from complications caused by COVID-19, according to the SBA.
hardCodedPullquote: He was truly a wonderful person and I extend my deepest and heartfelt #condolences.
pullquoteSource: Nilda Hofmann, Chief of the Community Affairs Bureau, NYPD
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: Travis Williams could be found playing basketball at the park in Richmond Hill, Queens, joking with his sister about the Golden State Warriors or falling asleep with the NBA on in the background. He had a nickname for everyone, said his sister, Tonia Williams. One of 10 siblings, he’d call his brothers “Kobe” or “LeBron” and dub people in the neighborhood “Shaquille O’Neal.” When Williams was a child, doctors said he would never walk without braces due to a disability. Yet he danced at his senior prom and his family’s New Year’s Eve parties. Partial to the Notorious B.I.G. and Busta Rhymes, Williams also listened to Christmas music year-round and insisted on leaving the tree up until his birthday at the end of January. Williams loved deeply and took every opportunity to show it, his sister said. He would give her a kiss on the cheek and say, “I like you, Tonia!” because he had trouble saying the word “love.” Williams died April 10, 2020, at Queens General Hospital. He was 33 years old. His sister left the Christmas tree up in his honor for a year after his death.
hardCodedPullquote: You can have a bad day and you sit next to Travis...and whatever I was going through doesn’t even matter because [he] makes the day so much better.
pullquoteSource: Tonia Williams, sister of Travis Williams
author: Rachel Ruggera

hardCodedText: John Crowe was born in the Bronx and graduated from Dewitt Clinton High School. After serving in the U.S. Navy, Crowe joined the NYPD, retiring as a lieutenant. At the NYPD, Crowe worked with his cousin, Heidi Higgins-Sermabekian. She remembers him as a friendly, fun-loving supervisor who inspired officers who worked under him. On Sept 11, 2001, Crowe was working with the Department of Homeland Security in downtown Manhattan when the Twin Towers collapsed. After responding to the attacks, Crowe beat cancer twice, Higgins said, and suffered from chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Higgins said the illnesses may have been triggered by his work at Ground Zero, which involved searching through the hazardous rubble for survivors. Crowe died December 7, 2020, at the age of 77.
hardCodedPullquote: [John was] well liked, well respected, just a stand up guy, a real cops’ cop.
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: David Stone served as an EMT with the New York City Fire Department for 30 years, retiring as a lieutenant. He was assigned to FDNY Station 26, where he trained hundreds of new recruits, including FDNY Capt. Lorena Conception-Martinez. Stone was a strict but effective instructor who cared deeply about those he trained, Conception-Martinez remembers. “Every time I got promoted he made it a point to go to every one of my ceremonies,” Conception-Martinez said. Although Stone helped respond to the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks, he did not talk openly about his experience, she added. After retiring from the FDNY, Stone served as a safety, security and emergency preparedness specialist in Rockland County, N.Y. Stone died April 28, 2020, at the age of 67.
hardCodedPullquote: He was always there for me, especially once I became an officer … He taught me the dos and don’ts and how to and how to be fair.
pullquoteSource: FDNY Capt. Lorena Concepcion-Martinez, David Stone’s former colleague
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: George E. Wolf was born on November 16, 1927, into a German-speaking, middle-class Jewish family in Brno, Czechoslovakia. Under threat of persecution by the Nazis, Wolf’s family escaped the country the night before Kristallnacht, or the night of broken glass, and found refuge in Switzerland. Wolf worked at the American consulate in Zurich during World War II, witnessing the Nuremberg trials in 1946 as a translator. He then worked in a Cold War intelligence project for the U.S. Army in Germany. Wolf emigrated to New York City and transitioned to the textile industry, launching a fashion manufacturing business. After the business closed in 2005, he was forced to pivot and found a way to help fellow Holocaust survivors through the Blue Card, the country’s only non-profit organization dedicated to providing financial assistance to low-income Holocaust survivors. In his spare time, Wolf organized concerts for the elderly with Juilliard students. He took care of his wife, Beth, née Horelick, until she died in 2015. Wolf contracted COVID-19 and died on June 28, 2020, at Dawn Greene Hospice at Mary Manning Walsh in Manhattan. He was 92.
author: Colleen McBride
additionalNotes: George Wolf escaped the Nazi occupation of Czechoslovakia. Was considered an extremely welcoming neighbor and he opened his 16th-floor apartment on Central Park West, to friends, many of them fellow tenants he had met in the laundry room or lobby.

hardCodedText: Roderick Paulus loved toys and games. When he wasn’t at work, he went to conventions like Toy Fair and Play NYC and recorded interviews with toymakers for his website, ToyMasters Video Magazine. Paulus was born in Brooklyn to immigrant parents from Trinidad. He started working in the mailroom of an office building on Wall Street as a teenager in the 1980s. There, he met his best friend, Anita Perry, and the pair remained close for more than three decades, spending Christmas together almost every year. Paulus was a godfather to Perry’s children and gifted them with his favorite toys. “It brought him joy,” she said. He continued working during the pandemic, Perry said. Paulus died on April 18, 2020, at the age of 56.
hardCodedPullquote: He had a smile that would just melt your heart.
author: Josh Merchant

hardCodedText: Born in Bangladesh, Tapan Barua began his career working for the United Nations World Food Programme after graduating from Lalmai Government College and Raozan Government College. He was later selected for the diversity immigrant visa program and moved to New York City in 1995. Barua worked as a taxi driver and loved meeting new people and hearing their stories. He went back to school to further his career and obtained a certification in paralegal studies from the City University of New York. His warm and empathetic nature lifted the moods of those around him, said his son, Joy Barua. He was a practicing Buddhist who dedicated his life to helping those in need, from donating a portion of his income to support farmers in Bangladesh to caring for his chronically-ill wife of 30 years, his family said. Barua died Dec. 22, 2020, at the age of 60. He is survived by his wife, Minu Barua; his son, Joy Barua; and many family members in Bangladesh.
hardCodedPullquote: He will be missed dearly forever, and never forgotten, and our hearts will remain broken.
author: Molly Wilde

hardCodedText: Accursio Zagara was born in 1933 in Sciacca, Sicily, the second of seven children to the late Leonardo and Giovanna Zagara. In the winter of 1964, Zagara immigrated to America, accompanied by his first wife, Vita Oliveri Zagara and their daughter, Joanne (both of whom predeceased him). They moved to Bensonhurst, Brooklyn, reuniting with parents, younger siblings, and good childhood friends. An Italian navy veteran, Zagara worked as a longshoreman at Pier 3 in Brooklyn. He later worked long hours at the Sciacca Social club and Societa Figli Di Ragusa in Brooklyn, taking on double shifts to provide for his family until he was admitted to the hospital, said his daughter, Christina Daleo. Zagara found joy in sharing what he earned. He gave his children and grandchildren money during the holidays and never hesitated to provide financial support to family members in need. Whether playing cards with his grandkids or visiting relatives in Sciacca, Italy, Zagara loved spending time with family. He died Dec. 25, 2020, at Maimonides Hospital in Brooklyn at the age of 87. He leaves behind his wife of almost 50 years, Giuseppa Piazza Zagara; daughters Maria, Donna, Christina Daleo; his sons-in-law and nine grandchildren: Maria, Elissa, Marisa, Antonio, Joseph, Nicholas, Anthony, Marco and Alexia.
hardCodedPullquote: My dad was the most hardworking person I knew and I’m so grateful that I got to be by his side during his last moments.
author: Molly Wilde
additionalNotes: Died in Maimonides hospital in Brooklyn

employer: City of New York CUNY at Bronx Community College

hardCodedText: Paul Lindner taught theology and ran the music and chess clubs at St. Mary’s School in Manhasset, Long Island, where he was adored by students, said his niece, Ellen. Knowing that some of his students might approach theology with some skepticism, Lindner invented “biblical baseball,” a game that brought an interactive approach to learning about the Bible. Linder also served as the train monitor at St. Mary’s, escorting students to the station in the morning. He also taught theology as an adjunct professor at St. John’s University. Outside of the classroom, Lindner was a doting father,  Ellen said, spending countless hours with his son, Pauli, who was diagnosed early on with severe autism. “He rose to the challenge with the utmost dedication,” she said. Lindner cared for his son with the help of his ex-wife, Jo Anne, with whom he remained close until his death. Lindner died Jan. 10, 2021, at the Long Island Jewish Hospital in Queens. He was 67.
hardCodedPullquote: He was an all around wonderful man to be in the presence of.
author: Zosia Czerwinski

additionalNotes: Info provided by friend, not family member; will attempt to get info from family

hardCodedText: After living through World War II, Marine veteran Robert Brogan settled in New York City and raised a family with his wife, Dorothy. He was a crooning fan of Frank Sinatra, according to his family, and “greeted everyone with a smile and a ‘How are you doing, babe?’” said Colleen Constantino, Brogan’s daughter. “If that person responded with any type of problem, he would sit and listen and offer a helping hand.” After his health declined, Brogan, who had dementia, moved to New York State Veterans’ Home at St. Albans in Queens. On April 13, 2020, he died at the facility at the age of 93.
hardCodedPullquote: I wish I could have held his hand in his last days and sang to him.
author: Dean Russell

hardCodedText: Stephen Durnin loved a good Western. He would spend hours listening to country singer Ray Price or watching John Wayne and Clint Eastwood, according to Durnin’s family. It may have been his love of rough-and-tumble icons that inspired him to join the Marines as a teenager, his family said. After serving in the Korean War, Durnin settled in Greenwich Village and spent decades as a doorman in Chelsea, said his niece, Colleen Hanley. When Durnin’s health started to decline and he began to show signs of dementia, he moved to New York State Veterans’ Home at St. Albans, Queens. On April 22, 2020, Durnin died at the home at the age of 85.
hardCodedPullquote: He was hilarious … almost like a fictional character but so much more than that.
pullquoteSource: Colleen Hanley, niece of Stephen Durnin
author: Dean Russell

hardCodedText: Eileen Ruiz was born in 1947 in Guayanilla, Puerto Rico, as the oldest of three children. In her early teens, she moved to the East Tremont neighborhood of the Bronx with her parents and siblings. She attended Benjamin Franklin High School in the Bronx and Boriqua College in Manhattan, where she studied business administration. After college she briefly worked at the Equitable Life Insurance Co., before becoming a medical secretary at the orthopedics department of Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center (now New York-Presbyterian) in Washington Heights in the late 1960s. With the exception of a few years at a private orthopedic practice, Ruiz worked at Columbia Presbyterian for 50 years until her retirement. “She loved her job, and she loved people,” said her niece, Rée Rosado, who described her aunt as “smart, nurturing” and “outspoken.” Ruiz enjoyed swimming, handball, rollerblading and especially salsa dancing, her family said, and she was involved in a women’s empowerment group and proudly stayed connected to her Puerto Rican roots. Ruiz died April 11 at the age of 72 at St. Barnabas Hospital in the Bronx. She is survived by her daughter, son-in-law and granddaughter, as well as her domestic partner of the past 27 years.
hardCodedPullquote: She was like a mom to me and my best friend. She took me under her wing. She was very caring, but also outspoken, honest, and a realist — and I respected her for that. I miss her terribly, my beautiful Aunt Eileen.
author: Talia Bloch
employer: Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center (now New York - Presbyterian)

hardCodedText: Felipe Ortiz knew all the parks in the five boroughs, and he often brought his daughter and his two youngest grandchildren to his favorite parks “for a fresh mindset,” he would say — and to play catch. Felipe Ortiz was born in Puerto Rico in 1933, and he came to New York as a young man. He worked as a security guard and for a law firm. At home, he cooked rice and beans with chicken or pork and had a taste for pies and pastries. He was funny, recalls his granddaughter, Kira, “Him and my grandmother used to crack jokes back and forth and make us laugh.” Ortiz visited Puerto Rico with his family and took them on road trips up and down the East Coast in his minivan. He also liked to ride horses and hunt deer. Ortiz had heart disease and was living at Meadow Park Rehabilitation & Healthcare Center in Queens when he contracted COVID-19. He died there on April 3, 2020, at the age of 86. He is survived by his wife, Damaris Ortiz; his daughter, Genoveva Villanueva; grandchildren Joseph, Melissa, Lawrence, Kira and Gianna; and great-grandchildren TJ., Penny and Makio.
hardCodedPullquote: He was always helping other people out and was known everywhere in New York City.
author: Cathy Shufro

hardCodedText: Liaquat Mohammed was born in 1949 in Trinidad and immigrated to the United States in 1980. With his wife of 48 years, he had three children and six grandchildren. His children remember his “corny” jokes and family road trips, which he could navigate without GPS, but still find himself lost in his own backyard, his family said. The family lived in Brooklyn for 16 years, then purchased a home in Queens, where they lived for 24 years. Liaquat also built a dream home in Trinidad for his wife and was the hub of extended family in both countries. His homes were a proverbial revolving door of friends and family, each receiving “red carpet” treatment, his family said, and gatherings were infused with his strong Muslim faith and a certain mischievious quality: As guests left the house, he would quip, "Thanks for leaving!" Liaquat worked 37 years as a New York City doorman. To the Park Avenue tenants on the Upper East Side, he was humble and indispensable, they said. He remembered birthdays and anniversaries and kept a watchful eye on the children in the building. Liaquat was still working when he contracted COVID 19. He died April 5, 2020, at Long Island Jewish Forest Hills Hospital in Queens at the age of 70.
hardCodedPullquote: He was our hero.
pullquoteSource: Sherina, Sheriza and Riaz Mohammed, Liaquat Mohammed’s children
author: Holly Bell

hardCodedText: William “Billy” Plantt was a man who “loved his family, he loved the lord, he loved helping people,” according to his daughter, Marian Hargett. Plantt worked as a Safety and Security Officer at Kirby Forensic Psychiatric Center. In his Brooklyn neighborhood he was simply known as “Uncle Bill” or “Mr. Bill.” Plantt was an elder in the Abundant Life Church of God in Christ in Brooklyn. He was also part of two fishing groups, Reel Brothers and Hooked for Life, who would take charter trips as far away as Rhode Island and North Carolina. Plantt and his wife Malissa were together since 1979 and they officially married in 1992, having four children and nine grandchildren. He also had three siblings, nieces and nephews, and three godchildren. Plantt died April 2, 2020, at Downstate Hospital at the age of 62.
hardCodedPullquote: He continued to go out of his way for me and for everybody else even during this time (of COVID), when people were being shut in … He was just that kind of person that would lend a helping hand.
author: Abe Kenmore
additionalNotes: His daughter and the NYSCOPBA press release both mention that he did not have PPE, he was working with only gloves at the psychiatric center and according to his union the Office of Mental Health was not issuing masks or allowing workers to bring their own.

hardCodedText: At the age of 86, Theresa “Terry” Collins would perform high kicks in her living room. At 87, when her granddaughter offered to carry heavy bags of cat food for her, she refused and carried them herself. Collins would tell anyone who tried to help: “You know, I’m not an ‘invalid!’ Standing just 4-foot-10, Collins was a “little ball of energy” and was the mother of three, grandmother of seven and great grandmother of two, her family said. “She may have been on this earth for 87 years but was very much young at heart, body and soul,” said a granddaughter, Kim James. “She loved everyone and everyone loved her. How could you not?” On her 87th birthday, Collins asked her family to celebrate with shots of Patrón tequila with coffee liqueur. The family took precautions but she became sick shortly after; She was admitted to Nassau University Medical Center in Queens on the last day of March and died there on April 9, 2020.
hardCodedPullquote: Life has not and will never be the same without her here with us.
pullquoteSource: Kim James, granddaughter of Theresa Collins
author: Cathy Shufro
