hardCodedText: Mildred Bargebuhr Kunin was born in the Bronx in 1932. She graduated from Evander Childs High School with a commercial high school diploma in 1948 and worked as a secretary. She met her husband, Roy, when they worked near each other at 19th and Broadway. They married in 1950, moved to Fresh Meadows in Queens and had two children. Mildred Bargebuhr Kunin moved to Manhattan in 1969 after separating from her husband. She lived there until she moved into a nursing home in the Bronx in 2016. In the early 1960s, she returned to high school to earn a full academic diploma, something that was important to her, her family said. She always had at least one cat or dog and volunteered for years at the New York Foundling and typing braille at her Jewish temple. Her daughter, Nancy Bargebuhr, remembered her as “a truly resilient native Bronx/New Yorker.” She died April 11, 2020, at the age of 88 at Citadel Rehabilitation and Nursing Center in the Bronx.
hardCodedPullquote: My mother had the gift of the heart … my mother just had the gift of being a good human.
pullquoteSource: Nancy Bargebuhr, Mildred Bargebuhr Kunin’s daughter
author: Abe Kenmore
streetAddress: The Citadel Rehabilitation and Nursing Center, 3400-26 Cannon Pl., Bronx, NY
employer: New York Diabetes Association (at one time)
additionalNotes: Nancy Bargebuhr (daughter) said her mother had a Bronx Guardian who was really bad, same one as Elayne Boosler (https://www.thecity.nyc/coronavirus/2020/5/7/21257157/calls-for-probe-of-nursing-home-that-sent-comedian-s-kin-to-wrong-cemetery). It was her second guardian after she was declared a ward of the state four years ago, and Nancy sent a letter to everyone after Mildred died, never heard anything from the guardian. Nancy is a Hospice social worker and says she tried to look into what happened but has been overwhelmed with her own work, is still looking into it.

hardCodedText: Ernest “Ernie” Morency was born in 1939 in Haiti. He came to the United States in 1968, moved to Brooklyn and never left. Morency graduated from New York City College of Technology and met Maryse, his wife of 45 years. Maryse brought a son to the marriage and they had two more children together. Morency worked at the World Trade Center in the 1970s before moving to the New York City Department of Housing Preservation and Development where he worked as an accountant. Funny, generous and dependable, Morency enjoyed bringing people together, said his daughter, Wilda Morency. He was a member of St. Vincent Church where he often attended services on both Saturdays and Sundays. Morency enjoyed reading The New York Times and books on subjects from Haitian politics and global affairs to history and self-help. He liked attending Brooklyn Museum’s First Saturday programs and watching the Knicks, even old games — especially from the Patrick Ewing era. Morency died March 23, 2020, at Downstate Hospital in Brooklyn at the age of 82.
hardCodedPullquote: He was just always a problem solver, always solution oriented, if there was any type of conflict, he’d try to find a positive way to help out or to look at the brighter side of things.
author: Abe Kenmore
employer: New York City Housing Preservation and Development
additionalNotes: Submitted by Wilda Morency

hardCodedText: Miriam Stolzenberg was born in the Bronx in 1923. A child of the Great Depression, she attended Walton High School. She met her first husband, Samuel, at the White Roe Resort in the Catskills, and they married in 1946. They had three children: David, Ronni, and Rochelle. A brilliant, organized woman, Stolzenberg had an “iron will,” according to her daughter, Rochelle Stolzenberg. She renounced the role of a homemaker, her family said, returning to school in her 40s while working part-time as a nursery school teacher. She earned two master’s degrees at Hunter College (now Lehman College) — one in early childhood education, the other in reading. A dedicated teacher and union member, Stolzenberg traveled from her home in Roslyn Heights on Long Island to teach in Ozone Park, Queens. Stolzenberg was “indomitable” and she continued driving until the age of 92, her family said. Known as “Mimi” to those close to her, she was feisty, lively, irrepressible and loved to dance, and so was also affectionately nicknamed “the squirrel” at her last residence at The Atria in Riverdale in the Bronx. Though she “had a tough life, and sometimes took that out on the people she loved the most,” she was also generous and “loved fiercely,” according to her daughter. In early April, Stolzenberg tested positive for COVID-19 and received treatment at Columbia Presbyterian Hospital before being transferred to hospice care at Calvary Hospital. She died April 15 at the age of 96. At the time of her death, her daughter Ronni said, “Y’know, the most un-Mimi like thing she could do was die.”
hardCodedPullquote: She was just unbelievably strong. She was this tiny little person who was fierce —  she had strength, grit, balls and determination.
author: Robert Pluma

hardCodedText: Gisele Menard was born in Haiti and, after her father died, money was tight. In 1970, Menard immigrated to the United States, reuniting with her mother and sister who had settled here years earlier. She worked in the Bronx and went to school to become a certified nursing assistant. Menard settled in Queens Village with her then-husband and children, working as a nurse at Franklin Nursing Home in Flushing, Queens. She treated her kid’s friends like they were her own children and almost everyone in Queens Village knew her, said her daughter, Christie Bruno. Menard enjoyed going out and had an eye for food and clothes, luxuries she did not have growing up, her family said. She loved going on cruises — and if you couldn’t find her on the ship, she was at the casino. She enjoyed riding roller coasters into her 60s, loved The Golden Girls and Harlequin novels and “had a hunger to live,” her daughter said. Menard moved to Florida and returned to New York City in 2019. She had early onset dementia, though was still active with a companion. Menard contracted COVID-19 at the early onset of the pandemic. She was admitted to Long Island Jewish Hospital and there was a staff shortage so Gisele’s daughter, Christie, a nurse, helped care for her mother and checked her vital signs until April 10. Gisele Menard died April 11 at the Long Island Jewish Hospital at the age of 67.
hardCodedPullquote: She was such a kind person, and really fun. She always loved life, no matter how tough things were. She was always up for adventure; I had to take vitamins, I couldn’t keep up with her!
author: Robert Pluma

hardCodedText: James Green was born in South Carolina and, shortly after, his family went north, moving to New York to find better jobs. The oldest of 12 children, Green was an athlete, playing football, basketball and baseball, and was a singer, his family said. He was offered a chance to try out for the Dodgers and sang in a Doo-wop group, having been raised on classics from Nat King Cole, especially during the holidays. He “wore his heart on his sleeve,” his brother said, and would often spend Saturday afternoons, in between his shifts working for an electronics company, watching western films with his siblings. Green worked at the electronics store until he retired. He was taken care of by his sister, Audrey, until his death.
hardCodedPullquote: We were doing karaoke before there was karaoke.
author: Neimra Coulibaly

hardCodedText: Jay Goldstein loved Graceland, the Paul Simon album, so much that he made his kids repeatedly watch the videotape of the concert. Loyalty was the quality, his daughter, Rachel, remembers the most about Goldstein; He frequently told his three children and four grandchildren about the value of his lifelong friends. Goldstein loved basketball and although he hadn't played in a long time, he never stopped talking, watching or teaching the sport. Goldstein was 75 years old when he died on May 12 at Columbia Presbyterian Hospital. His family was with him via a video call when he died.
hardCodedPullquote: This incredible man I was lucky to choose as my dad taught me so many things that make me the woman I am today.
author: Mariel Lozada
underlyingCondition: Asthma, Heart condition, Diabetes, High blood pressure

hardCodedText: In 1973, Charles Thorpe stopped a man from taunting two teenage girls at a New Year’s Eve party in Freetown, Sierra Leone. After warding him off, Thorpe, who was 18, escorted the women to their church and left. One of the women was Dorothy Scott. Weeks went by and Scott had forgotten about the encounter. Then, she received a letter from Thorpe telling her how much he liked her. The two exchanged letters until they could meet up again. He proposed in 1979 and they immigrated to the U.S. six months later. The two moved to Queens, where they had two children. “We have quite a history,” said Dorothy Thorpe, his wife of 40 years. Thorpe was soft-spoken and had a preternatural smile on his face, said his friend, Wilfred Taylor. He was also generous, willing to share his last dollar to anyone in need, Taylor said. Thorpe worked as a traffic enforcement agent for the New York City Police Department for 25 years. He was passionate about music, particularly African music, and he collected old albums and records. Thorpe died April 7 at the Staten Island University Hospital at the age of 69. He is survived by his wife, two children and four grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: He enjoyed life and was a good husband.
author: Kynala Phillips

hardCodedText: Ok J. Choi was born and raised in Korea. In the early 1970s, believing that her family would have a better life in the United States, Choi and her husband, Jong Suk Choi, moved to Harlem with their young daughter. Despite hard work, the immigrant experience was not easy for the Chois, her daughter Jiwon said. Ok Choi got into real estate but faced challenges as both a new arrival and a woman of color. She later opened a deli and a butcher shop in Harlem with her husband. Choi was an avid reader and took her daughter “to the Barnes and Noble on 18th Street and let me get a bunch of books,” she said. Choi also enjoyed music. She had an eight-track player in the living room and a collection of cassette tapes, many of which featured classical music. Choi was suffering from dementia and living in a nursing home when she contracted COVID-19 in April. She died May 10 at Interfaith Hospital in Brooklyn at the age of 81.
hardCodedPullquote: She was the fabric of this city.
pullquoteSource: Jiwon Choi, Ok J. Choi’s daughter
author: Catherine Montesi

hardCodedText: In retirement, Gary Jaeger had two passions: travel and spending time with his grandson. A lifelong New Yorker, Jaeger was born in Brooklyn at Bushwick Hospital and spent most of his life in Glendale, Queens. Jaeger was a history buff who enjoyed reading historical fiction novels and visiting historical sites with his family. Over the years, Jaeger took his children, Elizabeth and Gary Jr., to sites throughout the U.S., including several National Parks. One of the last gifts Jaeger gave his grandson was a scratch map of the National Parks. “When most people go on vacation it's a time to relax and rest. Not Daddy,” his daughter said. Jaeger was an important figure in the life of his youngest namesake, Gary III. From rides at Disney World to speaking to Gary’s class on career day, Jaeger was, “always present,” Elizabeth said. Since retiring from his job as a programmer with New York Life Insurance, Jaeger and his wife, Toni, enjoyed traveling the world on cruise ships. They had just returned from one when Jaeger became sick. Jaeger’s family was unable to be with him when he died. They said goodbye over FaceTime. Gary III made a goodbye video for his grandfather that caregivers played for him before he died. Gary Jaeger died on April 14 at the Hospital for Special Surgery, just five months shy of his 49th wedding anniversary. He was 71 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: He was the best grandpa. His absence has left a giant hole.
author: Catherine Montesi

hardCodedText: Juan Andres Ollarvide, from San Luis Potosí, Mexico, was one of five brothers. He immigrated to the United States in 1984 after meeting his wife, Sally, in the Cancun airport. She was trying to rent a car and he was selling transport tickets. He called her the next day and, after two dates, suggested she delay her flight home. “He said, ‘We’re getting along so well, why don’t you stay another week?’” Sally said. She did. A week later she returned to her home in Florida just long enough to pack her bags to move to Mexico. Though Ollarvide had a degree in drafting when he moved to the U.S., some of his first jobs were working at a fruit stand and as a busboy in a hotel restaurant. He eventually started his own drafting company and became an American citizen in 1999. He had been receiving cancer treatment at Memorial Sloan Kettering but was improving when he contracted COVID-19. He played golf twice a week with the same group of friends; was in a men’s tennis league; and ran his business remotely throughout his treatment. Ollarvide was a favorite at his local bar and was described as a jokester, his family said. He often used the hashtag #Juaninamillion on his social media posts, which his family and friends adopted as their own. Ollarvide died April 20 at Harlem Hospital at the age of 60. A friend stenciled #JuanInAMillion on the sidewalk in front of the hospital.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a larger than life jokester who lit up every room he entered.
pullquoteSource: Sally Ollarvide, Juan Andres Ollarvide’s wife
author: Catherine Montesi

additionalNotes: Hispanic/Latino
Obit written by Abe Levine

hardCodedText: Dustin J. Petrie lived and worked in Manhattan’s East Village. A graduate of New York University’s Stern School of Business, Petrie was an entrepreneur whose latest project involved advising startups. He loved travelling and adventure, from rafting in the Colorado River to skydiving, his family said. On Sept. 11, 2001, Petrie was working in downtown Manhattan and narrowly survived the attacks on the World Trade Center. “He worked in the Woolworth Building close to the Towers at that time. He had a meeting there which got postponed at the last minute,” said his mother,, Teri Petrie. He suffered from chronic respiratory issues and PTSD from that day onward, she said. Petrie’s friends jokingly called him the “Mayor of the East Village.” He was an accomplished chef and, when stay-at-home restrictions tightened in New York City in March and April, he went out to deliver meals for friends who were ill. Petrie died April 1 at the age of 39.
hardCodedPullquote: We would like to remember Dustin as the son, brother, and good friend he was, and to forever hold him in our hearts. We sustain ourselves by believing that he is in a better place.
pullquoteSource: John Petrie and Teri Petrie, Dustin J. Petrie’s parents
author: Harpal Singh
additionalNotes: Dustin Petrie's mother, Teri Petrie (terylpetrie@gmail.com), and his father, John Petrie (jmpetrie3@gmail.com), exchanged multiple emails with me.

hardCodedText: Gloria Maria Espertin emigrated from the Dominican Republic more than 30 years ago. She worked in the United States as a caregiver to children. Struggling with recurring health problems, she retired and became a stay-at-home mother. Espertin’s family was an integral part of her life, and she developed relationships with the local Citicare, her church and women from a nearby hair salon. Her family remembers her rice, steak and beans and the songs she would sing to her grandchildren. After visits to her native Dominican Republic, Espertin would bring back traditional dresses for her granddaughter and have sweet plantains ready for her grandson’s visits. She died March 29, 2020, at the age of 65.
hardCodedPullquote: Now that I am a mother myself, I understand all the things she taught me and my siblings. It has helped shape me into the mother I am today. When people talk about how well behaved, kind and polite my children are I have to give her all the credit.
pullquoteSource: Dianna Perez, Gloria Maria Espertin’s daughter
author: Neimra Coulibaly

hardCodedText: Jason Fuchs was never able to come home one final time to see his wife, Myrna Torres. “I am still grieving. This is traumatizing,” Torres said. Fuchs died on March 26, 2020 at Brooklyn Hospital Center after contracting covid-19 at the Goldquest Nursing Home in Crown Heights. He was 77 years old. Fuchs was born in Riverdale in the Bronx and went on to graduate from NYU. He spent much of his adult years working as an executive recruiter in New Jersey. Fuchs then moved to Brooklyn and began working at St. Bonaventure’s Hospital in the Bronx until a workplace accident in which he broke his femur forced him to retire early. Fuchs lived independently until his health took a turn for the worse. He then spent out his remaining days at the Goldquest Nursing home. “He had a magnetic personality. Everybody was drawn to him,” his late wife Myrna said. According to Myrna, he was particularly popular with the ladies. When Myrna first met Fuchs while they were living in Northern New Jersey, Myrna recalls Fuchs received several phone calls from other women in the community. Fuchs leaves behind his beloved wife Myrna, his daughter Jody Thall and five grandchildren.
author: Maxwell Adler
additionalNotes: Obituary by Maxwell Adler

hardCodedText: Evelyn Rivera worked multiple jobs to support her two daughters and never missed a family event, including their monthly family dinner, her daughter said. In 2016, Rivera retired from her job as a custodial worker for the city after more than 20 years. Born and raised in the Bronx, Rivera spent most of her life in the borough. She died April 5 at Bronx Lebanon Hospital. Rivera is survived by her two daughters and two grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: I still have so much to learn from my mom.
author: Maxwell Adler
additionalNotes: Hispanic/Latino

hardCodedText: Born and raised in Mount Vernon, Jonathon Davis was a jack of all trades in Brooklyn. Davis, who died at the age of 36, worked as a mortician, truck driver, boat captain and security officer for the Mount Vernon High School boys basketball team. In 2015, Davis started Cigar Events, a company specializing in throwing cigar-themed cruises. He captained a cigar cruise called the Klondike IX twice a year around the Statue of Liberty for fellow cigar aficionados. Davis, who is survived by his mother, grandmother and uncle, was described by his family as a prankster who spoke several languages and left behind a diverse group of friends.
hardCodedPullquote: He was Bonnie to his grandma Mimi’s Clyde.
author: Maxwell Adler
additionalNotes: Black/African American; Interviewed by Maxwell Adler

hardCodedText: Lucy Nicolelis was born to Greek parents in 1929 in Astoria, where she lived almost her entire life. She was married and had two daughters. “She was a Yiayia and a friend like no other, supportive and loving,” wrote her granddaughter, Stephanie Litsas. She especially enjoyed traveling with her family, to California, Greece, London, Paris, Cairo. Nicolelis was a “self-starter,” who might have a different career, and life, altogether if she had been born in a later generation. Still, Nicolelis was unusually active, her family said; she served on the PTA board, as a translator for Greek immigrants in area hospitals and a volunteer for several causes she believed in. When her husband suddenly died in 1980, Nicolelis set up a scholarship fund in his memory. Because he was a chemist, the scholarship is awarded to an outstanding student in science at St. Demetrios Preparatory School. Today, that fund is named after both of them. Nicolelis died April 15 at the Mount Sinai Queens at the age of 90.
hardCodedPullquote: The thing people will remember the most about her is her dignity, her ready smile and her thoughtfulness. What a great way to be remembered.
author: Natalia Gutiérrez
additionalNotes: She had parkinson's disease. She got infected at a nursing home (they were following all the measures) and was sick only for one week.

hardCodedText: Gabriella Hernandez had a habitual greeting — “Hello, my love” — for those she worked with at EarlyLearn Corona, where she was a family social worker. Hernandez was born in Peru, but used the Italian, not Spanish, spelling of her first name after an Italian grandmother. She came to the U.S. some 30 years ago, and lived in Queens. Hernandez looked out for others, her family and coworkers said, and she was relentless in her advocacy for the children she worked with. Her family remembered her as resourceful, with solutions for any situation. “I’ll always remember the kindness she showed someone she had never met,” said Larry Lutsky, Hernandez’s fiancée. Hernandez died April 13 at the age of 57 in Jamaica Hospital. She is survived by Lutsky and three adult sons.
hardCodedPullquote: Sometimes people [she helped at work] would come up to her on the street and give her a hug and a kiss.
author: Abe Kenmore
additionalNotes: Spoke to her fiance, Larry Lutsky, who said she initially went to Long Island Jewish Hospital, she was discharged shortly before even receiving the results of her COVID test. She went home for a few days and then was taken to Jamaica Hospital as an emergency case, where she died. Lutsky never got her engagement ring back from Jamaica Hospital, it was either lost or stolen.

hardCodedText: Adalberto “Tito” Lebron was born the only son and the oldest of three children in Brooklyn. He grew up in Brownsville and had a special bond with his mother, who retired to take care of him when he became sick with kidney failure. Lebron is remembered by his family as a prankster who, despite his illnesses, looked out for friends, including those on a “dangerous path” and those that were homeless after stints in jail. He and his mother visited California for his 53rd birthday, visiting Hollywood, even though he was on dialysis. His sister kept a journal of all of the measures his doctor tried during his battle with COVID-19. Lebron died March 27 at Cornell Hospital and is survived by his father, two sisters, nephews, nieces and many friends.
hardCodedPullquote: I speak for my son. He is more than a statistic. He’s my son.
author: Carla Canning
additionalNotes: Mother, Digna Lebron

hardCodedText: Clyde William Henry was born in Barbados and, at the age of 17, immigrated to the United States. He worked at Barton’s Candy Factory in Brooklyn for more than 11 years and then as a foreman at United Airlines for more than 27 years. Henry could talk about his job at United Airlines “from morning till night,” according to his daughter, Sheila Sample. Henry, who was a parishioner at Saint George Episcopal Church, particularly enjoyed traveling and considered Hawaii his “home away from home.” Until his illness, he served in the vestry and was a member of the Brotherhood of Saint Andrew. Henry died April 23 at Methodist Hospital in Brooklyn at the age of 90.
hardCodedPullquote: He could tell you any story that happened in his lifetime — he was incredibly witty and smart.
pullquoteSource: Sheila Sample, Clyde William Henry’s daughter
author: Grace Dennis
jobTitle: retired but was the lead foreman at United Airlines

hardCodedText: Elisabeth “Lis” Rubert was one of three children born in Cuba in 1955. The family left their neighborhood of Sancti-Spiritus and immigrated to the United States in 1962 and Rubert attended Hoboken High School before moving out at the age of 18. Described by her brother as a smart saleswoman and investor, Rubert worked at Saks Fifth Avenue in New York City and her clients included Jackie Kennedy, Barbara Streisand and Carol Burnett. When Rubert retired, she devoted her time to caring for her husband, Dale Richard Pon, who was suffering from a degenerative neurological disease. While she cared for him, she told family that she had never been happier. Rupert, an active member of the First Presbyterian Church in Manhattan, died on Easter Sunday at Lenox Health Greenwich Village. Her husband died 17 days later.
hardCodedPullquote: Elisabeth fought hard for what she wanted...she still inspires me. During the last few years of her life we talked about 3 times a week — it’s been rough without those talks. I could always count on her.
author: Colleen McBride
obitSource: First Presbyterian Church of New York
additionalNotes: Next of kin: Edson (brother) edsonrubert@yahoo.com

hardCodedText: Dale Richard Pon was the oldest of four children. His father was a “paper son” — one of thousands of Chinese immigrants who used false documents to become U.S. citizens when the Chinese Exclusion Act severely restricted immigration. Growing up in a family of Chinese-immigrant grocery-store owners, Pon made a name for himself with radio and television advertising work at ABC, CBS and NBC, before moving to New York City to start his own business in 1988. Pon was best known for the “I want my MTV!” ad, which persuaded cable operators to carry the channel and thereby redefined music and video. Pon also worked in radio, where he persuaded Miles Davis to advertise the MJAZ station as “Cool, real cool.” He was also unafraid to ask family members, “What are you doing with your life?”, his brother recalled, and Pon — described as equal parts brash and spontaneous — loved the outspoken, loud and boisterous nature of New York City. Pon and his wife, Elisabeth Rubert, were married in 2007. She died of COVID-19 on Easter Sunday and Pon died April 29 at Lenox Hill Hospital at the age of 75.
hardCodedPullquote: He wasn’t happy unless he was teaching somebody something.
pullquoteSource: Fred Seibert, Dale Richard Pon’s colleague and friend
author: Colleen McBride
underlyingCondition: Unlisted immune deficiency, No underlying conditions
additionalNotes: Next of kin: Tyler Pon (brother)

hardCodedText: In 1969, Chandrakant F. Sheth left Mumbai and immigrated to Woodside, Queens, which he would later call “the best city in the world.” Sheth owned and operated convenience stores and supported his son’s real estate business. He was well known in his Queens community, frequenting the Jain Center of America in Elmhurst; the Jain Temple of New York in New Hyde Park; and, later, the Sunnyside Senior Center and Boulevard Senior Center in Flushing. In the summer, Sheth would take his grandchildren on tours of the city and to play basketball at Little Bush Park, where there is now a memorial bench in his honor. Sheth, who enjoyed talking about philosophy and current events, was “a curious, spiritual, and caring man who embraced new ideas, seeking to participate in the culture around him while also being faithful to his Indian heritage,” said his granddaughter, Sarina S. Noone. Sheth died April 4 at Long Island Jewish Medical Center in New Hyde Park at the age of 85.
hardCodedPullquote: He was proud of his Indian heritage and also a boastful New Yorker — he loved a good slice of pizza and a Knicks game as much as masala dosa and a cricket match.
pullquoteSource: Sarina S. Noone, Chandrakant F. Sheth’s granddaughter
author: Grace Dennis
additionalNotes: https://www.exceedingexpectations.nyc/chandrakant

hardCodedText: A longtime resident of Hempstead on Long Island, Grace Granter had a big heart, family said, and shared it with others. As a volunteer at local animal shelters, Granter was a generous friend, her family said, with a genuine warmth and kindness. She died April 6 at Providence Rest Nursing Home in Brooklyn at the age of 95.
hardCodedPullquote: Grace was a kind, compassionate human who loved animals.
author: Molly Wilde
additionalNotes: Resident of Hempstead, NY. Died at Providence Rest Nursing Home in Brooklyn.

hardCodedText: A longtime resident of Queens, Rosemary C. Guerrero dedicated herself to serving those around her, her family said. As a wife, mother and grandmother, she loved her family and cherished the time they spent together, they said. An avid baker, she was known for her cheesecake and rainbow cookies —  a crowd favorite during the holiday season. She died April 24 at Flushing Hospital in Queens at the age of 73. She is survived by three sons, two grandsons and two granddaughters.
hardCodedPullquote: Heaven truly gained an angel and she will always be in the hearts of those who knew her forever.
pullquoteSource: Cynthia Guerrero, daughter of Rosemary C. Guerrero
author: Molly Wilde
additionalNotes: Died at Flushing Hospital Medical Center in Queens, NY

hardCodedText: Ajaz Bashir Mohammed, who was known as “Bashir” to friends and family, was born and raised in Pakistan and moved to New York City in his early 20s. Mohammed loved his four children and made sure to never leave for work without giving his youngest daughter a hug. Mohammed had an infectious joy and vibrant presence, his family said. “He was the laughter of our family,” wrote his nephew, Idrees Shafi. One day, after being lured by the aroma of mangoes, Mohammed bought a few and brought them to his doctor’s appointment. Unable to eat them himself because of his diabetes, Mohammed offered them to the doctor. Mohammed died April 30 at Maimonides Hospital in Brooklyn at the age of 54.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a loving father, husband, brother, uncle and just a great person overall. Losing him left a huge hole in the hearts of our family and friends and we are going to miss him so much.
pullquoteSource: Idrees Shafi, Ajaz Bashir Mohammed’s nephew
author: Molly Wilde
additionalNotes: Died at Maimonides Medical Center in Brooklyn, NY

hardCodedText: Vidal Cruz was born in Puerto Rico and immigrated to New York City at a young age. He joined his sister and relatives already living in Bushwick, Brooklyn, and later moved to Staten Island. He traveled between New York City, where he worked at a garment factory, and his home in Puerto Rico, where he farmed coffee beans, banana trees and cassava. Cruz died April 2 at Richmond University Medical Center. His sister, Iris Cruz, died of COVID-19 a day earlier, although Vidal didn’t know of his sister’s death. His body was sent back to Puerto Rico as he had wished.
author: Jiyong Lee
photoSource: His great niece, Katherine C Ramos

additionalNotes: https://www.paullanefuneral.com/memorials/sean-artis/4185486/ (Funeral Home website but w/out obituary)

hardCodedText: Iris Cruz was born in Puerto Rico in 1942 and immigrated to New York City in the 1960s with her sister, settling in Bushwick, Brooklyn. Cruz worked at a garment factory until she became a certified childcare worker in her late 40s. She was loved by her neighbors and babysat children, including her great nieces. "She had a strong character and was like my second mom," said Katherine Ramos, Cruz’s great niece. Cruz embraced her Puerto Rican heritage, cooking her signature dish — pasteles — and singing and dancing to salsa. She never missed Spanish mass on Sundays. Cruz died April 1 at the age of 77 in her home in Brooklyn. The next day,her brother, Vidal, also died of COVID-19 at a hospital on Staten Island. Cruz is survived by her husband, three children, four grandchildren and a great-grandson.
hardCodedPullquote: She had a really good heart. If you needed her help, she was there.
pullquoteSource: Katherine C. Ramos, great-niece of Iris Cruz
author: Jiyong Lee

hardCodedText: David Perez was born in 1945 in New York City to Puerto Rican parents and grew up in Spanish Harlem. He later lived in the Bronx and worked as a plumber until his retirement. He enjoyed watching Westerns with John Wayne, listening to oldies music and going to casinos. Whenever he won, his family and friends knew because he would share his winnings. During the Vietnam War, Perez served in the Marine Corps infantry and worked as a cook. He received the veterans’ benefits due to medical conditions caused by his exposure to Agent Orange. “He was not one to complain,” said his son, David Perez. For many years, he was involved in “Toys for Tots,” a project run by the U.S. Marine Corps Reserve. He died May 12 at the age of 74 at Jack D. Weiler Hospital of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine. Perez is survived by his wife of 50 years, Josephine; their two children, David and Joselyn; and two granddaughters, Brittany and Lisandra.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a man who was always willing to help.
pullquoteSource: David Perez, son of David Perez
author: Jiyong Lee

hardCodedText: Born in Puerto Rico, Marilu Lopez Santiago dropped out of high school to care for her mother, who was battling kidney failure. In 1984, Santiago immigrated to New York along with her two sons, Pablo and Omar, and her daughter, Ruth. Her other two daughters, Rosa and Beverly, later joined them after finishing school. Santiago became an active member of her new community, serving as the usher at her Christian church and doing missionary work, Santiago was intent on practicing her Christian faith. “Mama,” as she was known by her grandkids, was famous for her rice and peas, and pork chops. Santiago enjoyed bowling, exploring Governor’s Island, riding the Staten Island ferry and Christmas, when the Lopez family would come together to play a game that involved taking turns opening gifts while wearing mittens. Santiago died April 5 at the age of 69.
hardCodedPullquote: Her smile was the first thing anyone noticed, she was always happy.
pullquoteSource: Omar Lopez, Marilu Lopez Santiago’s son
author: Seamus Kilgarriff

hardCodedText: Beverly Rubock Gray was born in the Bronx and grew up in Glen Oaks, Queens, along with her sister, Nancy. Gray went on to work as a paralegal and, after the shooting at Stoneman Douglas High School in Parkland, Florida, in 2018, Gray and her husband, Albert, both in their 60s, protested in T-shirts that read: “I am defiant.” Gray was “all about her family,” according to her granddaughter, Lauren Gray. Gray spent her weekend mornings drinking coffee and playing Scrabble against her grandchildren, and didn’t let them win. A constant source of advice for her family, Gray was particularly proud of passing on her Jewish heritage to her family. She died March 26 at the age of 70.
hardCodedPullquote: There was no difference between being one of her grandchildren and one of her actual children, she was like a second mother.
author: Seamus Kilgarriff

hardCodedText: A lifelong New Yorker, Lisa G. Mack loved science fiction. “I was really little, and she taught me the Star Trek sign,” said Stefanie Alleyne, Mack’s niece. Mack was a devoted member of her church and an avid reader. Another niece, Francia Alleyne, recalled Mack’s support while she juggled full-time work and graduate school. “She really knew how to live well, and she did everything she could to teach us how to enjoy life,” Alleyne said. Mack was famous for her holiday cookies. Every year around the holidays, she delivered a tin of home-baked cookies to her extended family — a tradition that spanned 15 years. “Every year got better and better,” Alleyne said. Mack died March 3 at Kings County Hospital. She was 61.
hardCodedPullquote: She was feisty and fun. She was proud of her nieces and nephews. She loved tremendously.
pullquoteSource: Stefanie Alleyne, Lisa Mack’s niece and goddaughter
author: Eli Frankel
additionalNotes:
From Goddaughter Stefanie Alleyne:

She was feisty and fun. She was proud of her nieces and nephews. She loved tremendously. Her signature were her holiday cookies. Every year we looked forward to a tin pan full of various Christmas cookies she would make. She had been making cookies for over 15 years. Each year got better and better. It would be great coming home to a house that smelled like cookies, and getting to sample various ones.

hardCodedText: Born in Harlem Hospital, Tracey M. Murchison was a beloved mother and grandmother who worked as a housekeeper for most of her life before falling ill six years ago. “She was so sweet — kind-hearted, loving, she’d give you the shirt off her back,” said her daughter, Lakecia. Remembered as someone “with a glow” who loved to cook and bake, Murchison fought off pneumonia two years ago, but died July 4 at the age of 55 at the ForestView Center for Rehabilitation and Nursing in Forest Hills. Murchison had spent her life in the Bronx, Queens and Littleton, N.C., before returning to live in Jamaica, Queens, in 2012 to care for her own mother. Her 8-year-old granddaughter, Arianna, “was her pride and joy. She did everything with her. She was her heart.”
hardCodedPullquote: She was so encouraging, and motivating. No matter what she was going through, you would’ve never known, because she was always there for everybody else.
pullquoteSource: Lakecia Murchison, daughter of Tracey M. Murchison
author: Thomas J. Walsh
underlyingCondition: High blood pressure, Chronic kidney disease (and/or undergoing dialysis)

hardCodedText: Food. Travel. Books. Those words best describe Robert Zolnerzak, his family and friends say. Growing up, Zolnerzak, loved books. His sister, Rita Robinson, who was 11 years younger, said he would read to her. Years later, Robinson said he paid her tuition so she could attend college. By then, Zolnerzak had left their hometown of Akron, Ohio and moved to New York City to pursue a master’s degree in physics from Columbia University. A job offer from IBM enticed him to leave school. Zolnerzak worked as a coder and professional indexer. As a result, “nobody wanted to play Trivial Pursuit with him,” Robinson said. Zolnerzak, who lived in Brooklyn Heights, traveled the world, his sister said. When he got home, he’d regale his friends with slideshows of his global escapades. During his final days in the hospital, he enjoyed hearing from those same friends. “He wanted people to talk to him and call him,” Robinson said. “Sometimes, you couldn’t get through to him on the phone because the line was so busy.” Zolnerzak died March 26 at NYU Langone Hospital at the age of 83, days shy of his 84th birthday.
author: Kirstin McCudden
jobTitle: retired, former IBM coder; independent indexer
additionalNotes: Sister only surviving family
Place of Death: Fieldston Nursing Home

hardCodedText: Randip S. “Bobby” Minhas was a U.S. citizen by birth; His parents emigrated from India in the 1960s so his father could pursue an engineering degree at the University of Iowa. Minhas, who spoke Punjabi at home despite English being his first language, became a home inspector and later settled in Queens. He married his wife, Simi, when he was 21 and she was 19. Minhas was especially supportive of his family, Simi Minhas said, caring for his mother-in-law during a bout with cancer and supporting his wife’s career “every step of the way.” Minhas’s family said he began running a high fever after a visit to a grocery store. After 28 days on a ventilator at LIJ Medical Center in Queens, Minhas’s oxygen levels plummeted and, just before he died, he asked his wife via FaceTime to “stay a little longer.” He died at the age of 49 and is survived by Simi, the principal of Queens College School of Math, Science and Technology, and his 26-year-old daughter, Supnah. Simi Minhas is holding onto her husband’s ashes and plans to bury them in her backyard and plant a tree there. “I’m not ready yet to give up his last memory,” she said.
hardCodedPullquote: He was an amazing man. A loving husband, father and son. He was caring, kind and generous. I am what I am because of him.
pullquoteSource: Simi Minhas, wife of Randip S. “Bobby” Minhas
author: Harpal Singh

hardCodedText: Fareeda Ann Kadwani was born in Mumbai, India, where she became a teacher and taught for 15 years. She married her husband, Arif Kadwani, in 1966 and the couple later immigrated to the Bronx with their children. While in New York, Fareeda received her bachelor’s and master’s degrees in Early Childhood Education, and went on to work as a paraprofessional and then a teacher until her retirement. She set time aside to volunteer as a tutor for children in the Bronx and made it a goal to cultivate an appreciation for Indian culture amongst her friends and students. Fareeda died at the age of 75 on April 28. She is survived by her husband of more than 50 years and their two children, Obaid and Qurrat.
hardCodedPullquote: She traveled the world and she had many lifelong friendships in the U.S.

hardCodedText: Arlene Schneidman’s love of animals was infectious. She volunteered at the Bronx Zoo for more than 30 years, leading tours, doing odd jobs and speaking at local schools. ''When I come here, the rest of the world doesn't exist,'' she told the New York Times in 1987. At that time, Schneidman was helping care for Cleopatra, a baby Nile hippopotamus, who she compared to “an enormous puppy.” In her free time, Schneidman traveled to see animals in their natural habitats, including on an African safari. At home, Schneidman dedicated herself to raising her three sons, tending to her grandchildren and caring for her husband, who had Type 1 diabetes and other illnesses throughout his life. Her grandson, Jon Schneidman, remembers her as unique in her ability to relate to other people’s problems — and to get to the heart of the matter. “She wasn’t big on euphemisms or innuendo or talking around a subject,” he says. “For better or for worse, she was always direct.” After her husband’s death, Schneidman lived at Hebrew Home in Riverdale. A lifelong Yankees fan, Schneidman enthusiastically shared her thoughts on the games, the management, and the players with her family over text. She died April 14 at St. Joseph's Medical Center in Yonkers.
hardCodedPullquote: She was easy to be known … because she wasn’t hiding any parts of herself.
author: Eleanor Cummins

hardCodedText: Elsa Gomez was born and raised in the Dominican Republic. When she was in early 20s, Gomez left her children behind and moved to Brooklyn to work in a factory. “She would go to the store and it was ‘chicken, chicken, chicken’ — that was the only word in English that she knew,” says daughter Clara Paris, with a laugh. In 1972, her kids were able to join her. “It was a different world for us to come here, but it was a lot of opportunity,” Paris says. Gomez eventually became a home attendant. Her family, which also includes eight grandchildren and 15 great-grandchildren, remembers her as warm, caring and ready with a smile. Gomez took pride in the fact that three of her four children joined the U.S. military. But she also made sure to return to the Dominican Republic every few years. Gomez, who lived at a senior housing facility near Fort Tryon Park, died April 13 at St. Joseph's Medical Center in Yonkers.
hardCodedPullquote: She loved this country and she also loved her country.
author: Eleanor Cummins

hardCodedText: Arthur C. Hurwitz lived in New York City for most of his life. A graduate of the University of Massachusetts Amherst, he was college friends with members of the band, Dinosaur Jr., and appeared on their first album cover. He had a keen interest in politics, pop culture and rock music, his family and friends said. According to his friend, Victor Ortega, Hurwitz had “a true love and appreciation for language,” and frequently spoke about his time studying in Egypt, where he became fluent in Arabic. Hurwitz later worked as an immigration consultant for architecture firms. He could often be found surrounded by stacks of documents while meeting with clients in public spaces. He loved socializing in coffee shops, cafes and hookah bars, and was a regular at the Hungarian Pastry Shop and Caffe Dante. He was a “really gregarious New York guy,” Ortega said. “Everyone would want to talk with him.” Hurwitz died March 23 at the age of 54.
hardCodedPullquote: [He had] a deep loving and understanding and respect for New York as a place where the most complex and eccentric parts of American life happen.

hardCodedText: Lila Charlotte Swedelson Weissman was born in Brooklyn in 1936. After a stint as a hospital administrator at Coney Island Hospital, she became an occupational therapist for children, working in schools across the city and Yonkers as well as providing home care. Her husband, Stanley, proposed after their first date; she declined. Within six months, however, Stanley had moved in, with a borrowed shotgun, after someone tried to break into Weissman’s apartment. They were together until his death, and had two children, Dana and Larry. Weissman would often wake up at 5 a.m. to do the books for her husband’s two animal hospitals before a full day of therapy. She continued running one of the hospitals after his death. Weissman was active in multiple causes, stylish and a lover of Irish music, her family said — she enjoyed dancing at Slainte in the Bowery on Sunday afternoons. Although she lived much of her life in Westchester and Yonkers, she had moved back to New York City a few years ago. Weissman died April 11 at the age of 83 at Columbia Memorial Hospital in Hudson.
hardCodedPullquote: She was particularly drawn to working with children … (with) children, there’s all the hope in the world, and she could see real progress.
pullquoteSource: Dana Weissman-Scali, Lila Charlotte Weissman’s daughter
author: Abe Kenmore

hardCodedText: Originally from South Carolina, Elias Melton followed his sister north in the 1970s before eventually settling down in Springfield Gardens, Queens. Once settled, Elias became a familiar member of the community, installing doors and windows from his yellow company truck. His daughter Trenia Campbell, remembers how neighborhood kids would run after the yellow truck, yelling, “Mr. Lane.” When not running his construction business, Elias was also the president of his local chapter of the Freemasons, often traveling across the country to attend and run meetings. Melton, who died on Easter Sunday at the age of 82 in the Brooklyn Queens Nursing Home, always found his way back to his neighborhood, though, his family said, where he could be found listening to jazz records and spending time with his wife and children.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a neighborhood man … with a big sense of humor. Everyone knew Mr. Lane.

hardCodedText: Samuel W. Arbeeny spent his life on Staten Island. The oldest of six children, he grew up in Oakwood, graduated from New Dorp High School and married his high school sweetheart, Linda Filippelli. After working as a sheet-metal mechanic, Arbeeny founded the Verrazano Fence Co. and ran it for 40 years. Arbeeny’s daughter, Danielle Messina, said her father loved going to the Jersey Shore to watch doo-wop groups and was a league bowler at Rab’s in New Dorp. He loved fishing and caught a record-breaking 48-pound bass in the Verrazano Narrows. A popular figure on Staten Island, Arbeeny could also be tough; his brother, Michael Arbeeny, recalled that once, when a customer refused to pay for a fence, Arbeeny connected it to his truck and dragged it down the street. When he died on April 25, Arbeeny was living in Clove Lakes Health Care and Rehabilitation Center on Staten Island. He had diabetes and was on kidney dialysis, but, his daughter said, “He was doing fantastic.” He went from chatting on the phone with her daily to dying in just six days. Along with his daughter and brother, Michael, Arbeeny is survived by his father, Michael S. Arbeeny; siblings, Cynthia, Audrey and Ashley Arbeeny, and Darian Touhey; son-in-law, Neal Messina; and grandsons, Anthony, Nicholas and Michael Messina. His wife died in 2001.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a gentle giant with a heart of gold. He would do anything for anyone.
pullquoteSource: Danielle Messina, Samuel W. Arbeeny’s daughter

hardCodedText: Everyone looked forward to Mudada Kabir’s barbecue and his famed red velvet cake at family reunions in Wilson, N.C. “He was the go-to cook in our family,” recalled his daughter, Keiona Warren. A resident of Brooklyn, Kabir was born in 1962 in Newark, N.J. He attended Weequahic High School there and graduated with a business degree from New Jersey City University. He worked as a drug counselor in New York City and was the father of eight children and grandfather of 15. As an outgrowth of his Muslim faith, he changed his name from Reginald Williams in the early 2000s, and he spent his free time at the masjid. He loved conversation, and he attuned himself to his grandchildren’s interests. They called him Poppy or Pop-Pop. “He could talk to you about anything, from religion to ancient history to current events,” said his daughter. Friends and family didn’t know Kabir was sick, but when they couldn’t reach him during Easter weekend, they began calling hospitals. By the time they managed to talk to him, via iPad, he was on life support. They spent two hours reminiscing and saying goodbye. Kabir died at Brooklyn Hospital Center on April 22. His survivors also include his “partner in love,” Karla Barnett.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a person anyone could talk to, without judgment.

hardCodedText: Though Evelyn Bulcock had lived for almost a century, she had the vitality of someone much younger, her family said. Affectionately called “Aunty Evelyn” or “Evo,” Evelyn Louise Bulcock was born in 1922 in Bagotville, Guyana, the eldest of four. She was a nurse by training who, in her early years, treated patients stricken with tuberculosis. She eventually moved to Brooklyn and, although she had no children of her own, she was a maternal figure to her nieces and nephews, family members said. Bulcock particularly enjoyed church, crossword puzzles, bingo and “just having fun,” said her grand-niece, Nicole Denny. Her favorite phrase was “not to worry.” She died March 28 at Brookdale Hospital in Brooklyn at the age of 98.
hardCodedPullquote: Her happiest moments were when she was able to give someone something, whether it be relatives or friends. She had a huge heart.
pullquoteSource: Nicole Denny, Evelyn Louise Bulcock’s grand-niece

hardCodedText: Stanley “Stan” Kaplan found his first creative outlet as a painter. Specializing in hard-edge paintings, Kaplan exhibited his work five times at the 55 Mercer Street Gallery, which he helped to establish in 1969. His work was recognized with grants from the Adolph & Esther Gottlieb Foundation and the Pollock-Krasner Foundation. Kaplan combined his painting career with his leftist politics through his membership with the Art Workers' Coalition, a collective of artists, writers and critics who advocated for economic, political and social reforms at New York City’s museums. He also taught a new generation of artists at several colleges and universities. A Brooklyn native, Kaplan called SoHo home before moving to the Hebrew Home in Riverdale. There, friends say, the 84-year-old regaled fellow residents with funny stories and a sharp wit. At the time of his death, Kaplan continued to paint, working on a series dedicated to his longtime partner. He died April 17 at St. Joseph’s Hospital in Yonkers.
hardCodedPullquote: When I first met him, he was basically a painter. Then, he got interested in writing. He did a lot of writing. Then, he got interested in poetry. And he was a published poet. He was a polymath in many ways.

hardCodedText: Nataliya Rudnichenko was born in the former Soviet Union, present-day Ukraine, in 1938. She grew up in the midst of World War II and became a formally-trained geologist, traveling extensively through Central Asia on expeditions. After she retired seven years ago, she moved to Staten Island to join her daughter and two granddaughters. Rudnichenko took English classes and “every program available” at the Happy Island Senior Center, said her granddaughter, Maryana. “She was very independent her entire life.” Rudnichenko obtained her U.S. citizenship in 2018 and attended Maryana’s naturalization ceremony in 2019. She died April 12 after a brief hospitalization for COVID-19 at the age of 82. Rudnichenko is survived by her daughter, two granddaughters and a grandson.
author: Phyllis Kaufman
additionalNotes: This submission was made by Ms. Rudnichenko's granddaughter, who only provided her cell phone number.

hardCodedText: Elizabeth Lamberty moved to New York City from Costa Rica in 1998 and settled in the Bronx. As a single mother to six children, Elizabeth worked several jobs at a time as a housekeeper and a nanny to support them. But no matter how hard she worked, she still found time to celebrate life; She was an “incredible dancer,” her family said, who loved the city she had made her home. After her son, Freddy, died suddenly in November 2019, Elizabeth was broken-hearted, and struggled with her health. She fought the COVID-19 virus for 25 days before dying on May 1 at the age of 70.

hardCodedText: Miguel Almarante Jr. came to New York from the Dominican Republic with his sister at age 2. His three younger siblings were born in New York, and Almarante grew up as the big brother of the family. A “father figure” and a “super dad” to his young daughter, when he got a minivan, everyone counted on him to transport the whole family to dinners and birthdays in the park. Spiritual, funny, and attentive to details, he believed “you have to be on point.” Almarante had a lifelong interest in law enforcement. He started as a security guard, then took a job as peace officer at night at Hunts Point Produce Market, where he took on any extra days he could. The week before he died, Almarante accepted a job with Customs and Border Patrol. Almarante died on April 13 at the age of 32, at Lincoln Hospital in the Bronx.

hardCodedText: John Dunston Jr. grew up on a farm in North Carolina as the youngest of 12 children. After serving in the Army, he moved to New York where he had a career as a bus operator with the Metropolitan Transportation Authority. His son followed in his steps as a bus operator. Dunston stayed active after his retirement; He loved to travel all over the country on his Harley Davidson, and attended the Americade in Lake George with his partner, Cheryl, every year. Every summer he traveled back to North Carolina for the Dunston family gathering, which he helped finance. John was in remission from prostate cancer at the time of his death, on April 14 at Jamaica Hospital in Queens at the age of 74. After a funeral service in Queens, he was buried in North Carolina with full military honors.

hardCodedText: Born and raised in Milwaukee, Dr. Jay Martin Galst moved to New York City in the 1970s to attend medical school at Columbia University. After receiving his degree, he set up a private practice in Manhattan, which he ran for decades. At a young age, Dr. Galst developed an interest in coin collecting, a passion that he continued to pursue throughout his life, becoming an expert in coins related to the eye (as well as those from Judea). He wrote a 574-page book on the subject titled “Ophthalmologia, Optica et Visio in Nummis.” He was a clinical professor at New York Medical College and past president and longtime board member of the New York Numismatic Club. Dr. Galst and his wife, psychologist Joann Paley Galst, met as children and became best friends while working on their high school yearbook. Dr. Galst was drawn to ophthalmology by the concrete nature and specificity of the field, she said, viewing the eyes as “a window to the well-being of a person.” As someone who valued family, Dr. Galst often saw patients across generations, treating the children of those who had first come to him when they were young themselves. Dr. Galst died April 12 at the age of 69 at NYU Langone Hospital in Manhattan. He is survived by his wife, their son, and two grandchildren, one of whom was born shortly after his death.
hardCodedPullquote: He was the ultimate mensch, a very kind and generous person who gave of his time to anyone who needed or wanted it. He was still in touch with his friends from years ago, even his best friends from kindergarten and high school. We were best friends for 54 years.

hardCodedText: Dolores Altagracia Mena was born in 1936 in the Dominican Republic, and grew up on a farm on the coast in Monte Cristi. She came to the United States around 1978, settling in New York to be closer to family. For 36 years, she lived in an apartment in Jackson Heights, Queens. “She found a community here, and loved New York a lot,” said her grandson, Steven Luna. Mena enjoyed books, hot chocolate with whipped cream, puzzles, Sudoku, crosswords and building Lego sets — a replica of the White House was her favorite set of all. In her youth, she studied to be a fashion designer, though gave up her studies and took on duties as a caretaker when her three children were born. She has nine grandchildren, and her personality continues to influence the “incredible, powerful” women in her family, Luna said. Mena died on April 17 at the age of 84.

hardCodedText: A lifelong Brooklyn resident, Theresa Estelle Morris was a mother to three, a grandmother to five, and a great-grandmother to 10. After a stint working in a Brooklyn pearl factory, Morris became a homemaker after marrying John Morris, who served in the military and was from Brooklyn. While her husband worked as an NYPD officer, Morris and her three children spent the summers at the family home in upstate New York. Those days were “pure joy” for her, according to her son, William Morris. “It was so cute how happy she was to be there,” he said. “She just enjoyed it so much.” After her husband died in 2004, Morris lived in Waterford on the Bay, an assisted living home. She enjoyed bingo and dances and lovingly described the home as a “cruise ship going nowhere,” a far cry from her work in the pearl factory. Morris suffered with COVID-like symptoms for more than a month and was transferred between several nursing homes and hospitals before she died April 6 in Coney Island Hospital at the age of 91. Her cremated remains will be buried at Calverton Military Cemetery with her husband, John.
hardCodedPullquote: She was a good mom, and a good grandma. It was sad, the way it went, because we didn’t get to spend any time with her.
pullquoteSource: Anne Slamka, Theresa Estelle Morris’ daughter-in-law
author: Eli Frankel

hardCodedText: Kimberly Wetzel was known by many names — Kimasaki, Aunty Kim and, most often, Kim. She grew up with her mom, Judy, and brother, Marty, in Pennsylvania. Her love for travel and languages brought her to years of living abroad in Poland, London and Nicaragua, teaching English as a foreign language, and, for the last 15 years, working in NYU’s Office of Global Services. She lived in Brooklyn with her two beloved “copy cats,” Carbon and Ditto. Kim found a group of close friends in the Sirens, New York City’s oldest women’s motorcycle club. Two New York City benches are dedicated in her memory — one in Green-Wood Cemetery, where she frequently spent time with friends and took night photography classes, and one in Washington Square Park, near her work. The plaque in Green-Wood reads: “Beloved friend, storyteller, motorcyclist, photographer, artist, baker, musician, and adventurer. She loved cats, squirrels, Sirens MC, and Green-Wood.” After a rescue attempt that had friends, neighbors, and family from across the country coordinating to get into her apartment, and successfully got her to a hospital, she died on March 29, 2020, at the age of 50.
hardCodedPullquote: We were all just blown away by how much she impacted people on a one-on-one level. If you needed something, you ask Kim. It would be done, it would be helped.
author: Hannah Reale

He played the lottery for 40 years and dreamed of hitting the jackpot so he could buy each of his two daughters a house with a picket fence, said his daughter, Magdalena. Matos died April 23 at the age of 80.

hardCodedText: Timothy Olan Montgomery was a photographer, painter, make-up artist and, later in life, an actor. Early in his career, Montgomery made a name for himself as a make-up artist working with publications like Glamour and Cosmopolitan. He photographed the likes of Alan Cumming and Anne Hathaway. His friend, Hanna Edwards, described him as a “fun, adventurous and kind spirit.” In 2011, he began a second career as an actor, appearing in Boardwalk Empire, Stranger Things and The Irishman. Montgomery died April 4 at Long Island Jewish Medical Center after a 29-day battle with COVID-19. He was 56 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: He was impulsively creative and doggedly curious. He was kind to everyone and especially loved animals.

From SI Live: 

Abraham “Avi” Sharoni, 78, was a fun, loving, and caring man. Avi was known by many in the Heartland Village and New Springville community for making people laugh and his warm smile. He was a carpenter who “could fix anything he set his mind to." No matter what the task was, Avi always completed it to perfection. Avi enjoyed going to Atlantic City, traveling and going on cruises with friends, taking walks, gardening and planting his own vegetables, and hosting holiday events and dinners. Most of all, he was a family man and a supportive husband, father, grandfather, and brother. He will be remembered for his generosity and jovial personality. Avi is survived by his wife of 53 years, Esther, three children, Roni, Gigi, and Leor, his four grandchildren, his brother, and his sister.

From SI Live:
Rosalie Acampora, 83, was loving, caring, and creative, and she always had a smile on her face. She was originally from Brooklyn, where she attended Lafayette High School. She later earned a degree from the Fashion Institute of Technology and got a job in retail buying. She moved to Staten Island in 1968 and raised her children there. She was an active part of her children’s lives, even holding the title of PTA President at Port Richmond High School for several years. Rosalie loved giving back to the community; she literally once gave a homeless man the coat off of her back. She helped deliver toys to local organizations, such as Toys for Tots. Outside of giving and caring for her mother, children, and grandchildren, Rosalie loved sewing, painting, singing, and needlepoint. She is survived by her two sisters, Antoinette and Connie, her four children Marie, Anne, Alice, and Anthony, as well as her 10 grandchildren. She led an incredible life and is loved and missed by all who knew her.

Health Conditions: Pietro was battling cancer at time of death. May have also had diabetes and/or heart disease (joint obit with wife).

Pietro and his wife Rita emigrated to the United States from the same small town of Pozzallo, Sicily, but met in the U.S. They lived in Brooklyn for 30 years before settling in Tottenville, Staten Island in 2000. Pietro and Rita died one week apart.

Rita was called Nonna (grandmother) and Pietro was called Nonno (grandfather) by their grandchildren.

Pietro and Rita survived by their children, Manni and Frank, and five grandchildren, Pietro and Nico, Pietro, Elena, and Francesca.

Both Pietro and Rita loved to cook and taught their family the tradition of making wine with family.

hardCodedText: In 1925, on the day Louis Schmidt stepped foot in New York City from Szatmar, Hungary with his mother, Bella and his brother, Michael, he became an American and put his homeland behind him, said his daughter, Susan Chevel. He grew up on the Lower East Side on Avenue C and attended Seward Park High School. He enlisted in the armed forces and proudly served in the Army Air Corps in Saipan as a mechanic working in the B52 bomber division. Upon his return, he migrated to Miami Beach where he met Margaret Benneche on the beach, fell in love and married. She was from Bay Ridge and they returned to New York where they raised their family. Louis spent the next 40 years working for the NYCHA as a plasterer and a foreman. He died March 30 and was laid to rest next to his wife and son on August 20, 2020, which would have been his 100th birthday. He is survived by his daughter, Susan Chevel, his grandchildren, Tracy and Stephen as well as his great grandchildren, Grace and Christian.
hardCodedPullquote: My father was the kindest gentleman I ever met. His love for his family, friends, co workers and neighbors was admirable. His sense of pride for his country never faltered. His commitment to mankind was extraordinary. My father Louis Schmidt was indeed one from our greatest generation and my brother and I were proud to call him Dad. I will miss him forever.
pullquoteSource: Susan Chevel, Daughter of Louis Schmidt
streetAddress: Sunrise of East Meadow 1555 Glenn Curtiss Blvd. East Meadow NY

hardCodedText: Gregory Penny Sr. seemed to constantly be surrounded by family. In photograph after photograph, his blue eyes are complimented by a wide grin. Penny, a Bronx resident, died April 30 at Albert Einstein Hospital at the age of 74. He was buried May 4 at Pelham Cemetery in City Island, New York.
hardCodedPullquote: My dad was an amazing man, loving husband, role model to his children and grandchildren, devoted family man and loyal friend.
pullquoteSource: Kimberly Fusco, Gregory Penny Sr.’s daughter
author: Rachel Bailey

hardCodedText: Richard Litkofsky was "uniquely abled," his family said, and communicated through his tone, facial expressions and a "special magic," they said. A "convivial spirit," he particularly enjoyed dancing and laughing and was a diehard New York Mets fan who loved taking trips to Shea Stadium and expanding his collection of baseball caps. Deeply rooted in faith and family, Litkofsky lived in Sheepshead Bay for 72 years and was a founding resident of the Young Adult Institute; He died May 5 and was buried next to his parents and his sister on Long Island.
hardCodedPullquote: Richard left the world a better and brighter place than the one he came into.
author: Kate Christobek

hardCodedText: Thomas Crater Jr. was an activist and entrepreneur who published and edited his own local newspaper called The New York Page. Born in Memphis, Tennessee, Crater lived in Jamaica, Queens, for more than 50 years. He worked for several major news organizations including Jet, Ebony and Black Enterprise and dreamed of starting his own business. In 1984, Crater began publishing The New York Page, a newspaper that served Jamaica, Queens. Always a free paper, The New York Page ran for more than three decades. Known by many as “TC,” Crater was a sharp dresser who never wore jeans and liked wing-tipped shoes, white shirts and bowties. Up until he became sick with COVID-19, he took care of his sister, Edna Mae; fought for improvements in his apartment building; distributed a free local paper; and served as an usher for 40 years at his church. Crater, who died April 29 at Columbia Presbyterian at the age of 75, is survived by his sister, two daughters and two grandchildren. In 2018, Crater suffered a stroke. But after he recovered, he continued to care for his sister, began volunteering at a church soup kitchen and even rode his foldable bike to the farmer’s market against doctor’s orders.
hardCodedPullquote: He really believed in people. He really tried to see the good in everybody.
pullquoteSource: Elizabeth Gray, Thomas Crater Jr.’s daughter
author: Emily Lowinger

hardCodedText: Juan M. Caban grew up in the south Bronx after his parents immigrated to the U.S. from Puerto Rico. In 2005, he opened the J&A Hardware store, which he owned and ran until his death. He died May 5 at the Jack D. Weiler Hospital of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine and is survived by his daughter, Gloria.
author: Anna Bianca Roach

hardCodedText: After emigrating from Chinantla, Mexico, to New York City, Justo Calixto Andon worked for more than 20 years at a clothing factory where he saw to it that machines ran smoothly, his family said. Though he didn’t have kids of his own, Andon was “a family guy,” said his nephew, Pedro Calixto Lucero. The family lived under one roof, and Andon was akin to a second father to his nephew and nieces, whom he delighted in surprising with freshly-bought pizza. While he was known for his unrelenting work ethic, “Tio Goyo” also enjoyed jogging and family time, his nephew said. Andon died May 26 at Maimonides Hospital in Brooklyn at the age of 53.
hardCodedPullquote: I didn’t see him as an uncle, I saw him as a second father. He was always there. He did a lot of things to show that he cared.
pullquoteSource: Pedro Calixto Lucero, Justo Calixto Andon’s nephew
author: Matthew Samuel Reysio-Cruz

hardCodedText: Decades after immigrating to Brooklyn, Eloy Calixto Andon would stay up late into the night to watch mariachi singers ring in Mexico’s Independence Day. He never missed an annual trip to his hometown of Chinantla, where his son, Pedro, said he asked to be buried. Andon did, however, relish the most American of pastimes: cheering on the New York Yankees and Mets. Serious and outspoken, he worked for years at a Greek restaurant to support his wife, put his three children through college and send money to his parents back home, his family said. Andon died May 5 at Brooklyn Methodist Hospital at the age of 66.
hardCodedPullquote: His son and daughters, his wife—he just cared that we were all doing OK. He wasn’t always affectionate, but we knew he was just proud of us, proud of his hometown, proud of his wife, proud of everything.
pullquoteSource: Pedro Calixto Lucero, Eloy Calixto Andon’s son
author: Matthew Samuel Reysio-Cruz

hardCodedText: A lifelong Staten Islander, Louis C. Barbato Jr. was born and raised in Tomkinsville, attended Curtis High School and moved to Westerleigh in the early 1970s, where he lived until his death. After graduating high school, Barbato went into carpentry and founded his own contracting company, LJB Associates. A craftsman and designer, Barbato was nicknamed “MacGyver” by those who knew him, because “he could build or fix anything,” said his daughter, Jennifer DeMeo. After a decade running LJB, Barbato became a design contractor for a national chain of cosmetology schools. In the 1990s, he went on to join the New York City Department of Housing Preservation and Development as a building inspector. Ever social, Barbato enjoyed traveling, dining out, and attending Broadway shows. He also took pleasure in teaching others woodworking and often had projects going in the homes of neighbors and friends. When he was a young man, Barbato once passed a burning house on his way to work, and made sure that everyone inside escaped. “He did whatever he could to help people, whoever it was: neighbor, friend, family member, stranger,” his daughter said. After retiring 11 years ago, Barbato took a part-time maintenance job at a funeral home, where he was most likely exposed to the novel coronavirus. Barbato died April 7 at the age of 74 at Staten Island University Hospital. He is survived by his wife of 54 years, Jean (DePete), two daughters, five grandchildren and two great-granddaughters.
hardCodedPullquote: My dad’s motto was ‘family first.’ He had a tattoo of it in Italian on his wrist, ‘familia prima.’ And for him, everyone was family. He treated everyone like gold, and that’s what he got in return. It’s the greatest loss.
pullquoteSource: Jennifer DeMeo, daughter of Louis C. Barbato Jr.
author: Talia Bloch

hardCodedText: Illuysha Aminov was born in Russia in 1942 and, after the Soviet Union collapsed, moved to New York in 1977 with his family. Aminov, who lived in Lefrak City, Queens, and worked around Rego Park, was a barber, as was his father. He especially enjoyed cutting children’s hair for the first time, repairing cars and watching boxing matches, his family said. He “fixes cars more than he drives them,” his son said, and “would work for us rather than just himself.” Aminov had suffered from a heart attack, diabetes and hypertension and he was hospitalized with COVID-19 for two weeks. As he was recovering, his lungs collapsed and he died April 18 at the North Shore University Hospital at the age of 77. He is survived by his wife, Zinaida Aminova, and his son and daughter, Roman and Iran Aminov.
hardCodedPullquote: He had cut my hair ever since I was a little boy and his loss still feels like I’ve lost a part of myself.
author: Natalia Gutiérrez
underlyingCondition: Heart condition, Diabetes, High blood pressure

hardCodedText: Wayne Steele was born in the Bahamas, lived in Trinidad and came to the U.S. as a child. Steele lived in Atlanta and Texas before settling in Crown Heights in Brooklyn. Steele was a veteran who served in the Navy from 1976 to 1979. He later worked as a bus driver for New York City public schools and as a paralegal in Brooklyn. The third of five siblings. Steele is survived by his mother and four children. Despite living in New York for most of his life, Steele maintained his Caribbean roots, his family said. As a practitioner of Rastafari, a religious branch of Christianity and social movement started in Jamaica, he wore his hair in dreadlocks and was a vegan. As hobbies, Steele worked on cars and enjoyed basketball and soccer. Steele met Venette Payton, the mother of his youngest son and his partner, 13 years ago at a daycare that their children attended. Steele didn’t care for the cold or the hustle of New York, Payton said, and preferred the beach and warm weather. He had planned to retire to Trinidad, where he still has family. Steele died May 7 at the Manhattan VA Medical Center at the age of 60.
hardCodedPullquote: He was just well-mannered, a gentleman, respectful and helpful to anybody.
author: Liz Richards
