hardCodedText: Lori McDonald was a performer, fundraiser and educator. Born in Washington D.C. and raised in Holbrook, Ariz., McDonald lived in Los Angeles briefly and worked as a costume designer on “Hollywood Squares.” McDonald met her husband, Terence, while earning a master’s degree in theater at the University of Connecticut. At the time, Terence was tap dancing down the street. The couple founded the Playhouse of American Classics in New York in 1989 before bringing the organization to Buffalo, where Terence worked as a professor at SUNY Buffalo State. The playhouse put on classic American plays at the Buffalo History Museum and McDonald wrote a play called “War Stories” based on the child abuse she saw as a teacher. Earlier in her career, McDonald worked in the fundraising department at United Way and the Joffrey Ballet. In the 1990s, she became a public school teacher, working in Harlem and the Bronx. She later taught at several city schools, including Trinity School, the Spence School and the Chapin School. McDonald, who her family said was beloved by her students, once got stranded with her students overnight at a CVS in a snowstorm and ate convenience store snacks to get through the night. McDonald died May 6 at Danbury Hospital in Danbury, Conn., at the age of 75.
hardCodedPullquote: She was one of my role models as an educator. She just had unbelievable confidence.
author: Liz Richards
additionalNotes: She had Parkinson's, which isn't listed as an underlying condition. Additional photos of Lori and Playhouse American Classics were provided.

hardCodedText: John “Yasho” Dearden had enough pairs of shoes to last for years. Having developed a close relationship with his Polish-speaking, shoe-making grandfather, Dearden knew how to make new shoes comfortable and old shoes shiny, said his son, J.D. Arden-Kimmel. Those shoes would accompany Dearden to the jazz bars he loved, to the marches of the Civil Rights movement and to his son’s wedding. Dearden grew up in New Jersey in the 1940s and 50s and he particularly enjoyed telling corny dad jokes, his son said, and a story about meeting Ella Fitzgerald at a bar after one of her performances. After suffering a stroke in 2016, Dearden moved to a nursing home in Coney Island, to be closer to his son and son-in-law. Even as he worked through rehabilitation from the stroke and was mostly unable to walk, he was able to get up from his wheelchair and dance at his son's wedding. Dearden died April 10 at Coney Island Hospital at the age of 80 after being admitted with coronavirus symptoms; he was not administered a COVID-19 test before he died.
author: Haidee Chu

hardCodedText: A Great Neck native, Robert "Rob" Nathan loved the New York Islanders and met his wife of 15 years, Danielle, at a local adult league hockey game. Nathan served nine years with the Great Neck Alert Volunteer Fire Company and became a certified defensive driving instructor with his wife. He was also instrumental in sending his stepdaughter, Sam, to college at St. John's, his family said. He and Danielle Nathan boarded dogs for deployed military personnel, adopting two of them (Taz and Damien) and operated the Paw It Forward Pet Pantry out of their home. Nathan, who died April 14 at LIJ Hospital in Queens, is survived by his wife, stepdaughter, parents and his brother, Steven.
author: Matthew Durot

hardCodedText: Brilla Garces Jaldane, or "Tita Brilla," to her family, was never afraid to speak her mind. She was “opinionated” and “brazenly outspoken," said her niece, Luzette Garces. Jarldane emigrated from the Phillippines to Canarsie, where her four younger siblings joined her. A world traveler, she liked to carry snacks whether she was visiting Egypt or Atlantic City, her family said. Although she had no children, she was a maternal figure to her siblings, nephews and nieces. She was particularly generous in giving her family support, advice and fur coats she had ordered from the Home Shopping Network, they said. She died April 21 at the age of 77, shortly after her husband, George.
hardCodedPullquote: She had a very strong personality and was very independent. She inspired all the girls in the family.
pullquoteSource: Luzette Garces, Brilla Garces Jarldane's niece
author: Cassidy Jensen

hardCodedText: Larry DeVito would give anyone the shirt off his back, said his daughter, Janine DeVito. DeVito owned two businesses in Brooklyn: Petals Florist in Gravesend and Mi-Lar Landscaping in Mill Basin. DeVito gave fellow florists bunches of blooms from the 25-year-old curly willow tree in his backyard. He snowblowed older Mill Basin residents’ driveways in the winter, when he was in his 60s himself. And he brought old orchid blossoms to one Petals customer, just because he knew she liked to nurse the flowers back to health. When DeVito died, his daughter received an outpouring of messages from customers. DeVito emigrated from Italy when he was young and, in the last years of his life, he worked seven days a week. But his daughter also convinced him to take a few vacations, including a trip to Italy in 2018. Out of all the desserts at any Sicilian restaurant he went to, DeVito would always choose ice cream — and vanilla, preferably, she said. DeVito died April 15 at NewYork-Presbyterian Methodist Hospital at the age of 71.
hardCodedPullquote: He just always gave, you know. There are 100 stories like that. Little things. You realize how many people he did these little things for and you realize how his life was just about making people happy.
author: Jacqueline Neber

hardCodedText: Raymond Vázquez Muñoz was born in Mayagüez, Puerto Rico, and lived in every borough in New York City, except Staten Island, according to his son, Ray Muñoz. It’s unclear where Muñoz picked up his cooking skills but Muñoz’s culinary career took him from private clubs to public schools, and he was a chef at Planet Hollywood. Muñoz taught his son how to tie his shoelaces; would take the scenic route on any drive; and played guitar, including a performance with Stevie Wonder at the Apollo Theater. Muñoz also loved the Mets. He died at home on April 7 at the age of 66.
hardCodedPullquote: If heaven exists, he’s playing guitar with angels, unlocking mysteries of the universe and trying the local beer.
pullquoteSource: Ray Muñoz, Raymond Vázquez Muñoz’s son
author: Jacqueline Neber
newsSource: His son Ray's Twitter thread eulogizing his father
additionalNotes: Raymond was Hispanic/Latino and was born in Mayagüez, Puerto Rico. He lived in all NYC boroughs except Staten Island, according to his son Ray Muñoz.

hardCodedText: To Frank Orsini, his wife, Janet, and two children, Frank and Jennifer, his sister and three grandchildren, were his "lifeline," his family said. When he died, his car club — the Mustang and Shelby Club of Long Island — held a drive-by funeral for him. If you needed someone to dress up as Santa Claus, Frank Orsini was your guy. He was a union teamster for much of his life, delivering raw materials to construction sites. After the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks, he helped remove debris from Ground Zero, working “relentlessly," his family said. He grew up in Ozone Park, Queens; married his wife, Janet, in 1980; and settled in Richmond Hill before moving to Long Island, where he and Janet lived for about 35 years. He decorated one room of his home with Yankee and Elvis memorabilia and was a dedicated member of the Mustang and Shelby Club, where he won first prize for his Mustang. During his drive-by funeral, the street was filled with friends, neighbors and passersby. He died April 2 at Good Samaritan Hospital in West Islip at the age of 62.
hardCodedPullquote: Frank was one of the hardest working men you could know. He was all about his family. He was generous. He would lend a hand to anybody at the drop of a hat, without question. He was a very good man, like many men.
author: Jacqueline Neber
additionalNotes: Janet Orsini, Frank's wife, asked if she could see his obituary before publication; Long Island, Suffolk County

hardCodedText: Ezzard Christopher, also known as Burnham, was a man who would greet everyone with a “Hey man, how are you?” according to his wife, Megan Christopher. He had a passion for dancing, especially Caribbean-style ballroom dancing and could be found many Friday nights at the Guyanese social club in his neighborhood, dancing and playing dominos. He and his wife competed in many Guyanese dance competitions where they frequently returned home with trophies. “I remember as a little girl growing up, him teaching me how to dance and waltzing on his feet as he taught me the box movements and where to hold my hands,” said his daughter, Angel Christopher. A bauxite mining foreman from Guyana, he immigrated to Brooklyn in 1988 with his wife and daughter. He worked for the New York City Department of Environmental Protection for more than 25 years, first machining then moving through the ranks to become a water filtration engineer. Over the years, the DEP shifted to a digitized testing system, which he learned how to use. “He was determined not to let a new technology push him out of his career,” his daughter said. He loved to travel and frequently sent money back to Guyana. He died April 2 at a hospital in Brooklyn at the age of 68. He was the oldest of 11 children and the father to five children: Nigel, Sheldon, Rawle, Gavin and Angel.
hardCodedPullquote: He was always smiling, always joking, always shaking and hugging people. He was definitely the life of the party.
author: Kayce Stevens

hardCodedText: Michael Dimin grew up on Long Island surrounded by boats and fishing before settling in Brooklyn and founding the sustainable seafood company Sea to Table. During a family vacation in Tobago in the late 1990s, Dimin had gone fishing with a local fisherman and caught a boat load of fish. Upon returning to port, Dimin realized all the other boats had caught the same amount of fish, and with no refrigeration on the island, there was no way they could sell all of their fish before it spoiled. Thus was the start of Dimin’s vision to create a way to connect fishermen with people who wanted to eat better fish. In 2010, his vision became reality and his family business began with three employees. “He made everyone work harder because he could trace [the source of] the fish he sold and others couldn’t always say the same,” said his friend and former colleague, Holley Atkinson. Dimin valued his employees, appreciated their opinions and made Sea To Table a fun place to work, she said. “As an employee, you really felt like you were part of the family,” Atkinson said. Dimin died April 13 at his mother’s home in Point Lookout, N.Y., at the age of 67. He is survived by five children, Daniel, Katie, Sean, Alex and Philip, and numerous grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: Michael had an outrageous exuberance. He was a passionate visionary, no holds barred kind of guy, really smart and fun.
pullquoteSource: Holley Atkinson, Michael Dimin’s friend and former coworker
author: Kayce Stevens

hardCodedText: From the age of 5, James C. Thompson picked cotton with his aunt rather than attend school, leaving scars on his legs. At the age of 9, he left Williston, S.C., and moved to Brooklyn with his father. He became a star athlete, leading his high school basketball team to a championship game at Madison Square Garden. Thompson played college basketball in Kansas and, after graduating, worked at the Walt Whitman Houses, a NYCHA housing complex in Fort Greene. “He had a very deep feeling for his people, and people who were poor,” said his wife of more than 40 years, Dolores B. Thompson. Thompson, known to his students as “Mr. T or JT,” worked as a teacher in a daycare center and later in a classroom support role at PS 67 for 40 years. Often, before his shift started, he’d ride his bike from his home in Prospect Heights to Fort Greene so he could greet each child at the school breakfast program. Outside of class, Thompson loved to sing or “hit the notes,” as he’d say. He helped establish the Fort Greene Council Inc. with his mentor Sam Pinn Jr., lobbying for more Black stewardship of community institutions, namely care centers for children and seniors, and worked with Brooklyn CORE (Congress on Racial Equity). Thompson died May 17 at the Cobble Hill Care Center, after suffering from kidney failure, Alzheimer’s and finally Covid-19. His wife was by his side as he died. “I had all his music on the iPod. When visiting, I’d take a little speaker, and he would sing to it.”
hardCodedPullquote: He had this tremendous instinct for what human beings want.
pullquoteSource: Dolores B. Thompson, James C. Thompson’s wife
author: Abē Ross Levine
additionalNotes: I have two additional obituaries I can upload by PDF that Dolores sent me.

hardCodedText: Born during the Great Depression, Jennie Graziano — or “Aunt Jennie” as she was called by those close to her — grew up in downtown Brooklyn, sleeping with her five sisters under a pile of coats in a single bed. Described as a “Bobby Socks Girl,” Graziano adored Frank Sinatra and had his picture hanging on her wall for the entirety of her adult life. She loved to sing, cook classic southern Italian food and never missed the chance to “bust chops,” even with strangers, said her nephew, Rob LeDonne. Before moving into a nursing home, Graziano’s home in Canarsie — with a disco ball hanging low in the living room — was the site of most family gatherings and holidays. Graziano died March 22 at Mount Sinai Hospital. Her nephew said her last words to her family were of love and appreciation. She was 93 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: Feisty, sweet, wise-cracking and a woman of deep faith, Aunt Jennie was a classic New York City character; With a thick Brooklyn-Italian accent, she was the true definition and embodiment of what New York used to be.
pullquoteSource: Rob LeDonne, nephew of Jennie Graziano
author: J Alejandra Pedraza Buenahor
newsSource: People Magazine - The Nephew Honoring His Feisty Aunt, 93, a 'True New York City Character' until Coronavirus Struck

hardCodedText: Shaimeek Raijeen Frazier went by many names: ShyShee, ShyShy, FlyShy or just Shy. One of four siblings, Frazier was born and raised in Washington Heights and moved to the Bronx at 19. A “fashionista,” according to her mother, Shamika Kearney, Frazier was a “go-getter” who was preparing to attend nursing school. She started working at the age of 14: first, at a summer camp then at retail stores and restaurants. As the pandemic worsened in New York City, Frazier, who was saving money for nursing school, continued to go to work at Mighty Quinn’s BBQ, “just doing what a motivated 21-year-old would,” said her father, Reginald Frazier, who believes she caught coronavirus on the job. Her symptoms briefly improved before a sudden decline. She died at home on April 23 at the age of 21.
hardCodedPullquote: She was on her way when she got cut down by this. … She didn’t deserve that. None of us did.
pullquoteSource: Reginald Frazier, Shaimeek Raijeen Frazier’s father

hardCodedText: Blanca Castaño Mero was born in Manta, Ecuador, the daughter of livestock farmers. At 19, she immigrated to the U.S., paving the way for her immediate family who would later follow. While living in Brooklyn, she married Tito Mero, a fellow Ecuadorian immigrant. They raised three children and later settled in Queens. Mero had a career as a hairdresser and tailor; she was also the family matriarch, said her daughter, Diana Mero-Tasci. “She was there for me when I delivered my first child. She stayed there through the night to make sure I and the baby were OK.” Mero loved walking on the beach and feeling the sun on her skin, her family said. She took pride in her tomato garden and also had a knack for making new friends. Mero fought metastatic breast cancer and diabetes for years before getting sick with COVID-19. She died April 19 at NewYork-Presbyterian/Weill Cornell Medical Center at the age of 77.
hardCodedPullquote: She was a great mom who loved life, family and friends. She enjoyed helping people.
pullquoteSource: Diana Mero-Tasci, Blanca Castaño Mero’s daughter

hardCodedText: Stephen Cooper, who worked as an electrical engineer, was delivering documents downtown when the South Tower collapsed on Sept. 11, 2001. A photographer captured him fleeing the scene amidst a cloud of smoke and debris. The image of Cooper, taken by an Associated Press reporter, was reprinted in magazines and newspapers around the world and was later featured in the 9/11 Museum. Cooper died March 28 at the age of 78, according to the Palm Beach Post.

hardCodedText: Born and raised in Yonkers, New York, Edward Frederick Doty was a former police officer and assistant fire chief for Yonkers. Doty served as a first responder during the Sept. 11 attacks at the World Trade Center, which permanently damaged his lungs, according to his partner, Patricia Brengel. Despite Doty's injuries, "he was a happy-go-lucky guy," Brengel said. After retiring in 2002, Doty enjoyed fishing aboard his boat named "It's All Good" in Hampton Bays, where he lived with Brengel and two golden retrievers. Doty died at home on March 26 after suffering from COVID-19-like symptoms.
hardCodedPullquote: Anyone who needed help with anything, he was always there for them.

hardCodedText: Eli Klausner was a survivor: kidney cancer, multiple mini strokes, type II diabetes. On the morning of Sept. 11, 2001, Klausner, a Long Island native, was scheduled to attend a meeting at the World Trade Center, but he skipped it at the last minute. He loved spending the holidays with his children and grandchildren in North Carolina, they said. Klausner died April 13 at Duke Raleigh Hospital in North Carolina at the age of 64.

hardCodedText: Joel Gomez Dominguez was born in La Isabela, Dominican Republic, and moved to New York City in 2004, where he met Ileana Cotto. Gomez was 21 and Cotto was 37 with eight children. He adopted them and the couple had three more children along with a chihuahua named Pocahontas. The Gomez family made a living selling empanadas at baseball games in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. Gomez’s favorite dish was Dominican mangú and he enjoyed dancing to merengue or bachata, particularly El Chaval de la Bachata, Ala Jaza, Luis Vargas, El Varón de la Bachata and Tito Rodríguez. He was omnipresent at games and dance recitals. Gomez began feeling sick on March 26. Just three days before, he had conceived his 12th child with his wife. He died April 6 at the Woodhull Medical Center at the age of 37. He is survived by his wife, Ileana, and his children: Joel, Freddy, Sadan, Jessica, Charlie, Aires, Aneudi, Eivy, Joana, Joeli and Jomeli.

hardCodedText: Alphonse “J.R.” Agovino was born in Harlem in 1952. He loved baseball and was a lifelong Mets fan. As a kid, Agovino teamed up with his cousin, Danny, to cut Mets coupons out of milk cartons until they saved enough to attend a game, said his sisterm Toni Agovino. He was also fascinated by trains. Agovino loved the city’s subways and had a special knack for giving his friends and family exact instructions on how to navigate the MTA system. Agovino once competed on “The $64,000 Question,” a television quiz show in the 1960s and drove a taxi through the late 1980s. He had a wicked sense of humor, his sister said, and loved hanging out with his family. “He had a special relationship with each one of us,” she said. Agovino enjoyed going to baseball games with his brother and he remembered all of his siblings’ birthdays. One of his greatest accomplishments was taking care of his elderly mother. Agovino died April 4 at Jacobi Hospital at the age of 67. He is survived by four siblings and many nieces, nephews and aunts.
hardCodedPullquote: J.R. was a rare diamond in this world.
author: Kynala Phillips

hardCodedText: Anthony C. Dazzo was all about the little things. Before his daughter, Lauren Dazzo-Hanley, left the house, he would check her tires and warn her to back out slowly and look for nails. A doting grandfather, Dazzo hid toys in between couch cushions, so his youngest grandchild wouldn’t put them in her mouth. He’d leave folded up paper towels all over his daughter's house, just in case he needed one. When someone needed a ride, the answer was always yes, even if it meant waiting in the car for hours. Dazzo loved to cook meals for his family, even as he battled with Parkinson’s disease, and he insisted on making oatmeal for his grandchildren, his family said. A few months before Dazzo died, his daughter noticed that he started singing, “Skip To My Lou” including the chorus: “Flies in the buttermilk, shoo, shoo, shoo.” Dazzo died April 9 at the age of 73.
hardCodedPullquote: He was the most gentle man I know, patient, honest, a great cook.
pullquoteSource: Lauren Dazzo-Hanley, Anthony C. Dazzo’s daughter

hardCodedText: Manuel Rivera came to the United States from Puerto Rico in 1950. He became a fixture of East Harlem, running a bodega on 102nd and Lexington Avenue for 15 years. One of the happiest days of Rivera’s career happened in 1972, according to his daughter, Sandra Rivera, when the pianist and bandleader Eddie Palmieri performed in Central Park. Rivera hustled to serve dozens of people crowding the street and his bodega while listening to salsa music. Rivera was humble, his daughter said, and liked helping others and playing dominos in his downtime. He died April 13 at Harlem Hospital at the age of 88.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a very generous person. Instead of getting angry, there was always this part of him that reacted with love.
pullquoteSource: Sandra Rivera, daughter of Manuel Rivera

hardCodedText: Cynthia L. Adams once turned down a dream job with Disney. A talented artist in sculpture, painting and sketching, Adams told her family that moving and leaving them was unfathomable. Adams, who was raised in Ozone Park to a large Italian family, was remembered for always having a sketch pad in her hand and making her children’s Halloween costumes each year. Her daughter, Dawn Adams, described her as a “spark of energy.” After a hip replacement, Adams lived at Peninsula Nursing and Rehabilitation Center in Far Rockaway and, after a short stay at St. John’s Episcopal Hospital, died at the nursing home on May 4 at the age of 69. Some of Adams’s artwork can be seen at her alma mater, Amersham College of Art & Design.
hardCodedPullquote: When she walked in the room, she lit up the room. She was just full of life.
pullquoteSource: Dawn Adams, Cynthia L. Adams’s daughter

hardCodedText: Stanley Albert was a lifelong Bronx resident. For several decades, Stanley worked in the mailroom for the Bronx District Attorney’s Office, before eventually directing all mail services. At his retirement, colleagues were moved to tears, said his brother, Arthur Albert. His marriage to his wife, another neighborhood resident, lasted 52 years, weathering her ill health and the sudden death of their only daughter, Amy. When first admitted into the same nursing home room, a nurse dubbed the pair the home’s Romeo and Juliet. Albert was a lifelong Yankees fan and met with a group of childhood friends once a month at the same diner until his passing in April at the age of 82.
hardCodedPullquote: A wonderful, loving human being. He was a prince among men.

hardCodedText: Tobias Noboa immigrated to New York City from Milagro, Ecuador, in his 20s and spent over 45 years as a yellow taxi cab driver. Noboa and his wife bought a house in Corona, Queens, and raised their family there. He became a naturalized U.S. citizen and supported his family up until his death. His family remembers him as a “gentle soul” and “peace maker” who was the “life of the party.” In his retirement, Noboa found joy in spending time with his great-grandchildren and taking care of his wife. Noboa died on May 25, 2020, at the age of 82. He is survived by his wife of 62 years, three children, five grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: He put his family first.

hardCodedText: At the age of 92, Khana Vorovich was still babysitting her great-grandchildren and hosting sleepovers at her apartment. Vorovich was born in Kiev in 1928 and fled the city to escape Nazis during World War II. After the war, she returned to Kiev to marry and gave birth to two daughters. Vorovich moved to the United States in 1989 to escape growing anti-Semitism in the former Soviet Union, according to her family. She died on April 7 at the age of 92 at Maimonides Medical Center in Brooklyn.
hardCodedPullquote: She will always be missed and remembered. Her death has left a hole in all of our hearts.
author: Caitlin Antonios

hardCodedText: Family meant everything to Carmen M. Calero, according to her daughter, Kim Hernandez. Calero was born in Puerto Rico but her parents settled in Rockaway, Queens, when she was a toddler. Calero came from a family of 14 children and was pulled out of school to help raise her younger siblings. She worked different jobs around The Rockaways — at one time, she was a deli manager; at another she worked in a hospital. Calero raised four children of her own and loved to read, walk on the boardwalk and go camping, her family said. She died April 18 at the age of 69.
hardCodedPullquote: She didn’t take no shit.
author: Caitlin Antonios

hardCodedText: In his apartment complex, Eric Sobel was often the first person to respond whenever someone needed assistance, his neighbors said. Whether deciphering a confusing lease or fixing a broken lampshade, Sobel showed up. For years, Sobel worked alongside his mother in the hospitality industry. After his mother retired, Sobel moved to the Bronx and worked as a sales representative for a small pharmacy, Elm Drugs and Wellness. Sobel always made sure to say hello to every employee and customer, his family and friends said, and he was a fitness enthusiast who could often worked out at MidCityGym. This Christmas, Sobel’s friends say they will miss his Christmas tree, which he would adorn with 1960s ornaments. Sobel died April 2 at the age of 57.
hardCodedPullquote: Every time you would encounter him he would radiate like the sun — he was so warm and so optimistic.
author: Zosia Czerwinski

hardCodedText: Luis Liz was no stranger to a long night’s work. A custodian who regularly stayed long past closing time, Liz cleaned office buildings in the Lower East Side. Usually exhausted on the way home to the Bronx, Liz would always pick up food when his daughter, Ambar, asked. He would get double of everything, she said, because “that’s how he was.” Liz’s daughters meant everything to him, she said, and he remained a “kid at heart.” Liz died April 1 at the age of 47. He is survived by his wife, Rosanna, and his two daughters, Ambar and Ashley.
hardCodedPullquote: He sacrificed everything in his life for his family. He worked for his family, not for himself. We all miss him.
author: Luca Powell
additionalNotes: Ambar Liz, daughter

hardCodedText: Agatha Fina was known for having a sympathetic ear and for giving advice — both solicited and not. According to her daughter, Maria Vourlides, Fina would often say, “You might not want to hear this,” while still somehow saying the right thing. Fina was a devoted Catholic who recited the Hail Mary prayer every night before going to bed. Fina, who was known as “Ag,” “Aggie” or “Agster” — was “elegant,” “quick-witted” and a source of strength to her entire family, Vourlides said. She also loved wearing clothes with leopard print and watching reality television. Fina died April 4 at the age of 93. Her late husband, Tommy Fina, died 52 years ago.
hardCodedPullquote: She seemed indestructible and none of us were prepared for losing her. As her grandson Joey wrote in a tribute to her, “It took a global pandemic to take her down.”
pullquoteSource: Maris Vourlides, Agatha G. Fina’s daughter
author: Ashley Rodriguez

obitSource: John J. Fox and Sons Inc.

hardCodedText: Born in Berkeley County, S.C., in 1946, Laura Taylor Howell lived in the south most of her life, raising three children there. In the 1990s, she packed up the kids and headed to New York City. There, she met Clifton Howell, a tailor and homecare aid who worked in her building. The two got married, settling in The Bronx. “Everyone thinks their mom is the greatest mom, but I think she wins the award,” said her daughter, Marisa Taylor. She worked multiple jobs to make sure “we were going to have a great Christmas and a great birthday.” Among her talents and vocations: health care worker, jewelry maker, cupcake baker, teddy-bear fixer, jokester, cancer survivor and deacon at Lowly Nazarene Baptist Church in The Bronx, where she sang in the choir. Shortly after the coronavirus made its way into the city, Laura developed symptoms and was brought to Lincoln Medical Center. She died on April 27, 2020, hours before her husband, who also died of COVID-19. She was 73 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: She overcame everything. Cancer. Two car accidents, including one when she was hit by a semi-truck. The one thing she didn’t survive was a Donald Trump presidency.
pullquoteSource: Marisa Taylor, daughter of Laura Taylor Howell
author: Dean Russell

hardCodedText: One of five siblings, Clifton Howell moved to New York City from Memphis, Tenn., when he was 17 years old. After serving in the United States Air Force from 1952 to 1956, Howell worked in the Garment District, honing his skills as a tailor and dressmaker. In the 1990s, he met Laura Taylor, a health care worker and single mother of three. Howell fell in love, marrying Taylor and adopting her children. “We don’t do ‘step’ in my family,” said his daughter, Marisa Taylor. She described Howell as an “even-keeled” father, never overbearing, although “he would go into protection mode” from time to time. Howell was a jazz aficionado and voracious reader who was “always trying to find something new.” Even into his 80s, he was learning new languages, his family said. In the spring of 2020, he and his wife contracted the novel coronavirus. While the two were roomed separately at Lincoln Medical Center in The Bronx, they both died hours apart on April 27, 2020. He was 85 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: The piece of advice he always gave was that you never stop learning.
pullquoteSource: Marisa Taylor, daughter of Clifton Howell
author: Dean Russell

hardCodedText: After surviving Nazi Germany’s occupation of Hungary, Judith Patocs moved to Chile where she lived a decade before settling in the United States. She lost her brother during the war and arrived in the U.S. with few material possessions. Patocs traveled to Hungary once a year up until her 80s. Her friend, Katie Platt, described Patocs as a “force of nature” who enjoyed taking a shot of vodka on hot, summer days. Patocs lived near the South Street Seaport and loved eating seafood, once paying $100 at a Chinatown store for “all of the abalones she could buy,” Platt said. Patocs died May 15 at the age of 91.
hardCodedPullquote: She made a life on her own and was such a strong woman — she came to the U.S. with so little and couldn't believe this country had given her so much.
pullquoteSource: Katie Plat, Judith Patocs’ friend and neighbor
author: Ashley Rodriguez
additionalNotes: Fleed Hungry during the Nazi invasion and settled in Chile and then the US

hardCodedText: Born in Haiti, Jules Taylor Jr. immigrated to Brooklyn with his mother and brother when he was 6 years old. After the 2010 Haitian earthquake, Taylor organized a drive to fill a shipping container full of vital supplies like food and clothing for survivors. After visiting a Haitian orphanage and seeing the children sit on floors to eat, Taylor organized donations to buy them tables. Taylor worked as a human resources specialist at East Side Settlement and, outside of work, he organized fundraisers for the Rosedale Civic Association, the Tennis Club and the JFK Rotary Club. Taylor was admitted to North Shore University Hospital with COVID-19 on April 5 and died 29 days later, on May 3.
author: Akshay Desai
additionalNotes: Haitian

hardCodedText: When the Twin Towers fell on Sept. 11, Robert Papik, a Long Island native who worked as a caterer, packed up his gear and headed to Ground Zero. For two years he fed first responders and, later, construction crews performing clean-up. The experience left him with chronic respiratory problems but he never regretted it, his girlfriend of four years Maria Oliver said. “He knew he did the right thing.” The oldest of seven siblings and a father of four, Papik was a dedicated family man with a gift for keeping the peace. Papik died April 5 at Stonybrook Hospital on Long Island. He was 52 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: To know him, you’ll love him. He’ll do anything for anybody. He’ll give you his last dollar.
author: Dean Russell
additionalNotes: 9/11 related

hardCodedText: Rosemary Terio grew up in Manhattan, but she lived most of her life In Jackson Heights with her husband, Anthony. Terio was a beloved fixture in the neighborhood, according to family members. Holidays were her finest hours, when she would redecorate the entire house festively. On Halloween, Terio would hand out hundreds of prepared bags of candy, which often meant long lines of trick-or-treaters waiting at the Terios’ door. And on summer days, Rosemary could be found sitting outside her house on a lawn chair with Anthony, waving at passersby. Rosemary died April 5 at St. Francis Hospital on Long Island. She was 82 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: She had an eye for design. She could go into a room and knew how to create a welcoming atmosphere.

hardCodedText: Anthony Terio worked for his entire life at his own trucking company, driving 18-wheelers between Brooklyn, Queens and other navy yards around the tri-state area. His company, A&R Trucking, stood for Anthony and Rosemary, the name of the woman he met at the age of 17, and who he would later marry. Terio was gregarious, and a familiar face to many in Jackson Heights, where he lived, his family said. And he became known for giving people second chances: When he retired in the late 1990’s, Terio took on two recovering addicts to drive his trucks. It was a decision, his family said, that he never regretted. Terio died March 31 at Mount Sinai Hospital in Queens. He was 86 years old.
hardCodedPullquote: Everybody knew Tony when he pulled up. He was everybody’s dad.
author: Luca Powell

hardCodedText: Estelita Solomon was born in San Luis in the Batangas province of the Philippines. She immigrated to the United States in 1972 and worked as a nurse, where she cared deeply about her patients, her family said. She worked for several years at Indian River Memorial Hospital in Vero Beach, Fla., before settling in New York City and continuing her nearly four decades-long career at Wyckoff Heights Medical Center in Brooklyn. She is remembered for her “kind,” “trustworthy” and “fun-loving” nature, her family said. Solomon died April 10 at the age of 72.
hardCodedPullquote: [She] was the sweetest and most personable person ever.
author: Ashley Rodriguez
additionalNotes: Born in Luis, Batangas, Philippines. Died at Long Island Jewish Medical Center. worked at Wyckoff Heights Medical Center for 26 years. Know relatives daughters EmyLou and Cathrine, and grandchildren Leahna, Joleen and Christian.

hardCodedText: Antonio Solomon was born in Cavite province in the Philippines. He enlisted in the U.S. Navy in 1969 and spent more than two decades as a chief petty officer, traveling from the Philippines to California, Scotland and Cuba. After retiring from the Navy, Solomon worked for the U.S. Postal Service for 15 years. Solomon, who is remembered by his family as a “proud patriot,” father and grandfather, died March 26 at the age of 71.
hardCodedPullquote: [He] loved his country probably more than most of us who were born here.

hardCodedText: Antoinetta Florio lived on a farm in central Italy until she was 8. Her parents decided to move to New York City so their children could attend college in the United States. They settled in Astoria, Queens, on the same block as Florio’s future husband, Carlo, and his family. Florio, who died April 7 at the age of 56, was the “go-to” person at Key Food on Ditmars Boulevard, where she worked as a deli manager for more than 35 years, according to her daughter, Carla Florio. In her free time, she loved to cook large portions of authentic Italian food and maintained a garden outside her house that was filled with flowers and vegetables.
hardCodedPullquote: Our family used to joke that anytime you went to her house you should bring sweatpants because she would cook for an army. She gives, gives, gives.
author: Caitlin Antonios

hardCodedText: Mahmooda Shaheen was a maternal figure to many residents in her stretch of Midwood, Brooklyn, known as “Little Pakistan,” said her son, Kashif Hussain. Shaheen, who was born in India and migrated to Pakistan in 1948, moved to Brooklyn after the Persian Gulf War, where she managed her family’s finances, budgeting for rent and saving money for her children to go to college. When the coronavirus reached New York City, Shaheen was mostly concerned about her friends and neighbors. She died April 7 at the age of 71.
hardCodedPullquote: She was one of the biggest philanthropists in immigrant communities.

hardCodedText: Lenore Corcoran was born in the town of Amsterdam, N.Y., to a family of war veterans. Corcoran always wanted to be an educator, leaving Amsterdam to attend Albany State Teachers College. She taught English in schools across New York, including Highland Middle School and the Board of Cooperative Educational Services, where she took a particular interest in students who had disciplinary problems. Corcoran, a skilled tap dancer, was a fan of good films and musicals, and she enjoyed bringing students and family to Broadway. She retired in her 70s. In 2016, Corcoran suffered a stroke and she moved into the Parker Jewish Rehab Center in 2018 after developing dementia. There, the staff nicknamed her “the Belle of the Ball,” for her encyclopedic knowledge of songs and the ease with which she showed it. Parker Jewish was badly hit by COVID-19 in April and, on April 13, she was placed on a floor for COVID patients. She died on April 18.
hardCodedPullquote: I’m thankful for her love and kindness, and even in death, she still gives me good advice.
author: Akshay Desai
additionalNotes: Next of kin: Nancy Guzzetta, daughter. COVID took her ability to speak and effected her brain more than her lungs according to her daughter.

hardCodedText: Maria Hernandez had an uncanny ability to remember birthdays, including the birthdays of all 15 of her children. She immigrated to New York City in the late 1980s from Frenicia, a small farming town in Colombia. Hernandez became the matriarch of a large family in Brooklyn. An avid storyteller, her family says she loved sharing stories from her youth. Hernandez, who was known as “mita” or grandmother, sewed clothes for her family and mended worn-out garments. She died April 16 at the age of 83.

hardCodedText: New York City Fire Marshal John Knox came out of retirement after Sept. 11 to help dig through the rubble at Ground Zero — work that would damage his lungs for the remainder of his life, according to CBS News. Knox, a former U.S. Marine who lived in Rockaway, Queens, joined the FDNY in 1960. He spent decades investigating hundreds of fires and founded the New York City Fire Marshals Benevolent Association. He died March 16 at Mount Sinai South Nassau Medical Center at the age of 84, wearing a gold-embossed fire marshal's ring.

hardCodedText: Lemuel Sison didn’t like to argue. Sison, who was known as “Boyet,” would say that “agree culture” increases GDP: Gross Domestic Peace. Sison died March 31 at the age of 56 and is survived by his wife, Vannie, and his three children.

He studied nursing in the Philippines and dedicated his career to caring for elderly patients at a nursing home in Rego Park, Queens.

hardCodedText: Carmen Silva was born in Puerto Rico and moved to New York City in 1956 to work and provide for her family, working as a traffic cop and foster care parent. After she lost her youngest biological son at 11 years old to a heart attack, Silva channeled her grief into fostering children, her family said. She fostered hundreds of children, and adopted 10 of them, often from birth. One of the adopted children, Choya, has cerebral palsy. Carmen and Choya were close and often went out for coffee and grocery runs. Choya was taken care of by Carmen until she died, on April 8 at the age of 79 at Mount Sinai Hospital in Manhattan, and will now be raised by her siblings.
hardCodedPullquote: She was very caring and wanted the best for all of us.

hardCodedText: Joseph Daniel Volcy came to Brooklyn in 1974 from Haiti, where he was born. He was known as “Boss Joe” by staff at the baking plant where he worked. He later worked as a New York City cab driver. Volcy eventually settled with his wife, Ritha, in Prospect Lefferts Gardens, where he was dubbed the “mayor of the neighborhood” by the local block association, at least partially due to his helpful nature and encyclopedic knowledge of politics, in both the United States and Haiti, his family said. Volcy, who died April 7 at the age of 70, is survived by his wife, six children and seven grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a friend to all and a provider for anyone in need, to a fault at times...It was his superpower.

hardCodedText: Patricia Harriet Jackson was known fondly by many different names over the decades she spent as an HIV/AIDS educator at Montefiore’s Adolescent AIDS Program until her retirement in 2018. “Momma Pat” or “Mama Condom,” as she was affectionately dubbed, dedicated her life to helping people of color and LGBTQ+ youth in her native Bronx in the early 1990s and 2000s. “What she brought to the community, what she brought to the young people, it was invaluable,” said her former coworker, Lissette Marrero. “It’s just such a testament to who she was and how much she cared for people in general.” Born in Harlem Hospital and raised as a military brat, she was a “Bronx girl” to her core, according to her younger brother, Charles Shorter, who described her as a woman of faith who enjoyed traveling and living life to the fullest. Jackson, who suffered from several underlying conditions including lupus and diabetes, died from COVID-19 on April 7, 2020, at Einstein in the Bronx. She is survived by her brother; her son, Damian; and his family, and the “Village,” a close-knit group of friends.
hardCodedPullquote: Pat was extremely giving of herself, very forthcoming, she didn’t pull punches. I think you could probably [call it] tough love. She would meet you right where you were at, but she’d tell you you needed to move.
pullquoteSource: Charles Shorter, Patricia Harriet Jackson’s brother
author: Téa Kvetenadze

hardCodedText: Luis Rivera, a Queens native, grew up attending the Friendship Baptist Church in Jamaica, where he studied the Bible intensely. Years later, he would return to lead the worship service in song and prayer. His devotion, which included waking up at 5 a.m. to pray as well as spending hours composing worship songs, stemmed primarily from a “humble” desire to be a “servant of God,” said his wife, Barbara Rivera. Rivera also worked as a registrar at the Jamaica Hospital, and was often fetching blankets or telling jokes to patients, his family said. Rivera was called “mayor of the hospital” by friends and family and he found time to regularly send flowers to his wife and mother and call his three children and two step-children. Rivera died April 2 at the Jamaica Hospital at the age of 50.
hardCodedPullquote: He couldn’t help but break out into a smile, tell a few jokes, give you a hug if you needed it … He was a big teddy bear.

hardCodedText: Michael Anthony Stevens Sr. was known as “sugar” to his wife, “Uncle Mike'' to his nieces and nephews and the “Dallas Cowboys’ No. 1 fan” to everyone else. He was born and raised in Brooklyn, graduating from Boys and Girls High and SUNY Brockport, where he got a degree in communications. Stevens was also a trustee and usher of First AME Zion Church, where he met his wife, the Rev. Mary T. Lawrence. Stevens was the “life of the party,” according to his sister, Cynthia Morrison, and enjoyed entertaining friends and showing off his culinary skills. He leaves behind two sons, two daughters, eight grandchildren, three sisters and a brother. He died April 5 at Mt. Sinai Hospital at the age of 60.

hardCodedText: Juan “Macho” Rodriguez was passionate about cars, beginning his career at the age of 9 sweeping floors at an auto parts store and working in mechanic shops up until his death. Rodriguez, who died on March 24 at the age of 35, is survived by his mother, three children, 10 siblings, and eight nieces and nephews. “Family was everything to him,” his sister said. “Especially his children. hardCodedText: Thomas Ecker survived the Holocaust after he and his mother used false Dutch identification cards to evade the Nazis; his father was deported to the Auschwitz-Birkenau concentration camp, where he survived. After Ecker was drafted into the Soviet army, he escaped on foot through the Austrian Alps, arriving in Istanbul where he married his childhood friend, Edith. In 1957, the couple immigrated to the United States, settling in Queens where they had three children. Thomas and Edith Ecker — who died of COVID-19 nine days apart — were central figures in their Bayside community, according to their son, Bob Ecker. Thomas Ecker died at home on April 26 at the age of 89.
hardCodedPullquote: My mom and dad had a true love story. They were married for 68 years, and my dad caught COVID while taking care of my mom at her assisted living facility.
author: Rosa Schwartzburg
additionalNotes: Next of Kin: Bob Ecker (707)771-0911

hardCodedText: Rosemary “Rory” Sisco taught Spanish for more than 30 years at the Bellmore-Merrick school system on Long Island. Sisco, who was born in Queens, loved traveling and organized school trips to Spain for her students, her family said. Sisco, who died March 25 at the age of 71 at New York-Presbyterian Queens Hospital, also enjoyed gardening and knitting. She sold handmade hats and scarfs in local stores as “Mariposa Rose” and made miniature clothes for her nieces’ pets.
hardCodedPullquote: She was a kind, friendly and positive woman who will be very much missed.
author: Frank DiFiore

hardCodedText: Anna Sparacino, who lived in Brooklyn, died April 10 at the age of 79 in the Menorah Center for Rehabilitation and Nursing.
hardCodedPullquote: She died just weeks from her 80th birthday.
author: Frank DiFiore

hardCodedText: Fook Sheong Wong enjoyed a game of mahjong whenever he had free time. Emigrating from Hong Kong in the 1960s, Wong, who died on March 25 at age 74 at St. John’s Episcopal Hospital, faced discrimination in his new home and began working at the age of 18. He built a career in restaurant work to provide for his children, Alex and Serena.
hardCodedPullquote: Immigrant father who worked to provide a better life for his two children.
author: Frank DiFiore

hardCodedText: Judy Richheimer was known throughout Chelsea as an advocate for the neighborhood, according to her brother, David Richheimer. She was a liberal who was outspoken on political issues, her brother said, yet she was private about her personal life. She loved dogs and often volunteered to walk her neighbors’ pets. Richheimer, who grew up in Queens, died March 24 at age 70 at Lenox Hill Hospital.
hardCodedPullquote: She was very personable…and very knowledgeable.
author: Frank DiFiore

hardCodedText: Barbara Richardson doted on her children and grandchildren, and lived out her faith in God wherever she went: birthdays, weddings, even at the pharmacy. Richardson, a Brooklyn resident, died on April 20 at Woodhull Hospital Center at the age of 68.
hardCodedPullquote: [Her] voice, laughter, smile and hugs are truly missed daily.
author: Frank DiFiore

hardCodedText: Agustin Salvador was a member of Theatre of the Oppressed NYC, a social justice-oriented performance troupe. After joining the organization last fall as part of the Housing Works Theatre Troupe, Salvador quickly became a beloved member. He performed at the Housing Works bookstore and Susan’s Pace as well as a shelter in the Bronx. In each performance, Salvador delivered authentic emotion, his friends said, and was eager to connect New Yorkers through storytelling. Outside of his involvement with the troupe, Salvador was often seen singing in the streets and playfully puppeteering, his friends said. Salvador died on April 9.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a joyful presence, and fiercely loved by his friends.
author: Molly Wilde
obitSource: Theater of the Oppressed NYC Facebook

hardCodedText: When Anthony Meoli wasn’t helping a religious charity or cheering on the Yankees, the Bronx native worked as a telethon organizer for United Cerebral Palsy. His daughter, Laura, said that her father was especially proud to have helped the group. Meoli, who died April 4 at the age of 62 at his home, is survived by his wife, Pamela, and the couple’s three daughters.
hardCodedPullquote: Bronx native, Lehmanite and loving father who worked to raise money for cerebral palsy support services.

hardCodedText: Marc Goodman moved to New York City when he was 19 years old. He was a New Yorker from then on, his nieces said, cultivating a life full of athletics and the arts (he liked theatre and had a passion for photographing the New York subway). He was a natural conversationalist with a reassuring presence, his family said, qualities that helped him throughout his 20 year career as a real estate broker. Outside of work, he was a meditation mentor and personal trainer. Goodman died March 28 at the age of 67. His nieces, Emily and Alexis, remembered him as an uncle who was personable, whimsical and “driven by the notion of kindness.”
hardCodedPullquote: He was an introvert who could totally fool you. He knew how to bring out things in people, when his attention was on you he made you feel really special.
pullquoteSource: Emily Knower and Alexis Scott, Marc J. Goodman’s nieces
author: Luca Powell
additionalNotes: Submission from Erin Hudson, who wrote the obit.

hardCodedText: Cesar Mauro Sarmiento Lopez was born and raised in Cuenca, Ecuador, and came to the United States when he was in his 20s. Passionate about soccer, he played in several different leagues around Queens, Brooklyn and Manhattan and was known to score memorable goals by his teammates. Lopez valued family, and often told his wife and children that they could do anything, as long as they were together, they said. He was the patriarch of his extended family and would regularly plan trips and family gatherings, including vacations back to Ecuador to visit his parents. Lopez loved to fish, and would welcome company whenever he went for a day at the beach or pier. He died April 8 at Staten Island University Hospital at the age of 58.
hardCodedPullquote: He was such a smart, strong, fearless, creative man.

author: Caroline Leddy

hardCodedText: Michael Scura was an avid learner: he worked in finance for most of his career and attended school at night to earn a Ph.D. in theoretical nuclear physics. He loved everything about opera and classical music: He held season tickets to the Metropolitan Opera and attended performances by the New York Philharmonic Orchestra with his wife, Frances. A committee member of the Wagner Society of New York, Michael helped plan monthly performances and was always up to date on the latest literature to plan the performances around. Frances and Michael met in 1990, after he posted an ad in New York Magazine that said: “lonely Manhattanite ardently seeks woman to share concerts, dinner and literature.” After a year of writing letters to each other, the pair met and attended an opera in San Francisco, where Frances lived. She later moved to live with Michael in New York, and they got married shortly thereafter. Scura died March 28 at Bellevue Hospital at the age of 68.
hardCodedPullquote: He was a genius and a wonderful, loving person. He had an almost spiritual affinity with math, physics and cosmology, he just loved it.
pullquoteSource: Frances Scura, Michael A. Scura’s wife
author: Caroline Leddy
additionalNotes: Next of kin: Frances Scura. He had his Ph.D in Theoretical Nuclear Physics

hardCodedText: Andres Diaz fled Cuba in 1959 in the aftermath of the Cuban Revolution. In Brooklyn, he worked as a dishwasher then a cook, saving up enough money to fund his wife’s journey to the United States a year later. Diaz eventually helped the rest of his family flee Fidel Castor’s regime and resettle in New York City. He became a U.S. citizen and later worked for Canada Dry. Diaz was known for being responsible, trustworthy and hardworking, according to his family. He died April 14 at Richmond University Medical Center in Staten Island at the age of 85.

hardCodedText: Before moving to the United States from China in the late 1960s, Pik Chi Chan had sailed around the world, working as a boatswain on a ship in order to make money and support his family. After deciding life at sea wasn’t for him, Chan moved to the United States and opened a Chinese restaurant with his wife in Harlem in 1973. According to his family, he lived in the kitchen; food was a love language for him. Chan dedicated most of his time to running his restaurant, making sure he would be able to continue to provide for his family and support his children. When he retired in 2004, he sold the restaurant and often spent time playing poker with his friends and spending time with his grandchildren. Chan died June 7 at Flushing Hospital Medical Center at the age of 82.

hardCodedText: Robert J. Wolfson loved to learn about the world, as much as he loved to teach his economics students at Syracuse University, where he taught until he retired in 1996 and moved to Forest Hills in 2002 with his wife, Betty. Wolfson, who died April 4 at the age of 95, loved playing the piano, cooking, being outdoors and talking with people about a broad range of subjects, his family said. Wolfson encouraged his three children to be politically active, supporting organizations like the ACLU, Planned Parenthood and the Southern Poverty Law Center. He was “incredibly warm,” with a charming and outgoing personality that bordered on being too optimistic, said his two daughters, Laura and Anne.
hardCodedPullquote: He was very passionate about social justice. We all remember the first political demonstrations our parents took us to.

hardCodedText: Emelda Rodriguez used to embarrass her daughters by yelling from the window of their apartment when they wandered too far away while playing outside. “Everyone recognized her yell,” said her daughter, Millie. Rodriguez, who died April 20 at the age of 77, was born in Honduras and immigrated to Florida for a few years to work as a housekeeper before moving to New York in 1970, where she took pride in being a home attendant for her Lower East Side clients. In the little time she had when she wasn’t working, Rodriguez loved listening to merengue music and her favorite artists, Julio Iglesias and El Puma, her family said.
hardCodedPullquote: We want her to be remembered as a real person who had real feelings and died too young.

hardCodedText: Lenin “Lenny” Portillo was a sociology major at the City University of New York’s Lehman College in The Bronx. He was weeks away from graduation and planned on becoming a social studies teacher at a charter school, his family said. Portillo was passionate about education and came from a long line of educators. He was the “glue” of his Honduran-American family, said his cousin, Wendy Portillo-Speer, and was always there for his loved ones, both friends and family. Portillo-Speer said her cousin helped her stay on track in school during a rebellious teenage period and even accompanied her to her 8th grade prom. He enjoyed karaoke, traveling, trying out new food and was known for his contagious laugh and heart of gold, Portillo-Speer said. Portillo died on April 14, 2020, at Lincoln Medical Center at the age of 37. He was posthumously awarded a bachelor’s degree from Lehman College.

hardCodedText: David Perez was born and raised in the Bronx. A die-hard Yankees fan, Perez was a “true pinstripe,” according to his friend, David Caba. Perez worked as an investigator for the New York City Department of Corrections, investigating abuses of force cases inside New York City prisons from the department’s office in Queens. hardCodedText: Antonia Reynoso could often be found in her garden in the Bronx. After she died on April 17, the spring flowers she planted “blossomed beautifully,” said her daughter, Miralba. Reynoso, who died at the age of 81, was a devoted grandmother and great-grandmother. At the start of each day, Reynoso made her usual rounds, calling each of her five children to say good morning and see that they arrived at work safely. She was a constant and steady presence in her family members' lives, they said, reminding them to eat healthy and not to worry so much.

hardCodedText: Joseph “Joe” Aloe was born the youngest of 10 children in Carbondale, Pennsylvania, but lived in New York City for more than 50 years near Union Square, where he worked as a hair stylist for the Gerard Bollei Salon. Aloe and his partner, Kasey, a makeup artist, never had children but made every stranger in New York City — whether neighbors or restaurant owners — feel like family, friends said. Aloe, a cancer survivor who died April 17 at the age of 82 at Beth Israel Medical Center, enjoyed red wine, Frank Sinatra and fought for acceptance in the LGBTQIA+ community.
hardCodedPullquote: A truly special New Yorker who embodied the very best of what this city had to offer. I've never had a neighbor who became a friend in New York, until there was Joe.

Benoit was particularly social and active in her Jackson Heights, Queens, community, her family said. Originally from Puerto Rico, she would make traditional pernil and Coquito for holiday parties. She treasured going to Rockaway Beach, especially with her granddaughter. A past cancer survivor, Benoit died April 5 at the age of 74 at Montefiore Medical Center.

hardCodedText: Every Sunday, Luis A. Figueroa would make tuna salad while dancing along to the salsa music blasting on the radio at his home in Flushing, Queens. It was his routine, said the eldest of his four sons. On work days, Figueroa commuted to Sutton Terrace where he worked for more than 20 years as a repairman and porter. Figueroa loved to spend his lunch breaks joking around or talking about soccer, his family said, and he would bring traditional Peruvian dishes like ceviche to the building’s Christmas party. He seemed to be always smiling and care-free, said his family and Sutton Terrace residents. One year before his death, Figueroa achieved his lifetime goal of becoming a U.S. citizen after the third try.
hardCodedPullquote: He never worried about anything. He never looked at problems as being problems; he was always happy, he was a joker. He always put a smile on our face. In our house, it’s a funeral now. The sunlight is gone, he was the sun.

hardCodedText: Edith Ecker was born in Budapest, Hungary, and fled the Nazis’ persecution of the country’s Jewish population when she was 7 years old. Ecker was a linguist — she spoke five languages, including English — and earned a bachelor’s and master’s degree in linguistics from Queens College. hardCodedText: Born in Fajardo, Puerto Rico, Miguel Angel Calderon came to New York City as a teenager and settled in East Harlem with his mother. Calderon enlisted in the Army at 22, fighting with the 65th infantry — a Puerto Rican regiment also known as “The Borinqueneers” — in the Korean War. Calderon, who died on April 6 at the age of 90 in Mary Manning Walsh Nursing Home, was set to be presented this year with the Congressional Gold Medal for his military service. Washington, who died May 6 at a hospital in The Bronx at the age of 40, was generous and had a passion for social justice, colleagues said.

hardCodedText: Lorraine Joy Bagwell seemed to know every detail about every hotel, restaurant and tourist attraction in the city in her job for Qantas Airways. Bagwell, who died April 13 at the age of 71 at Elmhurst Hospital, was devoted to her job, ensuring guests enjoyed their time in New York, her family said. But she also never forgot a birthday, doted over her mother, sister and dog, Jojo, and rarely missed Sunday Mass. Her motto: “Always be kind, no matter what.”
hardCodedPullquote: She went out of her way to make everyone she came into contact with feel special.
pullquoteSource: Lorraine Joy Bagwell‘s niece, Cathy Kelleher
author: Caitlin Antonios

hardCodedText: Carmen Nerida Muniz came to New York City from Puerto Rico in 1949, settling in Washington Heights. After working for a few years as a seamstress, she met her husband, Pedro, and became a homemaker, raising three daughters. Later, she worked as a bank teller, and, in 2007, she began to show signs of Alzheimer’s. Although she was a New Yorker, she died at age 89 in a retirement home in Metairie, Louisiana on April 12, four days after her husband “probably, we think, to join him,” said her granddaughter, Amanda Calderon.
hardCodedPullquote: She stoically took on some of the most difficult times in her life with force and determination. … I credit her for my strength.
pullquoteSource: Sonia Calderon, daughter of Carmen Nerida Muniz
author: Dean Russell
streetAddress: Metairie Health Care Center, Metairie, LA
additionalNotes: Although she died in Louisiana, her family (living in NYC) argue that she was a New Yorker, spending the majority of her life here.

hardCodedText: Pedro Muniz met his wife, Nereida, at a party one week after he moved to Washington Heights from Puerto Rico in 1952. Starting as a busboy, he worked his way up, eventually managing the restaurant in the Statler Hilton, now the Hotel Pennsylvania, across from Madison Square Garden. Later he bought a diner, which he ran while raising three daughters. He loved to cook, his family said, especially while listening to “boleros” love songs on Saturday and Sunday mornings. Although he was a New Yorker, he died at age 88 on April 8 in a retirement home in Metairie, Louisiana. His wife, who had Alzheimer’s disease, died four days later.
hardCodedPullquote: He was bright, ambitious and hardworking — a dreamer who was able to achieve some of his dreams until my mother was struck with Alzheimer’s.
pullquoteSource: Sonia Calderon, daughter of Pedro Muniz

hardCodedText: Melody Reed was a photographer who taught digital photography and editing at New York City College of Technology and the Pratt Institute. She captured the city she loved with a sensitive eye — from sunsets captured on her terrace to reflections from skyscrapers. Reed shared her work on Instagram under the name @enchanted_camera. She came from a family of artists: her mother was an actress, her sister, Suzanne, was a folk singer and like her brother and their father were both jewelers. Reed was gentle, loving and sweet, according to her cousin, Laurence Gartel. She was a fixture in Lincoln Square and was often seen out walking her dog, Nico, and shooting portraits. After Reed died May 15 at the age of 78, Gartel said neighbors worried and asked him: “Who is walking Nico?”
hardCodedPullquote: I could describe her as soft, loving, sweet. You don't find people like that anymore, really like her.
author: Ashley Rodriguez
additionalNotes: Died at Mt. Sinai Hospital

hardCodedText: Phyllis Thompson was born in a small town in Virginia and moved to New York City in 1970 to work as a secretary at Bankers Trust, which later became Deutsche Bank, until she retired in 2009. Thompson enjoyed baking Christmas cookies for her colleagues each year, playing Sudoku and attending theater shows and concerts. She was “humbly charitable,” “mathematical,” “smart” and dedicated to her work, her family said. Thompson died on April 5 at the age of 77 at Mount Sinai Morningside.
hardCodedPullquote: She was 13 years older than me, so she was like my second mother.

Christopher was a 29-year member of the NYPD. He worked in the Intelligence Bureau’s Operations and Analysis Section as a first-grade detective. According to the union, he worked in Staten Island, lower Manhattan and the Narcotics Division. His death wasn't linked to COVID-19 until almost a month after he died.

hardCodedText: Charles Burrows grew up in Flatbush, Brooklyn, riding bikes and collecting comic books, a hobby he never quit. Burrows accumulated more than 5,000 comics in his lifetime and was a quiet, patient man, his family said. Besides comics and video games, he dedicated his life to being the caretaker for his parents and sister, Elaine, who has autism. Burrows contracted coronavirus while recovering from a stroke, his family said, and died April 20 at the age of 54 at St. John’s Episcopal Hospital in Far Rockaway, Queens.

hardCodedText: Beatrice Granberg grew up in South Beach, Staten Island, and worked for the NYPD, then later for Standard and Poor’s in downtown Manhattan, according to an obituary in Staten Island Advance. She was blocks away from the Twin Towers on Sept. 11, 2001. Granberg retired in 2002 and volunteered and supported numerous military and civilian charities. She was the matriarch of her family and hosted family gatherings during the holidays. Granberg enjoyed traveling, especially to Sicily, Italy. In February 2020, Granberg was diagnosed with lymphoma, which her family attributes to toxins she was exposed to while working near Ground Zero. She was undergoing chemotherapy last year when she caught the coronavirus. Granberg died May 9, 2020, at the age of 79.
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: For 2 ½ years after Sept. 11, 2001, Arthur Lacker worked to clean up the debris from Ground Zero. In his downtime, he loved socializing with friends and family, dancing, going to the beach, listening to music and gardening. Lacker also loved spending time at the beach. He battled lung cancer related to his work in Ground Zero (he was in remission when he died) and suffered from other respiratory conditions. He was diagnosed with COVID-19 and died April 2 at the age of 73 at NYU Winthrop Hospital. He is survived by his wife Robin Lacker; his two children, Jared and Tara; and his 13-year-old granddaughter, Olivia.
hardCodedPullquote: He loved disco and The Doo Wops. He also loved gardening, he had a good green thumb. He planted trees, flowers, and took care of it. He just loved that.
author: Beatriz Muylaert
additionalNotes: Beatriz interviewed his wife, Robin Lacker, for the covid + 9/11 story. Notes on drive.

hardCodedText: Jose A. Hernandez Jr. was a dedicated Mets fan who lived in the Soundview section of The Bronx with his roommates. Born with a learning disability, Hernandez was a “kind man,” his family said, who worked a variety of jobs including the concessions at the old Shea Stadium and as a courier. Hernandez died April 5 at the age of 56.

hardCodedText: Mark Pompa worked as a partner and project manager for a scaffolding company in New York City. With his large frame and tattooed arms, he often came off as “the mean Italian guy, but he was really a big teddy bear,” said his wife, Lisa Cilione. Pompa was a family man, his wife said, who enjoyed spending time with his five children: Alexa, Crysta, Mark, Nicolette and Stefani. If the kids were home for the summer,” Cilione said, “we always stayed home with them, so we could be together as a family.” A die-hard Yankees fan, Pompa would take his family to games at Yankee Stadium whenever he could. He also regularly took his children out to eat, indulging in icees at Ralph’s. When Stefani Wren, Lisa’s daughter who Pompa helped raise, broke her arm and needed a cast, Pompa would put on his bathing suit and help her wash her hair in the shower. He would go by the name, “Francois the hairdresser.” He also regularly pressed his daughters’ clothes, drove them to school and picked them up when the day was over. While Pompa would occasionally dance along to trendy pop songs, there was no musician he loved more than Frank Sinatra. His favorite songs were “My Way” and “The Way You Look Tonight,” which he danced to with his daughter, Nicolette, at her first communion. Mark Pompa died in Richmond County Hospital on April 20, 2020, at the age of 53.
hardCodedPullquote: He never wanted to be without his family.
author: Zosia Czerwinski

Rahman supervised a team of fire inspectors auditing high-risk buildings throughout the city, according to the FDNY Foundation. hardCodedText: In the wake of the Sept. 11 attacks, Michael Field spent nine months at Ground Zero working rescue and recovery. Field, a native of Valley Stream, N.Y., was an emergency medical technician for more than 30 years. Since 2007, he served as a warden on the Valley Stream Fire Department’s council. Engelson, who died April 21 at Lenox Hill Hospital at the age of 89, traveled the world for work, meeting with foregin dignitaries and heads of state. Cardona, who died April 24 at New York Presbyterian Queens Hospital at the age of 62, became an entrepreneur, opening two businesses in Queens. She was the “life of the party,” and a mother, sister and grandmother to four who was “always willing to give to people who were in need.”

hardCodedText: Gianmarco Bertolotti worked as a mason at Lenox Hill Hospital in Manhattan. He loved working with his hands and took pride in his role as a frontline worker, according to his sister, Monique Bertolotti. Bertolotti lived in Astoria, in an apartment he renovated himself with the help of friends and family. Outside of his job, he enjoyed exploring his neighborhood and trying new recipes. He especially loved playing board games and his father’s cooking. Bertolotti was an avid reader, his sister said, and loved attending concerts and listening to all kinds of music. Monique fondly recalled a Christmas Eve gathering with their large Italian family when Bertolotti got everyone, including his 90-year-old grandmother, to get up and dance with him across the kitchen. “He always made the holidays a little bit brighter,” she said. “I’ll forever cherish my memories of us cooking and laughing together.” Bertolotti died April 22, 2020, at Mount Sinai Hospital at the age of 42.
hardCodedPullquote: His impact was profound and I'm devastated knowing that such a sweet soul was truly meant for so much more.

hardCodedText: Janine Soleil, a Brooklyn native, spent most of her life in California. She recently returned to New York City to be closer to her son. Soleil, a formally-trained dancer who studied at Julliard School and UCLA, moved to Northern California to join the counter-cultural revolution of the 1960s, living in Haight Ashbury, and participated in the “Summer of Love.” She worked as a teacher while volunteering for the LA Women’s Center and later worked as a marriage and family therapist. Soleil contracted the coronavirus at a memory-care facility in Kew Gardens, Queens, and died at the age of 75 at a hospice on Long Island.

hardCodedText: In 1957, 7-year-old John Patrick Whyte moved from Manchester, England, to New York City with his family where he would spend the rest of his life. Whyte’s family owned a candy shop in Brooklyn, which later relocated to Staten Island. In 1983, after several years with the U.S. Postal Service, Whyte joined the New York City Fire Department and served for decades. A year after responding to the attack of Sept. 11, he retired with post-traumatic stress and debris-related asthma. Whyte and his wife, Patrcia, were married for nearly 40 years. He was a father and grandfather as well as a gifted singer and guitar player with an appreciation for rock and Irish folk music, his family said. Whyte died May 12 at Richmond University Medical Center in Staten Island at the age of 69.

hardCodedText: Antonio Suarez was born in 1957 in the town of La Vega in the Dominican Republic. His father died when he was 27, which resulted in him sticking close to his remaining family. He immigrated to the United States in the 1990s. Suarez enjoyed bachata music, listening to singers such as Marcus Antonio Solis and Yoskar Sarante. He also followed news about baseball and the Dominican Republic. Christmas was a special time for Suarez and his family; In 2019, he gathered with his family in Connecticut, swapping gifts with his daughter and giving her a bottle of perfume. Suarez worked for 20 years as a truck delivery driver, his family said, which allowed him to support his family in the U.S. and the Dominican Republic. He was two years away from retirement, and had planned to spend it in the Dominican Republic. Suarez died April 15, 2020, at the Long Island Jewish Medical Center. He was 63.

hardCodedText: Toward the end of her life, as Karen Garvin was confined to her bed with COVID-19, “she was asking us if we were eating and taking care of ourselves,” said her grandson, Jelani Hipps. Garvin was raised in Baltimore and moved to Brooklyn when she was 23 years old. There, and later in the Bronx, she raised two children. Outside the home, everyone called her, “Ms. Karen” and “Ms. G,” as a sign of respect, said her colleague, Rachel Sherrow. As the coordinator for City Meals on Wheels at Mid-Bronx Senior Council, Garvin oversaw regular food delivery to hundreds of residents in the Bronx, working long hours, six days a week and every Thanksgiving and other holidays. She gave “people opportunities who would not normally have opportunities, ex-cons and former drug addicts,” Hipps said. Garvin, who was described as a free spirit and avid reader by her family, died on April 10 at NewYork-Presbyterian Lawrence Hospital in Bronxville after a weekslong battle with the virus. She was 63.

hardCodedText: When Edward Antonio walked into a room, people noticed. Not only because he was 6-foot-1 but because of his smile. Antonio had a drive to help others. After Hurricane Sandy in 2012, Ed and his wife, Paula, stayed in their home in the Rockaways to help feed clean-up workers and watch the homes of their neighbors who had been forced to flee — all while enduring their own power outage. Antonio was resourceful and never wanted anything to go to waste, according to his son, E.J. Antonio. He repaired abandoned bicycles and donated them to local children, friends and strangers. Antonio “could establish relationships with strangers that felt as though they had lasted a lifetime,” E.J. said. “He had a way of connecting with others that made them feel seen and acknowledged.” Antonio also was naturally funny and was known for his “joke of the day.” His friends would send him jokes, simply because they wanted to hear him tell them with his special flair. Around the holidays, Antonio dressed up as Santa and visited schools and nursing homes in Brooklyn. It was his favorite way to give back, said his son, as he could do so anonymously. Antonio died April 14, 2020, at the age of 79 at his home in the Rockaways.
hardCodedPullquote: He felt an ownership to take care of people, always.
author: Zosia Czerwinski

hardCodedText: Romeo Agtarap arrived in New York City in 1983. A trained nurse from the Philippines, he was recruited to work at Peninsula Hospital in Far Rockaway. Agtarap worked for decades in New York City hospitals, eventually landing a nurse coordinator position at NewYork-Presbyterian/Columbia University Irving Medical, where he ran the hospital’s emergency department, said his wife, Joy Agtarap. In 2019, Agtarap stepped down from his managerial role to work as a part-time nurse, in preparation for retirement. But when COVID-19 arrived in New York City, he resumed many of his responsibilities. Agtarap died April 24, 2020, at the age of 63. After his death, Columbia Presbyterian mounted a plaque in his honor, describing him as a hero who spent his life mentoring young nurses and teaching others how to heal "through kindness."

hardCodedText: Jose L. Gonzalez, known as “Louie” by his friends and family, was born in Puerto Rico and came to New York City with his parents as a young child. After attending high school in The Bronx, Gonzalez enlisted in the U.S. Marines and deployed for a two-year tour in Vietnam. During his deployment he and Gladys Gonzalez, began a pen pal correspondence after an ad was posted in El Diario La Prensa. The Gonzalezs were married for 50 years. A lifelong resident of The Bronx, Gonzalez worked as an auto mechanic and school bus driver after his deployment. Gladys Gonzalez described her husband as a “big kind-hearted person,” armed with a joke and a smile for strangers and friends alike. Gonzalez died on April 9, 2020, from COVID-19 after a brief hospitalization at the James J. Peters VA Medical Center in The Bronx. He is survived by his wife; three sons, Jose Jr., David and Nick; one daughter, Vanessa, three daughters-in-law and six grandchildren.

hardCodedText: Every Friday, Ruth Corbett’s home was bustling. She would routinely cook and bake mac n’ cheese, peach cobbler and apple spice cake. Her daughter, Charlene Thomas, said she would feed her guests both “physically and spiritually.” After decades of working as an executive secretary for corporations, such as the United Nations Association, at the age of 60, Corbett achieved her lifelong dream and graduated with a bachelor’s degree followed by a master’s degree in Christian counseling at the age of 63. From there, she became a counselor at the Head Start Program in Brooklyn and eventually started a counseling ministry at Emmanuel Baptist Church. After Corbett died April 7 at the age of 76 at Kings County Hospital, more than 1,000 people tried to watch her funeral service. The livestream ended up crashing.
hardCodedPullquote: She never lived in regret, she never lived in, “I wish I could have.” She was, “I’m going to do it,” and she did it. It was amazing

hardCodedText: Idris Bey, an emergency medical technician, was on the scene when the Twin Towers collapsed on Sept. 11. Although his ambulance was nearly destroyed during the attack, Bey survived and was awarded a medal by the Fire Department of New York. Bey, a Queens resident, started his career with the FDNY at Station 35 in Williamsburg. After Sept. 11, he worked as an instructor at the EMS training academy. Over the course of two decades, Bey trained thousands of EMTs and firefighters in emergency medical care. Bey died April 22 at the age of 60, according to the FDNY. He is survived by four children.
hardCodedPullquote: During his extraordinary career, EMT Bey responded to countless calls for help in Brooklyn, and then took his experience and dedication to our academy, where he was responsible for the lifesaving training received by thousands of FDNY members. Every New Yorker owes him a debt of gratitude.
