hardCodedText: Andreas Koutsoudakis owned Tribeca’s Kitchen and worked in Manhattan’s restaurant industry for more than 30 years. On Sept. 11, 2001, Koutsoudakis was working at Gee Whiz Diner, a restaurant he co-owned, when the Twin Towers collapsed, according to an open letter written by his son in the Tribeca Citizen. Koutsoudakis quickly turned his restaurant over to FDNY workers, who used it as an emergency rescue site for their response efforts at Ground Zero. Koutsoudakis returned home that day covered in soot from the collapsing tower, still in shock. Koutsoudakis died March 27, 2020, at a hospital on Staten Island at the age of 59, according to the Tribeca Trib.
author: Scooty Nickerson

hardCodedText: A native South Carolinian, Leroy Hammett ran a barber’s shop from his apartment in the south Bronx, eventually moving it to a nearby storefront named Leroy’s Unisex. Every summer, he would host a back-to-school block party with DJ and grill, offering free haircuts to children. Hammett believed in the power of prayer and community and thought that everyone should have a second chance, his family said. He liked to mingle, and invited people to attend Little Widow's Mite Baptist Church, where he served as a deacon. Hammett also volunteered with his son, LeShawn Hammett, to coach the Penn State Wilkes-Barre basketball team, leading them to a championship in March 2019. He was a proud coach, his family said, as he talked about his players and showed off his championship ring. Hammett was caring and honest — at times, too much so, said his grandson, Chris Lewis. Lewis, who was raised by Hammett, recalls watching “The Lion King” with his grandfather years ago. After seeing Simba’s father, Mufasa, dying, Lewis turned to Hammett and asked if, one day, if he was going to die. “I’m not a lion,” he said. “No one lives forever, but I’m going to be here forever.” Hammett died March 30, 2020, at Lincoln Medical Center at the age of 71.
hardCodedPullquote: My dad was one of those guys that if he could find a way to make it work for you, he would.
author: Justin Yip

hardCodedText: Cedric Dixon grew up in the Bronx and always wanted to be a cop. He joined the NYPD in 1997 at the age of 25 and served for 23 years, assigned to the 32nd Precinct in Harlem. Dixon worked at Ground Zero in the aftermath of the 9/11 attacks, offering help to whoever needed it, said Vilma Rosario, a former NYPD colleague. Dixon died on March 28, 2020, at the age of 48. He was the first known NYPD detective to die of COVID-19. Shortly after his death, Gov. Andrew Cuomo tweeted: “I’m heartbroken that New York lost Detective Cedric Dixon… Our first responders are risking their lives every day to protect the people of this state. hardCodedText: Richard Johnson spent more than 30 years working in the entertainment industry, beginning as a parking production assistant and eventually rising to become a supervisor. He worked on more than 100 projects in film, television and commercials and, in addition to working on sets, Johnson was cast as one of the lead characters in the low-budget film “Crackdown Big City Blues” in 1987. A talented drummer, he was nicknamed “Fast Feets” and played the drums every Sunday for the Greater Springfield Community Church in Jamaica, Queens. He was self-taught and played in several types of bands, including punk rock, funk and blues. Johnson died March 27 at Queens Center Hospital at the age of 59.

hardCodedText: Harold John Solomon Jr., was a native Staten Islander. He and his wife, Ruth, bought and moved into her parents’ house when they got married 55 years ago. In that house, they raised their four children, and Hal instilled in his kids a sense of fairness, matching whatever they could save to buy their first cars, his family said. Yet his plan fell away when his granddaughters got their driver’s licenses, and he bought them new cars straightaway. After spending a few years in the U.S. Army out of high school, Hal spent much of his career as an MTA bus driver. The job didn't fit his temperament, as he generally had little patience and was decidedly “not a people person,” his family said. But he had other hobbies: Hal was an enthusiastic regular in the local baseball world, managing three or four teams at a time, and gave every kid “a fair shake.” Despite being frequently in and out of the hospital in the last few years of his life, he always worried more about his wife’s health than his own, his family said. He died at Richmond University Medical Center on April 8, 2020, at the age of 80.
hardCodedPullquote: They were very, very content with the life they had — their home, their family. And that’s all they wanted, and that’s all they needed.
pullquoteSource: Laura Reuter, Harold John Solomon Jr.’s daughter

hardCodedText: Albert “Al” Petrocelli Sr. met his wife, Ginger, when they were teenagers frequenting Brooklyn ice cream parlors like Herman’s and The Sweet Shop. They married in 1967 at the Brooklyn Chancery. A week later, Petrocelli was deployed to Vietnam with the U.S. Army, according to the Staten Island Advance. Petrocelli joined the New York City Fire Department after the war, rising to the rank of Battalion Chief of Staten Island. One of his sons would follow his footsteps into the FDNY and on Sept. 11, the two raced together to Ground Zero to search for Petrocelli’s other son, a commodities broker who died at the World Trade Center that day. Petrocelli retired from the FDNY and died April 1 at the age of 73.
hardCodedPullquote: He led by example.

hardCodedText: Shirley Ann Miller dedicated her life to children: not just her own three but the countless others she interacted with during her 27 years working as a school crossing guard. Born in a small town in Alabama, she moved to New York at 17 and lived in Harlem, where she served as a deaconess at Mount Neboh Baptist Church for almost four decades. Miller’s youngest son, Frederick, remembered her as a strict but loving mother and a “people person” who enjoyed gospel music and shopping for her grandchildren. She died at Saint Luke's Hospital at the age of 70 on March 24 — one week before the birth of Frederick’s son, Leon. Miller is survived by two of her three children, seven grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.
hardCodedPullquote: Kids and education was one of the biggest things in her life, making sure her kids, her grandkids got education, went to school, and she was all about love and family.

hardCodedText: Kenneth “Kenny” Henderson was called “Mr. Dependable” by his children, for his penchant of regularly stopping by their homes in Massachusetts to lend a hand, whether it was trimming hedges, painting, planting or fixing a broken door. Henderson also had a tendency to stop by unannounced to family functions and was affectionately known for his colorful flair. “My wife and I are on the altar and out of the corner of my eye I see this pink flash … as soon as I saw it I knew who it was,” said his son, Eric Smalls. Henderson, who worked on the Board of Elections, died April 7 at BronxCare Hospital at the age of 68.

hardCodedText: Indarjit Maraj was born in Trinidad and Tobago and immigrated to the U.S. in his 20s. He met Lilian, his wife of 27 years, in Coney Island. She was from El Salvador and spoke very little English. He didn’t speak Spanish. But they made it work. A train operator with the Metropolitan Transportation Authority for 27 years, Maraj worked long hours, serving as a conductor for the E, R and F lines. Maraj knew everyone on his block in Richmond Hill, Queens where he lived for over 30 years. An avid swimmer, Maraj participated in a “polar bear plunge” in February. During the summer months, he often swam in the ocean at Long Beach with his daughter, Savina, where his family plans to build a bench in his honor. He spent some of his last moments splitting a pizza with his son using money they won at a casino. Maraj died April 29 at the age of 73. He is survived by Lillian and their three children.
hardCodedPullquote: He was kind-hearted, quiet, full of life and always wanted to take care of everyone.
